{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JhJidYz49g2S3ee8JPxAGN","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# HYPOTHESIS: Multi-Objective Constrained CMA-ES with ITL Penalty\n     2→\n     3→**Round:** 4\n     4→**Idea:** 1 — Constrained CMA-ES\n     5→**Date:** 2026-03-02\n     6→**Status:** Pending\n     7→\n     8→## Context and Prior Findings\n     9→\n    10→Round 3's CMA-ES (Idea 3 H1) achieved 15.1% mean E2E with 4/10 experiments below 10% — the best E2E result in the research program. However, it sacrificed ITL accuracy: 87.4% mean ITL (was 9.5% in the trace replay baseline). The root cause is the unconstrained single-objective formulation — CMA-ES inflated `output_token_processing_time_us` to implausible values (e.g., 7B: 0 → 1,899μs) as a proxy for missing simulation dynamics.\n    11→\n    12→This idea adds three modifications to the R3 CMA-ES approach:\n    13→1. **ITL penalty term** in the objective function\n    14→2. **Parameter bounds** constraining physically implausible values\n    15→3. **Integrated TTFT corrections** (from R3 H3) applied during optimization rather than post-hoc\n    16→\n    17→### Related Work\n    18→\n    19→- Deb et al., 2002 — NSGA-II for multi-objective evolutionary optimization\n    20→- Igel et al., 2007 — MO-CMA-ES for multi-objective optimization with CMA-ES\n    21→- R3 Idea 3 — unconstrained CMA-ES achieving 15.1% E2E / 87.4% ITL\n    22→\n    23→## Sub-Hypotheses\n    24→\n    25→### H1: Constrained CMA-ES with ITL Penalty → Joint E2E + ITL\n    26→\n    27→**Claim:** A penalty-augmented CMA-ES objective (`objective = 0.5*e2e + 0.5*itl + penalty`) with constrained parameter bounds achieves **mean E2E < 15% AND mean ITL < 25%** simultaneously across 10 experiments.\n    28→\n    29→**Refutation criteria:** Mean E2E > 18% (worse than R3 by >3pp) OR mean ITL > 30%.\n    30→\n    31→**Method:**\n    32→1. Start from R3's optimized artifacts as initial CMA-ES population\n    33→2. Add parameter bounds: `output_token_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 500]`, `scheduling_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 2000]`, `step_overhead_us ∈ [model_baseline × 0.8, model_baseline × 3.0]`\n    34→3. Dual-metric objective: `f(x) = 0.5 * mean_e2e_error + 0.5 * mean_itl_error + 10.0 * max(0, mean_itl_error - 0.20)`\n    35→4. Apply TTFT additive corrections (per-model, from R3 H3) inside the objective evaluation loop\n    36→5. Run per-model optimization with CMA-ES (σ₀ = 0.1, ~100 evaluations per model)\n    37→6. Run with three α values (0.7, 0.5, 0.3 on the E2E weight) to explore the Pareto frontier\n    38→\n    39→**Data split:** No training/test split for CMA-ES — it optimizes against BLIS E2E on all 10 experiments simultaneously. Generalization tested via LOMO/LOWO.\n    40→\n    41→### H2: Pareto Sweep Identifies Knee Point\n    42→\n    43→**Claim:** Running CMA-ES with different E2E/ITL weight ratios produces a Pareto frontier where at least one configuration achieves **E2E < 12% AND ITL < 20%** — a result that R3's single-objective could not achieve.\n    44→\n    45→**Refutation criteria:** No Pareto point achieves both E2E < 15% and ITL < 25%.\n    46→\n    47→**Method:**\n    48→1. Run H1 with α ∈ {0.7, 0.5, 0.3} (weighting E2E vs ITL)\n    49→2. Collect per-experiment E2E and ITL errors for each α\n    50→3. Plot Pareto frontier: E2E vs ITL\n    51→4. Select knee point (closest to the origin) as the recommended configuration\n    52→\n    53→### H3: LOMO Generalization (Cross-Model Artifact Transfer)\n    54→\n    55→**Claim:** Constrained CMA-ES artifacts transfer across models with **mean best-donor E2E < 20%** (vs R3's 14.8% with unconstrained CMA-ES). Constraining the parameter space should maintain cross-model transferability while improving ITL.\n    56→\n    57→**Refutation criteria:** Mean best-donor E2E > 30% (2× worse than R3 LOMO).\n    58→\n    59→**Method:**\n    60→1. For each model group, apply the CMA-ES-optimized artifacts from other models\n    61→2. Evaluate BLIS E2E and ITL per experiment\n    62→3. Build cross-model transfer matrix (same as R3 H5)\n    63→4. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_model_out()` for data splitting\n    64→\n    65→### H4: LOWO Generalization (Cross-Workload Stability)\n    66→\n    67→**Claim:** Constrained CMA-ES artifacts show per-model workload variance **≤ 20pp** (range across workloads) for dense models, with **mean E2E within 2× of aggregate** for all 10 experiments.\n    68→\n    69→**Refutation criteria:** More than 2/10 experiments exceed 2× aggregate E2E error.\n    70→\n    71→**Method:**\n    72→1. Evaluate per-experiment E2E/ITL from H1's best configuration\n    73→2. Group by model, compute per-workload breakdown\n    74→3. Measure range (max-min) per model\n    75→4. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_workload_out()` for data splitting\n    76→\n    77→## Execution Plan\n    78→\n    79→1. H1 first — constrained CMA-ES per model with dual objective\n    80→2. H2 — Pareto sweep (runs H1 with different α values)\n    81→3. H3 — LOMO using H1's best artifacts\n    82→4. H4 — LOWO from H1's results\n    83→\n    84→## Short-Circuit Criteria\n    85→\n    86→If H1 produces mean E2E > 25% (significantly worse than R3's 15.1%), the constrained approach is harming more than helping — abort remaining hypotheses and document root cause.\n    87→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"ebb1c4f8-2d3c-4749-a18d-bc8e7ee88f4b","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/hypotheses/h-stepml/round4/idea-1-constrained-cmaes/HYPOTHESIS.md","content":"# HYPOTHESIS: Multi-Objective Constrained CMA-ES with ITL Penalty\n\n**Round:** 4\n**Idea:** 1 — Constrained CMA-ES\n**Date:** 2026-03-02\n**Status:** Pending\n\n## Context and Prior Findings\n\nRound 3's CMA-ES (Idea 3 H1) achieved 15.1% mean E2E with 4/10 experiments below 10% — the best E2E result in the research program. However, it sacrificed ITL accuracy: 87.4% mean ITL (was 9.5% in the trace replay baseline). The root cause is the unconstrained single-objective formulation — CMA-ES inflated `output_token_processing_time_us` to implausible values (e.g., 7B: 0 → 1,899μs) as a proxy for missing simulation dynamics.\n\nThis idea adds three modifications to the R3 CMA-ES approach:\n1. **ITL penalty term** in the objective function\n2. **Parameter bounds** constraining physically implausible values\n3. **Integrated TTFT corrections** (from R3 H3) applied during optimization rather than post-hoc\n\n### Related Work\n\n- Deb et al., 2002 — NSGA-II for multi-objective evolutionary optimization\n- Igel et al., 2007 — MO-CMA-ES for multi-objective optimization with CMA-ES\n- R3 Idea 3 — unconstrained CMA-ES achieving 15.1% E2E / 87.4% ITL\n\n## Sub-Hypotheses\n\n### H1: Constrained CMA-ES with ITL Penalty → Joint E2E + ITL\n\n**Claim:** A penalty-augmented CMA-ES objective (`objective = 0.5*e2e + 0.5*itl + penalty`) with constrained parameter bounds achieves **mean E2E < 15% AND mean ITL < 25%** simultaneously across 10 experiments.\n\n**Refutation criteria:** Mean E2E > 18% (worse than R3 by >3pp) OR mean ITL > 30%.\n\n**Method:**\n1. Start from R3's optimized artifacts as initial CMA-ES population\n2. Add parameter bounds: `output_token_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 500]`, `scheduling_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 2000]`, `step_overhead_us ∈ [model_baseline × 0.8, model_baseline × 3.0]`\n3. Dual-metric objective: `f(x) = 0.5 * mean_e2e_error + 0.5 * mean_itl_error + 10.0 * max(0, mean_itl_error - 0.20)`\n4. Apply TTFT additive corrections (per-model, from R3 H3) inside the objective evaluation loop\n5. Run per-model optimization with CMA-ES (σ₀ = 0.1, ~100 evaluations per model)\n6. Run with three α values (0.7, 0.5, 0.3 on the E2E weight) to explore the Pareto frontier\n\n**Data split:** No training/test split for CMA-ES — it optimizes against BLIS E2E on all 10 experiments simultaneously. Generalization tested via LOMO/LOWO.\n\n### H2: Pareto Sweep Identifies Knee Point\n\n**Claim:** Running CMA-ES with different E2E/ITL weight ratios produces a Pareto frontier where at least one configuration achieves **E2E < 12% AND ITL < 20%** — a result that R3's single-objective could not achieve.\n\n**Refutation criteria:** No Pareto point achieves both E2E < 15% and ITL < 25%.\n\n**Method:**\n1. Run H1 with α ∈ {0.7, 0.5, 0.3} (weighting E2E vs ITL)\n2. Collect per-experiment E2E and ITL errors for each α\n3. Plot Pareto frontier: E2E vs ITL\n4. Select knee point (closest to the origin) as the recommended configuration\n\n### H3: LOMO Generalization (Cross-Model Artifact Transfer)\n\n**Claim:** Constrained CMA-ES artifacts transfer across models with **mean best-donor E2E < 20%** (vs R3's 14.8% with unconstrained CMA-ES). Constraining the parameter space should maintain cross-model transferability while improving ITL.\n\n**Refutation criteria:** Mean best-donor E2E > 30% (2× worse than R3 LOMO).\n\n**Method:**\n1. For each model group, apply the CMA-ES-optimized artifacts from other models\n2. Evaluate BLIS E2E and ITL per experiment\n3. Build cross-model transfer matrix (same as R3 H5)\n4. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_model_out()` for data splitting\n\n### H4: LOWO Generalization (Cross-Workload Stability)\n\n**Claim:** Constrained CMA-ES artifacts show per-model workload variance **≤ 20pp** (range across workloads) for dense models, with **mean E2E within 2× of aggregate** for all 10 experiments.\n\n**Refutation criteria:** More than 2/10 experiments exceed 2× aggregate E2E error.\n\n**Method:**\n1. Evaluate per-experiment E2E/ITL from H1's best configuration\n2. Group by model, compute per-workload breakdown\n3. Measure range (max-min) per model\n4. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_workload_out()` for data splitting\n\n## Execution Plan\n\n1. H1 first — constrained CMA-ES per model with dual objective\n2. H2 — Pareto sweep (runs H1 with different α values)\n3. H3 — LOMO using H1's best artifacts\n4. H4 — LOWO from H1's results\n\n## Short-Circuit Criteria\n\nIf H1 produces mean E2E > 25% (significantly worse than R3's 15.1%), the constrained approach is harming more than helping — abort remaining hypotheses and document root cause.\n","numLines":87,"startLine":1,"totalLines":87}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_016FSvg5UquDQ3S9qSGcCwvk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# HYPOTHESIS: Data-Driven Step Cycle Time Model with Explicit CPU Overhead Separation\n     2→\n     3→**Round:** 4\n     4→**Idea:** 2 — Cycle-Time Regression\n     5→**Date:** 2026-03-02\n     6→**Status:** Pending\n     7→\n     8→## Context and Prior Findings\n     9→\n    10→All prior rounds modeled `step.duration_us` — the GPU forward pass time (~70–7,000μs) — and added overhead as a post-hoc floor via `max(overhead, compute)`. This creates the \"faster universe\" problem (BC-NEW-2): BLIS completes requests in ~40% of real time because the overhead floor is calibrated from ITL residuals, not from direct measurement.\n    11→\n    12→The real step cycle time (what matters for E2E/ITL) is the inter-token interval (ITI) between consecutive output tokens, which includes:\n    13→- GPU forward pass (`step.duration_us`)\n    14→- CPU scheduling overhead (queue scanning, KV allocation, priority sorting)\n    15→- CUDA synchronization time\n    16→- Memory management (block allocation, eviction decisions)\n    17→\n    18→This idea trains the step-time model on **actual ITI from lifecycle data** instead of `step.duration_us`, eliminating the need for a separate overhead floor.\n    19→\n    20→### Related Work\n    21→\n    22→- FairBatching [Patel et al., 2025] — `batch_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context`, ±1.3% with continuous calibration\n    23→- AIConfigurator [2026] — 7.8% TPOT MAPE via operator-level decomposition + summing\n    24→- Vidur [Agrawal et al., 2024] — operator-level RF models, <5% P95 error, random forest for attention ops\n    25→- R2 discovery: overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`) handles 77.9% of steps\n    26→- R3 discovery: per-step MAPE improvements have zero impact on BLIS E2E due to overhead floor dominance\n    27→\n    28→## Sub-Hypotheses\n    29→\n    30→### H1: Cycle-Time Extraction from Lifecycle Data\n    31→\n    32→**Claim:** Per-step cycle times can be reliably extracted from lifecycle per-token timestamps, with Pearson r > 0.7 between extracted cycle times and corresponding `step.duration_us` values for the compute-dominated regime (large batches).\n    33→\n    34→**Refutation criteria:** Pearson r < 0.3 (no meaningful correlation) or >50% of steps cannot be matched to lifecycle timestamps.\n    35→\n    36→**Method:**\n    37→1. Load per-request lifecycle data (per_request_lifecycle_metrics.json) for each experiment\n    38→2. For each request, compute ITI = timestamp[i+1] - timestamp[i] for consecutive output tokens\n    39→3. Join ITI values with step-level data by timestamp matching (within step window)\n    40→4. Compute cycle_time per step as mean or median ITI across requests in that step\n    41→5. Compare cycle_time vs step.duration_us: the ratio (cycle_time / step.duration_us) should be >1 for small batches (overhead-dominated) and ≈1 for large batches (compute-dominated)\n    42→6. Report distribution of cycle_time / step.duration_us across regimes\n    43→\n    44→### H2: FairBatching Cycle-Time Regression → BLIS E2E\n    45→\n    46→**Claim:** A per-model FairBatching-style regression on cycle time (`cycle_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum`) achieves **mean BLIS E2E < 25%** with **mean ITL < 20%** across 10 experiments, without any separate overhead floor.\n    47→\n    48→**Refutation criteria:** Mean BLIS E2E > 40% (worse than R3 trace replay baseline of 56.2%) OR mean ITL > 25%.\n    49→\n    50→**Method:**\n    51→1. Use H1's extracted cycle times as the training target\n    52→2. Train per-model OLS: `cycle_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum` (FairBatching formulation)\n    53→3. Also train regime-separated models: decode-only (prefill=0) and mixed-batch (prefill>0)\n    54→4. Export coefficients to StepML JSON artifact:\n    55→   - `step_overhead_us` = regression intercept for decode-only regime (data-derived)\n    56→   - `output_token_processing_time_us` = 0 (absorbed into cycle time)\n    57→   - TTFT correction from R3 H3 in QueueingTime\n    58→5. Run BLIS validation via `validate_blis.py` with trace replay\n    59→6. Report per-experiment E2E, TTFT, ITL errors\n    60→\n    61→**Data split:** Temporal split (60/20/20) for per-step regression training/validation. BLIS E2E evaluated on all experiments (trace replay mode).\n    62→\n    63→### H3: LOMO Generalization (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n    64→\n    65→**Claim:** Cycle-time regression achieves **LOMO per-step MAPE < 80%** per fold (train on 3 models, predict 4th).\n    66→\n    67→**Refutation criteria:** Any fold MAPE > 150% (worse than R2's 108.6% regime ensemble LOMO).\n    68→\n    69→**Method:**\n    70→1. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_model_out()` for 4-fold splitting\n    71→2. For each fold: train per-model cycle-time regression on 3 models, predict held-out 4th\n    72→3. Report per-fold MAPE and aggregate LOMO MAPE\n    73→4. Analyze which model is hardest to predict (expected: Mixtral due to MoE architecture)\n    74→\n    75→### H4: LOWO Generalization (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n    76→\n    77→**Claim:** Cycle-time regression achieves **LOWO per-step MAPE < 50%** per fold (train on 2 workloads, predict 3rd).\n    78→\n    79→**Refutation criteria:** Any fold MAPE > 100%.\n    80→\n    81→**Method:**\n    82→1. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_workload_out()` for 3-fold splitting\n    83→2. For each fold: train per-model cycle-time regression on 2 workloads, predict held-out 3rd\n    84→3. Report per-fold MAPE and aggregate LOWO MAPE\n    85→4. Analyze whether general/codegen/roleplay workloads have different cycle-time characteristics\n    86→\n    87→## Execution Plan\n    88→\n    89→1. H1 first — extract cycle times (prerequisite for all other hypotheses)\n    90→2. H2 — train and validate cycle-time regression\n    91→3. H3 + H4 — LOMO/LOWO generalization (can run in parallel after H2)\n    92→\n    93→## Short-Circuit Criteria\n    94→\n    95→If H1 fails (cannot reliably extract cycle times from lifecycle data, <50% join rate), the entire idea is infeasible — abort and document the data quality gap. If H2 produces mean E2E > 56.2% (worse than the R3 trace replay baseline without CMA-ES), the cycle-time model adds no value — abort H3/H4.\n    96→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"7f57dbbc-e4c0-4ce4-8c63-6a948f72d088","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/hypotheses/h-stepml/round4/idea-2-cycle-time-regression/HYPOTHESIS.md","content":"# HYPOTHESIS: Data-Driven Step Cycle Time Model with Explicit CPU Overhead Separation\n\n**Round:** 4\n**Idea:** 2 — Cycle-Time Regression\n**Date:** 2026-03-02\n**Status:** Pending\n\n## Context and Prior Findings\n\nAll prior rounds modeled `step.duration_us` — the GPU forward pass time (~70–7,000μs) — and added overhead as a post-hoc floor via `max(overhead, compute)`. This creates the \"faster universe\" problem (BC-NEW-2): BLIS completes requests in ~40% of real time because the overhead floor is calibrated from ITL residuals, not from direct measurement.\n\nThe real step cycle time (what matters for E2E/ITL) is the inter-token interval (ITI) between consecutive output tokens, which includes:\n- GPU forward pass (`step.duration_us`)\n- CPU scheduling overhead (queue scanning, KV allocation, priority sorting)\n- CUDA synchronization time\n- Memory management (block allocation, eviction decisions)\n\nThis idea trains the step-time model on **actual ITI from lifecycle data** instead of `step.duration_us`, eliminating the need for a separate overhead floor.\n\n### Related Work\n\n- FairBatching [Patel et al., 2025] — `batch_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context`, ±1.3% with continuous calibration\n- AIConfigurator [2026] — 7.8% TPOT MAPE via operator-level decomposition + summing\n- Vidur [Agrawal et al., 2024] — operator-level RF models, <5% P95 error, random forest for attention ops\n- R2 discovery: overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`) handles 77.9% of steps\n- R3 discovery: per-step MAPE improvements have zero impact on BLIS E2E due to overhead floor dominance\n\n## Sub-Hypotheses\n\n### H1: Cycle-Time Extraction from Lifecycle Data\n\n**Claim:** Per-step cycle times can be reliably extracted from lifecycle per-token timestamps, with Pearson r > 0.7 between extracted cycle times and corresponding `step.duration_us` values for the compute-dominated regime (large batches).\n\n**Refutation criteria:** Pearson r < 0.3 (no meaningful correlation) or >50% of steps cannot be matched to lifecycle timestamps.\n\n**Method:**\n1. Load per-request lifecycle data (per_request_lifecycle_metrics.json) for each experiment\n2. For each request, compute ITI = timestamp[i+1] - timestamp[i] for consecutive output tokens\n3. Join ITI values with step-level data by timestamp matching (within step window)\n4. Compute cycle_time per step as mean or median ITI across requests in that step\n5. Compare cycle_time vs step.duration_us: the ratio (cycle_time / step.duration_us) should be >1 for small batches (overhead-dominated) and ≈1 for large batches (compute-dominated)\n6. Report distribution of cycle_time / step.duration_us across regimes\n\n### H2: FairBatching Cycle-Time Regression → BLIS E2E\n\n**Claim:** A per-model FairBatching-style regression on cycle time (`cycle_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum`) achieves **mean BLIS E2E < 25%** with **mean ITL < 20%** across 10 experiments, without any separate overhead floor.\n\n**Refutation criteria:** Mean BLIS E2E > 40% (worse than R3 trace replay baseline of 56.2%) OR mean ITL > 25%.\n\n**Method:**\n1. Use H1's extracted cycle times as the training target\n2. Train per-model OLS: `cycle_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum` (FairBatching formulation)\n3. Also train regime-separated models: decode-only (prefill=0) and mixed-batch (prefill>0)\n4. Export coefficients to StepML JSON artifact:\n   - `step_overhead_us` = regression intercept for decode-only regime (data-derived)\n   - `output_token_processing_time_us` = 0 (absorbed into cycle time)\n   - TTFT correction from R3 H3 in QueueingTime\n5. Run BLIS validation via `validate_blis.py` with trace replay\n6. Report per-experiment E2E, TTFT, ITL errors\n\n**Data split:** Temporal split (60/20/20) for per-step regression training/validation. BLIS E2E evaluated on all experiments (trace replay mode).\n\n### H3: LOMO Generalization (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n\n**Claim:** Cycle-time regression achieves **LOMO per-step MAPE < 80%** per fold (train on 3 models, predict 4th).\n\n**Refutation criteria:** Any fold MAPE > 150% (worse than R2's 108.6% regime ensemble LOMO).\n\n**Method:**\n1. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_model_out()` for 4-fold splitting\n2. For each fold: train per-model cycle-time regression on 3 models, predict held-out 4th\n3. Report per-fold MAPE and aggregate LOMO MAPE\n4. Analyze which model is hardest to predict (expected: Mixtral due to MoE architecture)\n\n### H4: LOWO Generalization (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n\n**Claim:** Cycle-time regression achieves **LOWO per-step MAPE < 50%** per fold (train on 2 workloads, predict 3rd).\n\n**Refutation criteria:** Any fold MAPE > 100%.\n\n**Method:**\n1. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_workload_out()` for 3-fold splitting\n2. For each fold: train per-model cycle-time regression on 2 workloads, predict held-out 3rd\n3. Report per-fold MAPE and aggregate LOWO MAPE\n4. Analyze whether general/codegen/roleplay workloads have different cycle-time characteristics\n\n## Execution Plan\n\n1. H1 first — extract cycle times (prerequisite for all other hypotheses)\n2. H2 — train and validate cycle-time regression\n3. H3 + H4 — LOMO/LOWO generalization (can run in parallel after H2)\n\n## Short-Circuit Criteria\n\nIf H1 fails (cannot reliably extract cycle times from lifecycle data, <50% join rate), the entire idea is infeasible — abort and document the data quality gap. If H2 produces mean E2E > 56.2% (worse than the R3 trace replay baseline without CMA-ES), the cycle-time model adds no value — abort H3/H4.\n","numLines":96,"startLine":1,"totalLines":96}}}
