{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_012ehMExempzySVrhBugjoyv","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Round 4: Research Ideas\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-02\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Primary Binding Constraint:** BC-NEW-1 — E2E ↔ ITL fundamental tradeoff (CMA-ES achieves 15.1% E2E but 87.4% ITL)\n     6→**Secondary Constraints:** BC-NEW-2 (step cycle under-prediction), BC-6 (vLLM args sensitivity never analyzed)\n     7→**Number to Beat:** 15.1% mean E2E (R3 CMA-ES), 9.5% mean ITL (R3 trace replay baseline)\n     8→**Target:** E2E < 10% AND ITL < 15% simultaneously\n     9→\n    10→---\n    11→\n    12→## Idea 1: Multi-Objective Constrained CMA-ES with ITL Penalty\n    13→\n    14→### Title\n    15→Multi-Objective CMA-ES with Explicit ITL Constraint for Joint E2E + ITL Optimization\n    16→\n    17→### Rationale\n    18→\n    19→**Directly addresses BC-NEW-1 (E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff).** Round 3 showed CMA-ES is the only approach to achieve <16% E2E (15.1%), but it sacrifices ITL (87.4%) by inflating `output_token_processing_time_us` to implausible values (e.g., 0 → 1,899μs for 7B). The root cause is the single-objective formulation: CMA-ES minimizes E2E without knowledge of ITL consequences.\n    20→\n    21→**Literature grounding:** Multi-objective evolutionary optimization (NSGA-II, MO-CMA-ES) is well-established for Pareto frontier discovery in noisy simulation tuning [Deb et al., 2002; Igel et al., 2007]. FairBatching [Patel et al., 2025] demonstrates that step-time accuracy ±1.3% is achievable with `a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context`, suggesting that ITL accuracy ≤15% is feasible if the optimizer is constrained.\n    22→\n    23→**Codebase grounding:** The existing R3 CMA-ES infrastructure (`round3/idea-3-e2e-calibration/run_experiment.py`) already supports per-model optimization with trace replay. The change is to the objective function: instead of `f(params) = mean_e2e_error(experiments)`, use `f(params) = mean_e2e_error + λ * max(0, mean_itl_error - 0.15)` where λ is a penalty weight. This preserves the entire CMA-ES pipeline while adding ITL awareness.\n    24→\n    25→**Why it differs from R3 Idea 3:** R3 used unconstrained single-objective CMA-ES. This idea adds an explicit ITL penalty term and constrains `output_token_processing_time_us` to physically plausible ranges (0–500μs based on real vLLM measurements). The constrained search space prevents the optimizer from using OTPT as a proxy for missing simulation dynamics.\n    26→\n    27→### Method Sketch\n    28→\n    29→1. **Constrained parameter space:** Bound `output_token_processing_time_us` ∈ [0, 500], `scheduling_processing_time_us` ∈ [0, 2000], `step_overhead_us` ∈ [model_baseline × 0.8, model_baseline × 3.0]. This prevents physically implausible solutions.\n    30→2. **Penalty-augmented objective:** `objective = α * mean_e2e_error + (1-α) * mean_itl_error + λ * constraint_violation`, where constraint violations include ITL > 20% or OTPT > 500μs.\n    31→3. **TTFT additive corrections (from R3 H3):** Per-model TTFT corrections (16–61ms) are applied *within the objective evaluation*, not post-hoc. CMA-ES sees the corrected E2E and optimizes around it, avoiding the R3 H3 double-counting issue.\n    32→4. **Per-model optimization:** Same as R3 — separate CMA-ES run per model group.\n    33→5. **Pareto sweep:** Run with multiple α values (0.7, 0.5, 0.3) to explore the Pareto frontier, then select the knee point.\n    34→\n    35→### Expected Outcome\n    36→\n    37→E2E < 12% mean with ITL < 20% mean, with at least 6/10 experiments below 10% E2E. The constraint prevents the catastrophic ITL degradation seen in R3.\n    38→\n    39→### Go Integration Path\n    40→\n    41→Coefficient export — same StepML JSON artifact format as R3. No new Go code needed.\n    42→\n    43→### LatencyModel Methods Targeted\n    44→\n    45→All 5 methods via CMA-ES parameter tuning: StepTime (regime coefficients + overhead floor), QueueingTime (TTFT corrections), OutputTokenProcessingTime, SchedulingProcessingTime, PreemptionProcessingTime.\n    46→\n    47→### Generalization Plans\n    48→\n    49→#### LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n    50→Same protocol as R3 H5: train CMA-ES on 3 models, apply artifact to held-out 4th. R3 showed 14.8% LOMO E2E — the constrained version should maintain or improve this since the constraints prevent overfitting to simulation artifacts. Model features enabling transfer: overhead floor values scale with model size/TP, regime coefficients capture batch-composition physics.\n    51→\n    52→#### LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n    53→R3 showed 8/10 within 2× aggregate for LOWO. Re-run with constrained CMA-ES and verify workload variance doesn't increase. Dense models (70B, 34B) showed 9-16pp range — target ≤20pp with constrained optimization.\n    54→\n    55→#### vLLM Args Sensitivity Analysis\n    56→\n    57→| Parameter | Dependent? | Would predictions break? | Recalibration needed |\n    58→|---|---|---|---|\n    59→| `max_num_seqs` (128) | **Yes** — controls batch size distribution → affects overhead floor regime | Overhead floor would be wrong for different batch size regime | Re-optimize `step_overhead_us` only (~5 min CMA-ES) |\n    60→| `max_num_batched_tokens` (2048) | **Yes** — controls chunked prefill budget → changes mixed-batch frequency | Regime boundaries (prefill=0 threshold) might shift | Re-optimize regime coefficients (~15 min CMA-ES) |\n    61→| `max_model_len` (4096) | **Weak** — changes KV capacity → may shift batch sizes under pressure | Predictions stable unless KV pressure forces evictions | None for moderate changes; re-optimize for >2× change |\n    62→| `chunked_prefill` (on) | **Strong** — fundamentally changes batch composition | Model assumes mixed batches; pure-prefill regime doesn't exist in training data | Full retrain required |\n    63→| `prefix_caching` (on) | **Moderate** — changes effective prefill tokens | Prefill regime coefficients would over-predict | Re-optimize prefill regime coefficients only |\n    64→| `gpu_memory_utilization` (0.9) | **Weak** — changes KV capacity | Same as max_model_len: only matters under extreme memory pressure | None for ≥0.7; re-optimize for <0.5 |\n    65→| `tensor_parallel_size` (varies) | **Strong** — changes per-GPU compute/memory | Overhead floor and all coefficients change | Full retrain for new TP degree |\n    66→\n    67→**Recalibration story:** CMA-ES re-optimization for a single parameter change takes ~5-15 minutes (50-100 evaluations). For `chunked_prefill` or `TP` changes, full retrain (~30 min/model) is required. This is acceptable for production: new serving configs are deployed infrequently and calibration is automated.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## Idea 2: Principled Overhead Floor Calibration via Cycle-Time Regression\n    72→\n    73→### Title\n    74→Data-Driven Step Cycle Time Model with Explicit CPU Overhead Separation\n    75→\n    76→### Rationale\n    77→\n    78→**Directly addresses BC-NEW-2 (step cycle under-prediction) and the root cause of BC-NEW-1.** The \"faster universe\" problem (BLIS at ~40% real speed) exists because:\n    79→1. `step.duration_us` in training data captures GPU forward pass only (~70–7,000μs)\n    80→2. Real step cycle time = GPU forward pass + CPU overhead (scheduling, sync, memory management)\n    81→3. The overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`) is a heuristic — its value was hand-tuned from ITL residuals, not derived from the data itself\n    82→\n    83→**Literature grounding:** AIConfigurator [2026] achieves 7.8% TPOT MAPE by decomposing iteration time into profiled operator primitives and summing them. Vidur [Agrawal et al., 2024] achieves <5% P95 error with operator-level RF models. FairBatching [Patel et al., 2025] achieves ±1.3% with continuous calibration of `a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context`. The common thread: **model what you measure, then add overhead separately**.\n    84→\n    85→**Codebase grounding:** Examining `sim/latency/stepml.go:232-268`, the overhead is applied as `max(overhead, compute)` with a hard cap at 3×overhead. The overhead constant comes from R2's manual calibration (ground-truth ITL - mean compute). Instead, we should derive the overhead from the *ground-truth step cycle times* directly.\n    86→\n    87→**Key insight:** We have per-request lifecycle data with per-token timestamps. The inter-token interval (ITI) between consecutive output tokens of the same request represents the actual step cycle time that request experienced. By regressing ITI against batch composition features, we can build a **cycle time model** that inherently includes CPU overhead — no separate overhead floor needed.\n    88→\n    89→**Why it differs from prior rounds:** R1-R3 all modeled `step.duration_us` (GPU forward pass) and added overhead as a post-hoc floor. This idea models the **actual cycle time** (ITI from lifecycle data), which naturally includes all overhead. The overhead floor becomes unnecessary if the cycle time model is accurate.\n    90→\n    91→### Method Sketch\n    92→\n    93→1. **Extract per-step cycle times from lifecycle data:** For each request's output tokens, compute ITI = timestamp[i+1] - timestamp[i]. These represent real step cycle times.\n    94→2. **Join cycle times with step-level batch features:** Match lifecycle timestamps to step windows to assign batch composition features (prefill_tokens, decode_tokens, kv_sum) to each cycle time.\n    95→3. **Train per-model FairBatching-style regression on cycle times:** `cycle_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum` where the target is ITI (real cycle time), not step.duration_us (GPU-only). The intercept `a` naturally absorbs CPU overhead.\n    96→4. **Regime separation:** Decode-only (prefill=0) gets its own model where `a_decode` represents the full cycle overhead; mixed batches get `a_mixed + b*prefill + c*decode + d*kv_sum`.\n    97→5. **BLIS integration:** Export coefficients to StepML artifact. The overhead floor is set to `a_decode` (the regression intercept for decode-only steps), which is data-derived rather than hand-tuned. No cap needed since the model already predicts cycle time, not compute time.\n    98→6. **Combine with TTFT additive corrections:** Apply per-model TTFT corrections from R3 H3 (16–61ms) directly in the artifact's QueueingTime model.\n    99→\n   100→### Expected Outcome\n   101→\n   102→By modeling the *right target variable* (cycle time vs GPU-only time), the \"faster universe\" problem should largely disappear. Target: E2E < 15% with ITL < 15% (both without CMA-ES). If successful, CMA-ES can be applied on top for further E2E refinement without the E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff (since the baseline is already correctly calibrated).\n   103→\n   104→### Go Integration Path\n   105→\n   106→Coefficient export — same StepML JSON artifact format. The key difference is the overhead floor value changes (data-derived vs hand-tuned), and the regression targets cycle time instead of compute time.\n   107→\n   108→### LatencyModel Methods Targeted\n   109→\n   110→StepTime (primary — cycle time regression), QueueingTime (TTFT corrections). OutputTokenProcessingTime set to 0 (absorbed into cycle time model). SchedulingProcessingTime and PreemptionProcessingTime remain 0 (absorbed into intercept).\n   111→\n   112→### Generalization Plans\n   113→\n   114→#### LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n   115→4-fold LOMO on cycle time regression. Since the intercept `a` absorbs per-model CPU overhead, cross-model transfer depends on whether overhead scales predictably with model size/TP. Expected: intercept scales roughly with model parameter count (more parameters → more memory management overhead). Target: LOMO per-step MAPE < 80%.\n   116→\n   117→#### LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n   118→3-fold LOWO. The FairBatching formulation (`new_tokens + kv_sum`) captures workload-invariant compute physics — workload differences affect only the *distribution* of these features, not the *relationship* between features and cycle time. Expected: LOWO per-step MAPE < 50%.\n   119→\n   120→#### vLLM Args Sensitivity Analysis\n   121→\n   122→| Parameter | Dependent? | Would predictions break? | Recalibration needed |\n   123→|---|---|---|---|\n   124→| `max_num_seqs` (128) | **Moderate** — affects batch size distribution but regression captures the relationship | Predictions shift within trained range | None if batch sizes stay within training range; retrain for >2× change |\n   125→| `max_num_batched_tokens` (2048) | **Moderate** — changes mixed-batch frequency | Regime proportions shift, but per-regime models are independent | None for moderate changes |\n   126→| `max_model_len` (4096) | **Weak** — KV capacity affects eviction, not step time | No impact on cycle time model | None |\n   127→| `chunked_prefill` (on) | **Strong** — model trained on chunked-prefill data exclusively | Without chunked prefill, pure-prefill steps would appear; model has no data for these | Full retrain (need data with chunked_prefill=off) |\n   128→| `prefix_caching` (on) | **Moderate** — affects effective prefill tokens | Prefill coefficient might over-predict; but cycle time intercept still anchors predictions | Retrain prefill regime coefficients |\n   129→| `gpu_memory_utilization` (0.9) | **Weak** — no direct effect on cycle time per step | No impact | None |\n   130→| `tensor_parallel_size` (varies) | **Strong** — changes GPU communication overhead → changes intercept | Cycle time intercept (CPU overhead) changes with TP | Full retrain for new TP |\n   131→\n   132→**Recalibration story:** The formulation is structurally robust because it models *measured cycle time*, not derived quantities. For TP or chunked_prefill changes, collect ~1000 steps of profiling data and retrain (OLS, <1 second). The key advantage over CMA-ES: recalibration requires only step-level data, not full BLIS simulation runs.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## Idea 3: Hybrid Cycle-Time CMA-ES — Principled Base + Black-Box Residual\n   137→\n   138→### Title\n   139→Two-Stage Calibration: Data-Derived Cycle-Time Base + Constrained CMA-ES Residual Tuning\n   140→\n   141→### Rationale\n   142→\n   143→**Combines the strengths of Ideas 1 and 2 to address all binding constraints simultaneously.** The E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff (BC-NEW-1) arises because CMA-ES compensates for a poorly calibrated base model by distorting secondary coefficients. If the base model already runs at the correct speed (Idea 2 fixes BC-NEW-2), CMA-ES only needs to make *small residual adjustments* rather than large compensatory distortions.\n   144→\n   145→**Literature grounding:** Hybrid approaches combining physics-informed base models with learned residual corrections are standard in scientific simulation calibration [Kennedy & O'Hagan, 2001]. Revati [2025] uses Vidur's analytical models enhanced with profiling for <5% error. The principle: **start with a principled model, then calibrate residuals**.\n   146→\n   147→**Key insight from R3:** CMA-ES inflated `output_token_processing_time_us` to 1,899μs (llama-2-7b) because the base model under-predicted step cycle time by ~2×. If the base model is already correct (via cycle-time regression from Idea 2), CMA-ES's search space shrinks dramatically and the E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff softens.\n   148→\n   149→**Why it differs from prior approaches:** R3 Idea 3 applied CMA-ES to a poorly calibrated base (overhead floor from R2 hand-tuning). This idea first establishes a principled cycle-time base (Idea 2), then applies *tightly constrained* CMA-ES to fine-tune residuals. The two-stage approach means CMA-ES corrections are ≤20% of base values rather than ≥100%.\n   150→\n   151→### Method Sketch\n   152→\n   153→1. **Stage 1 — Principled base (from Idea 2):**\n   154→   - Train per-model cycle-time regression on ITI (inter-token interval) from lifecycle data\n   155→   - Derive overhead floor from regression intercept\n   156→   - Apply TTFT additive corrections from R3 H3\n   157→   - Evaluate BLIS E2E and ITL → this is the \"principled base\" result\n   158→\n   159→2. **Stage 2 — Constrained CMA-ES residual tuning:**\n   160→   - Starting point: Idea 2's principled coefficients\n   161→   - **Tight bounds:** Each parameter bounded within ±20% of Stage 1 value (not the ±200% that R3 effectively allowed)\n   162→   - **Dual-objective penalty:** `objective = 0.5 * mean_e2e_error + 0.5 * mean_itl_error + λ * constraint_violations`\n   163→   - **Hard constraints:** `output_token_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 200]`, `step_overhead_us ∈ [base ± 15%]`\n   164→   - **Fewer evaluations:** Since the starting point is already good, CMA-ES converges faster (~50-80 evaluations vs 96-152 in R3)\n   165→\n   166→3. **Fallback logic:** If CMA-ES Stage 2 worsens ITL by >5pp relative to Stage 1, discard CMA-ES results and use Stage 1 directly. This provides a safety net.\n   167→\n   168→### Expected Outcome\n   169→\n   170→Stage 1 alone: E2E ~20-25% with ITL ~12-15% (correctly calibrated base).\n   171→After Stage 2: E2E < 10% with ITL < 15% for ≥7/10 experiments. The tight bounds prevent CMA-ES from distorting the principled base.\n   172→\n   173→### Go Integration Path\n   174→\n   175→Coefficient export — same StepML JSON artifact format. Stage 2 produces the final artifact.\n   176→\n   177→### LatencyModel Methods Targeted\n   178→\n   179→All 5 methods:\n   180→- StepTime: Cycle-time regression (Stage 1) + residual tuning (Stage 2)\n   181→- QueueingTime: TTFT additive corrections (Stage 1) + fine-tuning (Stage 2)\n   182→- OutputTokenProcessingTime: Data-derived (Stage 1, ≤200μs) + bounded tuning (Stage 2)\n   183→- SchedulingProcessingTime: Small constant (Stage 1) + bounded tuning (Stage 2)\n   184→- PreemptionProcessingTime: Remains 0 (negligible in training data)\n   185→\n   186→### Generalization Plans\n   187→\n   188→#### LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n   189→Two-level LOMO test:\n   190→- **Stage 1 LOMO:** Train cycle-time regression on 3 models, predict 4th. Target: <80% per-step MAPE.\n   191→- **Stage 2 LOMO:** Apply CMA-ES artifacts (trained on 3 models) to held-out 4th via cross-model transfer. R3 showed 14.8% LOMO E2E — with a better base model, this should improve or maintain.\n   192→- **Combined LOMO:** The principled base provides structure; CMA-ES residuals provide per-model fine-tuning. For a truly new model, Stage 1 (cycle-time regression with lifecycle data) is all that's needed — CMA-ES Stage 2 is optional polish.\n   193→\n   194→#### LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n   195→3-fold LOWO on both stages. The cycle-time regression (Stage 1) is workload-invariant by construction (models batch-composition → cycle-time physics). CMA-ES residuals (Stage 2) are trained across all workloads per model, so they average workload effects. Target: <50% per-step MAPE for Stage 1; <30% E2E for combined.\n   196→\n   197→#### vLLM Args Sensitivity Analysis\n   198→\n   199→| Parameter | Dependent? | Would predictions break? | Recalibration needed |\n   200→|---|---|---|---|\n   201→| `max_num_seqs` (128) | **Moderate** — Stage 1 captures batch-level physics; Stage 2 residuals are small | Stage 1 robust within training range; Stage 2 residuals may be slightly wrong | Re-run Stage 2 CMA-ES only (~10 min) |\n   202→| `max_num_batched_tokens` (2048) | **Moderate** — affects mixed-batch frequency | Stage 1 regime boundaries may shift | Re-estimate regime thresholds from new data; Stage 2 optional |\n   203→| `max_model_len` (4096) | **Weak** — no direct impact on per-step cycle time | Stable | None |\n   204→| `chunked_prefill` (on) | **Strong** — both stages trained on chunked-prefill data | Without it, pure-prefill regime appears; Stage 1 has no data | Full retrain of Stage 1; Stage 2 optional re-run |\n   205→| `prefix_caching` (on) | **Moderate** — affects effective prefill tokens | Stage 1 prefill coefficients may over-predict | Retrain Stage 1 prefill regime; Stage 2 absorbs residual |\n   206→| `gpu_memory_utilization` (0.9) | **Weak** — no direct impact | Stable | None |\n   207→| `tensor_parallel_size` (varies) | **Strong** — changes communication overhead → Stage 1 intercept | Both stages wrong for new TP | Full retrain of both stages |\n   208→\n   209→**Recalibration story:** Two-level: (1) Stage 1 recalibration requires only ~1000 steps of profiling data + OLS fit (<1 second). (2) Stage 2 requires ~50 BLIS runs (~10 minutes). For routine changes (new max_num_seqs), only Stage 2 needs re-running. For fundamental changes (new TP, chunked_prefill off), both stages retrain from scratch. Total: ~35 minutes max, fully automated.\n   210→\n   211→---\n   212→\n   213→## Summary: How Ideas Address Binding Constraints\n   214→\n   215→| Constraint | Idea 1 (Constrained CMA-ES) | Idea 2 (Cycle-Time Regression) | Idea 3 (Hybrid) |\n   216→|---|---|---|---|\n   217→| **BC-NEW-1: E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff** | ITL penalty + parameter bounds | Eliminated at source (cycle-time model) | Both: principled base + bounded CMA-ES |\n   218→| **BC-NEW-2: Step cycle under-prediction** | Indirectly via overhead tuning | Directly (model cycle time, not compute time) | Directly via Stage 1 |\n   219→| **BC-6: vLLM args sensitivity** | Analyzed above | Analyzed above | Analyzed above |\n   220→| **BC-4: Mixtral MoE variance** | Better via constrained optimization | Uncertain (linear model may not capture MoE) | Best chance: Stage 1 + MoE-aware Stage 2 |\n   221→| **BC-5: LOMO generalization** | Inherits R3's 14.8% LOMO E2E | New — cycle time LOMO | Two-level LOMO |\n   222→\n   223→## Distinctiveness of Ideas\n   224→\n   225→- **Idea 1** improves the *optimization* (multi-objective + constraints) while keeping the same base model\n   226→- **Idea 2** improves the *base model* (cycle time target) without black-box optimization\n   227→- **Idea 3** combines both — principled base + constrained optimization\n   228→\n   229→All three are distinct and attack different aspects of the problem. Idea 3 subsumes Ideas 1 and 2, but testing them independently reveals which component contributes most.\n   230→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"e5ca4b9e-9d41-49ed-b9fa-f4c22e0405b4"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01VL6UPXf83fdSH48XfBhmsJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Round 4: Research Ideas\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-02\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Primary Binding Constraint:** BC-NEW-1 — E2E ↔ ITL fundamental tradeoff (CMA-ES achieves 15.1% E2E but 87.4% ITL)\n     6→**Secondary Constraints:** BC-NEW-2 (step cycle under-prediction), BC-6 (vLLM args sensitivity never analyzed)\n     7→**Number to Beat:** 15.1% mean E2E (R3 CMA-ES), 9.5% mean ITL (R3 trace replay baseline)\n     8→**Target:** E2E < 10% AND ITL < 15% simultaneously\n     9→\n    10→---\n    11→\n    12→## Idea 1: Multi-Objective Constrained CMA-ES with ITL Penalty\n    13→\n    14→### Title\n    15→Multi-Objective CMA-ES with Explicit ITL Constraint for Joint E2E + ITL Optimization\n    16→\n    17→### Rationale\n    18→\n    19→**Directly addresses BC-NEW-1 (E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff).** Round 3 showed CMA-ES is the only approach to achieve <16% E2E (15.1%), but it sacrifices ITL (87.4%) by inflating `output_token_processing_time_us` to implausible values (e.g., 0 → 1,899μs for 7B). The root cause is the single-objective formulation: CMA-ES minimizes E2E without knowledge of ITL consequences.\n    20→\n    21→**Literature grounding:** Multi-objective evolutionary optimization (NSGA-II, MO-CMA-ES) is well-established for Pareto frontier discovery in noisy simulation tuning [Deb et al., 2002; Igel et al., 2007]. FairBatching [Patel et al., 2025] demonstrates that step-time accuracy ±1.3% is achievable with `a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context`, suggesting that ITL accuracy ≤15% is feasible if the optimizer is constrained.\n    22→\n    23→**Codebase grounding:** The existing R3 CMA-ES infrastructure (`round3/idea-3-e2e-calibration/run_experiment.py`) already supports per-model optimization with trace replay. The change is to the objective function: instead of `f(params) = mean_e2e_error(experiments)`, use `f(params) = mean_e2e_error + λ * max(0, mean_itl_error - 0.15)` where λ is a penalty weight. This preserves the entire CMA-ES pipeline while adding ITL awareness.\n    24→\n    25→**Why it differs from R3 Idea 3:** R3 used unconstrained single-objective CMA-ES. This idea adds an explicit ITL penalty term and constrains `output_token_processing_time_us` to physically plausible ranges (0–500μs based on real vLLM measurements). The constrained search space prevents the optimizer from using OTPT as a proxy for missing simulation dynamics.\n    26→\n    27→### Method Sketch\n    28→\n    29→1. **Constrained parameter space:** Bound `output_token_processing_time_us` ∈ [0, 500], `scheduling_processing_time_us` ∈ [0, 2000], `step_overhead_us` ∈ [model_baseline × 0.8, model_baseline × 3.0]. This prevents physically implausible solutions.\n    30→2. **Penalty-augmented objective:** `objective = α * mean_e2e_error + (1-α) * mean_itl_error + λ * constraint_violation`, where constraint violations include ITL > 20% or OTPT > 500μs.\n    31→3. **TTFT additive corrections (from R3 H3):** Per-model TTFT corrections (16–61ms) are applied *within the objective evaluation*, not post-hoc. CMA-ES sees the corrected E2E and optimizes around it, avoiding the R3 H3 double-counting issue.\n    32→4. **Per-model optimization:** Same as R3 — separate CMA-ES run per model group.\n    33→5. **Pareto sweep:** Run with multiple α values (0.7, 0.5, 0.3) to explore the Pareto frontier, then select the knee point.\n    34→\n    35→### Expected Outcome\n    36→\n    37→E2E < 12% mean with ITL < 20% mean, with at least 6/10 experiments below 10% E2E. The constraint prevents the catastrophic ITL degradation seen in R3.\n    38→\n    39→### Go Integration Path\n    40→\n    41→Coefficient export — same StepML JSON artifact format as R3. No new Go code needed.\n    42→\n    43→### LatencyModel Methods Targeted\n    44→\n    45→All 5 methods via CMA-ES parameter tuning: StepTime (regime coefficients + overhead floor), QueueingTime (TTFT corrections), OutputTokenProcessingTime, SchedulingProcessingTime, PreemptionProcessingTime.\n    46→\n    47→### Generalization Plans\n    48→\n    49→#### LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n    50→Same protocol as R3 H5: train CMA-ES on 3 models, apply artifact to held-out 4th. R3 showed 14.8% LOMO E2E — the constrained version should maintain or improve this since the constraints prevent overfitting to simulation artifacts. Model features enabling transfer: overhead floor values scale with model size/TP, regime coefficients capture batch-composition physics.\n    51→\n    52→#### LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n    53→R3 showed 8/10 within 2× aggregate for LOWO. Re-run with constrained CMA-ES and verify workload variance doesn't increase. Dense models (70B, 34B) showed 9-16pp range — target ≤20pp with constrained optimization.\n    54→\n    55→#### vLLM Args Sensitivity Analysis\n    56→\n    57→| Parameter | Dependent? | Would predictions break? | Recalibration needed |\n    58→|---|---|---|---|\n    59→| `max_num_seqs` (128) | **Yes** — controls batch size distribution → affects overhead floor regime | Overhead floor would be wrong for different batch size regime | Re-optimize `step_overhead_us` only (~5 min CMA-ES) |\n    60→| `max_num_batched_tokens` (2048) | **Yes** — controls chunked prefill budget → changes mixed-batch frequency | Regime boundaries (prefill=0 threshold) might shift | Re-optimize regime coefficients (~15 min CMA-ES) |\n    61→| `max_model_len` (4096) | **Weak** — changes KV capacity → may shift batch sizes under pressure | Predictions stable unless KV pressure forces evictions | None for moderate changes; re-optimize for >2× change |\n    62→| `chunked_prefill` (on) | **Strong** — fundamentally changes batch composition | Model assumes mixed batches; pure-prefill regime doesn't exist in training data | Full retrain required |\n    63→| `prefix_caching` (on) | **Moderate** — changes effective prefill tokens | Prefill regime coefficients would over-predict | Re-optimize prefill regime coefficients only |\n    64→| `gpu_memory_utilization` (0.9) | **Weak** — changes KV capacity | Same as max_model_len: only matters under extreme memory pressure | None for ≥0.7; re-optimize for <0.5 |\n    65→| `tensor_parallel_size` (varies) | **Strong** — changes per-GPU compute/memory | Overhead floor and all coefficients change | Full retrain for new TP degree |\n    66→\n    67→**Recalibration story:** CMA-ES re-optimization for a single parameter change takes ~5-15 minutes (50-100 evaluations). For `chunked_prefill` or `TP` changes, full retrain (~30 min/model) is required. This is acceptable for production: new serving configs are deployed infrequently and calibration is automated.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## Idea 2: Principled Overhead Floor Calibration via Cycle-Time Regression\n    72→\n    73→### Title\n    74→Data-Driven Step Cycle Time Model with Explicit CPU Overhead Separation\n    75→\n    76→### Rationale\n    77→\n    78→**Directly addresses BC-NEW-2 (step cycle under-prediction) and the root cause of BC-NEW-1.** The \"faster universe\" problem (BLIS at ~40% real speed) exists because:\n    79→1. `step.duration_us` in training data captures GPU forward pass only (~70–7,000μs)\n    80→2. Real step cycle time = GPU forward pass + CPU overhead (scheduling, sync, memory management)\n    81→3. The overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`) is a heuristic — its value was hand-tuned from ITL residuals, not derived from the data itself\n    82→\n    83→**Literature grounding:** AIConfigurator [2026] achieves 7.8% TPOT MAPE by decomposing iteration time into profiled operator primitives and summing them. Vidur [Agrawal et al., 2024] achieves <5% P95 error with operator-level RF models. FairBatching [Patel et al., 2025] achieves ±1.3% with continuous calibration of `a + b*new_tokens + c*total_context`. The common thread: **model what you measure, then add overhead separately**.\n    84→\n    85→**Codebase grounding:** Examining `sim/latency/stepml.go:232-268`, the overhead is applied as `max(overhead, compute)` with a hard cap at 3×overhead. The overhead constant comes from R2's manual calibration (ground-truth ITL - mean compute). Instead, we should derive the overhead from the *ground-truth step cycle times* directly.\n    86→\n    87→**Key insight:** We have per-request lifecycle data with per-token timestamps. The inter-token interval (ITI) between consecutive output tokens of the same request represents the actual step cycle time that request experienced. By regressing ITI against batch composition features, we can build a **cycle time model** that inherently includes CPU overhead — no separate overhead floor needed.\n    88→\n    89→**Why it differs from prior rounds:** R1-R3 all modeled `step.duration_us` (GPU forward pass) and added overhead as a post-hoc floor. This idea models the **actual cycle time** (ITI from lifecycle data), which naturally includes all overhead. The overhead floor becomes unnecessary if the cycle time model is accurate.\n    90→\n    91→### Method Sketch\n    92→\n    93→1. **Extract per-step cycle times from lifecycle data:** For each request's output tokens, compute ITI = timestamp[i+1] - timestamp[i]. These represent real step cycle times.\n    94→2. **Join cycle times with step-level batch features:** Match lifecycle timestamps to step windows to assign batch composition features (prefill_tokens, decode_tokens, kv_sum) to each cycle time.\n    95→3. **Train per-model FairBatching-style regression on cycle times:** `cycle_time = a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum` where the target is ITI (real cycle time), not step.duration_us (GPU-only). The intercept `a` naturally absorbs CPU overhead.\n    96→4. **Regime separation:** Decode-only (prefill=0) gets its own model where `a_decode` represents the full cycle overhead; mixed batches get `a_mixed + b*prefill + c*decode + d*kv_sum`.\n    97→5. **BLIS integration:** Export coefficients to StepML artifact. The overhead floor is set to `a_decode` (the regression intercept for decode-only steps), which is data-derived rather than hand-tuned. No cap needed since the model already predicts cycle time, not compute time.\n    98→6. **Combine with TTFT additive corrections:** Apply per-model TTFT corrections from R3 H3 (16–61ms) directly in the artifact's QueueingTime model.\n    99→\n   100→### Expected Outcome\n   101→\n   102→By modeling the *right target variable* (cycle time vs GPU-only time), the \"faster universe\" problem should largely disappear. Target: E2E < 15% with ITL < 15% (both without CMA-ES). If successful, CMA-ES can be applied on top for further E2E refinement without the E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff (since the baseline is already correctly calibrated).\n   103→\n   104→### Go Integration Path\n   105→\n   106→Coefficient export — same StepML JSON artifact format. The key difference is the overhead floor value changes (data-derived vs hand-tuned), and the regression targets cycle time instead of compute time.\n   107→\n   108→### LatencyModel Methods Targeted\n   109→\n   110→StepTime (primary — cycle time regression), QueueingTime (TTFT corrections). OutputTokenProcessingTime set to 0 (absorbed into cycle time model). SchedulingProcessingTime and PreemptionProcessingTime remain 0 (absorbed into intercept).\n   111→\n   112→### Generalization Plans\n   113→\n   114→#### LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n   115→4-fold LOMO on cycle time regression. Since the intercept `a` absorbs per-model CPU overhead, cross-model transfer depends on whether overhead scales predictably with model size/TP. Expected: intercept scales roughly with model parameter count (more parameters → more memory management overhead). Target: LOMO per-step MAPE < 80%.\n   116→\n   117→#### LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n   118→3-fold LOWO. The FairBatching formulation (`new_tokens + kv_sum`) captures workload-invariant compute physics — workload differences affect only the *distribution* of these features, not the *relationship* between features and cycle time. Expected: LOWO per-step MAPE < 50%.\n   119→\n   120→#### vLLM Args Sensitivity Analysis\n   121→\n   122→| Parameter | Dependent? | Would predictions break? | Recalibration needed |\n   123→|---|---|---|---|\n   124→| `max_num_seqs` (128) | **Moderate** — affects batch size distribution but regression captures the relationship | Predictions shift within trained range | None if batch sizes stay within training range; retrain for >2× change |\n   125→| `max_num_batched_tokens` (2048) | **Moderate** — changes mixed-batch frequency | Regime proportions shift, but per-regime models are independent | None for moderate changes |\n   126→| `max_model_len` (4096) | **Weak** — KV capacity affects eviction, not step time | No impact on cycle time model | None |\n   127→| `chunked_prefill` (on) | **Strong** — model trained on chunked-prefill data exclusively | Without chunked prefill, pure-prefill steps would appear; model has no data for these | Full retrain (need data with chunked_prefill=off) |\n   128→| `prefix_caching` (on) | **Moderate** — affects effective prefill tokens | Prefill coefficient might over-predict; but cycle time intercept still anchors predictions | Retrain prefill regime coefficients |\n   129→| `gpu_memory_utilization` (0.9) | **Weak** — no direct effect on cycle time per step | No impact | None |\n   130→| `tensor_parallel_size` (varies) | **Strong** — changes GPU communication overhead → changes intercept | Cycle time intercept (CPU overhead) changes with TP | Full retrain for new TP |\n   131→\n   132→**Recalibration story:** The formulation is structurally robust because it models *measured cycle time*, not derived quantities. For TP or chunked_prefill changes, collect ~1000 steps of profiling data and retrain (OLS, <1 second). The key advantage over CMA-ES: recalibration requires only step-level data, not full BLIS simulation runs.\n   133→\n   134→---\n   135→\n   136→## Idea 3: Hybrid Cycle-Time CMA-ES — Principled Base + Black-Box Residual\n   137→\n   138→### Title\n   139→Two-Stage Calibration: Data-Derived Cycle-Time Base + Constrained CMA-ES Residual Tuning\n   140→\n   141→### Rationale\n   142→\n   143→**Combines the strengths of Ideas 1 and 2 to address all binding constraints simultaneously.** The E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff (BC-NEW-1) arises because CMA-ES compensates for a poorly calibrated base model by distorting secondary coefficients. If the base model already runs at the correct speed (Idea 2 fixes BC-NEW-2), CMA-ES only needs to make *small residual adjustments* rather than large compensatory distortions.\n   144→\n   145→**Literature grounding:** Hybrid approaches combining physics-informed base models with learned residual corrections are standard in scientific simulation calibration [Kennedy & O'Hagan, 2001]. Revati [2025] uses Vidur's analytical models enhanced with profiling for <5% error. The principle: **start with a principled model, then calibrate residuals**.\n   146→\n   147→**Key insight from R3:** CMA-ES inflated `output_token_processing_time_us` to 1,899μs (llama-2-7b) because the base model under-predicted step cycle time by ~2×. If the base model is already correct (via cycle-time regression from Idea 2), CMA-ES's search space shrinks dramatically and the E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff softens.\n   148→\n   149→**Why it differs from prior approaches:** R3 Idea 3 applied CMA-ES to a poorly calibrated base (overhead floor from R2 hand-tuning). This idea first establishes a principled cycle-time base (Idea 2), then applies *tightly constrained* CMA-ES to fine-tune residuals. The two-stage approach means CMA-ES corrections are ≤20% of base values rather than ≥100%.\n   150→\n   151→### Method Sketch\n   152→\n   153→1. **Stage 1 — Principled base (from Idea 2):**\n   154→   - Train per-model cycle-time regression on ITI (inter-token interval) from lifecycle data\n   155→   - Derive overhead floor from regression intercept\n   156→   - Apply TTFT additive corrections from R3 H3\n   157→   - Evaluate BLIS E2E and ITL → this is the \"principled base\" result\n   158→\n   159→2. **Stage 2 — Constrained CMA-ES residual tuning:**\n   160→   - Starting point: Idea 2's principled coefficients\n   161→   - **Tight bounds:** Each parameter bounded within ±20% of Stage 1 value (not the ±200% that R3 effectively allowed)\n   162→   - **Dual-objective penalty:** `objective = 0.5 * mean_e2e_error + 0.5 * mean_itl_error + λ * constraint_violations`\n   163→   - **Hard constraints:** `output_token_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 200]`, `step_overhead_us ∈ [base ± 15%]`\n   164→   - **Fewer evaluations:** Since the starting point is already good, CMA-ES converges faster (~50-80 evaluations vs 96-152 in R3)\n   165→\n   166→3. **Fallback logic:** If CMA-ES Stage 2 worsens ITL by >5pp relative to Stage 1, discard CMA-ES results and use Stage 1 directly. This provides a safety net.\n   167→\n   168→### Expected Outcome\n   169→\n   170→Stage 1 alone: E2E ~20-25% with ITL ~12-15% (correctly calibrated base).\n   171→After Stage 2: E2E < 10% with ITL < 15% for ≥7/10 experiments. The tight bounds prevent CMA-ES from distorting the principled base.\n   172→\n   173→### Go Integration Path\n   174→\n   175→Coefficient export — same StepML JSON artifact format. Stage 2 produces the final artifact.\n   176→\n   177→### LatencyModel Methods Targeted\n   178→\n   179→All 5 methods:\n   180→- StepTime: Cycle-time regression (Stage 1) + residual tuning (Stage 2)\n   181→- QueueingTime: TTFT additive corrections (Stage 1) + fine-tuning (Stage 2)\n   182→- OutputTokenProcessingTime: Data-derived (Stage 1, ≤200μs) + bounded tuning (Stage 2)\n   183→- SchedulingProcessingTime: Small constant (Stage 1) + bounded tuning (Stage 2)\n   184→- PreemptionProcessingTime: Remains 0 (negligible in training data)\n   185→\n   186→### Generalization Plans\n   187→\n   188→#### LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out)\n   189→Two-level LOMO test:\n   190→- **Stage 1 LOMO:** Train cycle-time regression on 3 models, predict 4th. Target: <80% per-step MAPE.\n   191→- **Stage 2 LOMO:** Apply CMA-ES artifacts (trained on 3 models) to held-out 4th via cross-model transfer. R3 showed 14.8% LOMO E2E — with a better base model, this should improve or maintain.\n   192→- **Combined LOMO:** The principled base provides structure; CMA-ES residuals provide per-model fine-tuning. For a truly new model, Stage 1 (cycle-time regression with lifecycle data) is all that's needed — CMA-ES Stage 2 is optional polish.\n   193→\n   194→#### LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out)\n   195→3-fold LOWO on both stages. The cycle-time regression (Stage 1) is workload-invariant by construction (models batch-composition → cycle-time physics). CMA-ES residuals (Stage 2) are trained across all workloads per model, so they average workload effects. Target: <50% per-step MAPE for Stage 1; <30% E2E for combined.\n   196→\n   197→#### vLLM Args Sensitivity Analysis\n   198→\n   199→| Parameter | Dependent? | Would predictions break? | Recalibration needed |\n   200→|---|---|---|---|\n   201→| `max_num_seqs` (128) | **Moderate** — Stage 1 captures batch-level physics; Stage 2 residuals are small | Stage 1 robust within training range; Stage 2 residuals may be slightly wrong | Re-run Stage 2 CMA-ES only (~10 min) |\n   202→| `max_num_batched_tokens` (2048) | **Moderate** — affects mixed-batch frequency | Stage 1 regime boundaries may shift | Re-estimate regime thresholds from new data; Stage 2 optional |\n   203→| `max_model_len` (4096) | **Weak** — no direct impact on per-step cycle time | Stable | None |\n   204→| `chunked_prefill` (on) | **Strong** — both stages trained on chunked-prefill data | Without it, pure-prefill regime appears; Stage 1 has no data | Full retrain of Stage 1; Stage 2 optional re-run |\n   205→| `prefix_caching` (on) | **Moderate** — affects effective prefill tokens | Stage 1 prefill coefficients may over-predict | Retrain Stage 1 prefill regime; Stage 2 absorbs residual |\n   206→| `gpu_memory_utilization` (0.9) | **Weak** — no direct impact | Stable | None |\n   207→| `tensor_parallel_size` (varies) | **Strong** — changes communication overhead → Stage 1 intercept | Both stages wrong for new TP | Full retrain of both stages |\n   208→\n   209→**Recalibration story:** Two-level: (1) Stage 1 recalibration requires only ~1000 steps of profiling data + OLS fit (<1 second). (2) Stage 2 requires ~50 BLIS runs (~10 minutes). For routine changes (new max_num_seqs), only Stage 2 needs re-running. For fundamental changes (new TP, chunked_prefill off), both stages retrain from scratch. Total: ~35 minutes max, fully automated.\n   210→\n   211→---\n   212→\n   213→## Summary: How Ideas Address Binding Constraints\n   214→\n   215→| Constraint | Idea 1 (Constrained CMA-ES) | Idea 2 (Cycle-Time Regression) | Idea 3 (Hybrid) |\n   216→|---|---|---|---|\n   217→| **BC-NEW-1: E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff** | ITL penalty + parameter bounds | Eliminated at source (cycle-time model) | Both: principled base + bounded CMA-ES |\n   218→| **BC-NEW-2: Step cycle under-prediction** | Indirectly via overhead tuning | Directly (model cycle time, not compute time) | Directly via Stage 1 |\n   219→| **BC-6: vLLM args sensitivity** | Analyzed above | Analyzed above | Analyzed above |\n   220→| **BC-4: Mixtral MoE variance** | Better via constrained optimization | Uncertain (linear model may not capture MoE) | Best chance: Stage 1 + MoE-aware Stage 2 |\n   221→| **BC-5: LOMO generalization** | Inherits R3's 14.8% LOMO E2E | New — cycle time LOMO | Two-level LOMO |\n   222→\n   223→## Distinctiveness of Ideas\n   224→\n   225→- **Idea 1** improves the *optimization* (multi-objective + constraints) while keeping the same base model\n   226→- **Idea 2** improves the *base model* (cycle time target) without black-box optimization\n   227→- **Idea 3** combines both — principled base + constrained optimization\n   228→\n   229→All three are distinct and attack different aspects of the problem. Idea 3 subsumes Ideas 1 and 2, but testing them independently reveals which component contributes most.\n   230→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"52c97aff-04c0-4de8-af0b-20db72f02dae"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01BWggJWx2St4ZQnfVxgPijk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Round 1: Findings Summary\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Purpose:** Comprehensive summary of all Round 1 experiments to inform future rounds of ideation and testing.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 1. Problem Recap\n    10→\n    11→Replace BLIS's 3-coefficient blackbox latency model (`step_time = beta0 + beta1*prefill_tokens + beta2*decode_tokens`) with a data-driven predictor achieving **<10% workload-level E2E mean error** across 16 experiments (4 models × 4 workloads, H100 GPUs). The winning model must integrate into BLIS as a Go `LatencyModel` implementation.\n    12→\n    13→**Data:** 122,752 step-level observations from instrumented vLLM v0.15.1 with OpenTelemetry tracing (10% sample rate).\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## 2. What We Tried\n    18→\n    19→### Idea 1: Physics-Informed Tree Ensemble\n    20→\n    21→**Approach:** Engineer 30 physics-informed features from batch composition and architecture parameters, train XGBoost per-experiment.\n    22→\n    23→| Sub-Hypothesis | Result | Key Number |\n    24→|---|---|---|\n    25→| h1: 30 features + Ridge | Weakly Supported (per-exp) | 92.1% avg MAPE per-exp; global 301.7% short-circuited |\n    26→| h2: XGBoost per-experiment | **Weakly Supported** | **34.0% avg MAPE** (2x better than blackbox 70.4%) |\n    27→| h3: Cross-config generalization | Not Supported | LOMO 2559.7%, LOWO 109.7% |\n    28→\n    29→### Idea 2: Analytical Decomposition + Learned Corrections\n    30→\n    31→**Approach:** Decompose step time into 4 analytical FLOPs components (prefill GEMM, prefill attention, decode GEMM, decode attention), then learn multiplicative correction factors.\n    32→\n    33→| Sub-Hypothesis | Result | Key Number |\n    34→|---|---|---|\n    35→| h1: Component correlation | Not Supported | 0/4 components > 0.8 Pearson r |\n    36→| h2: Correction factors | Not Supported | 78.7% avg MAPE (worse than blackbox 70.4%) |\n    37→\n    38→### Idea 3: Evolutionary Synthesis (OpenEvolve)\n    39→\n    40→**Status:** Deferred — h2 depends on Idea 2's analytical components (which are structurally incomplete), and OpenEvolve infrastructure was not set up.\n    41→\n    42→---\n    43→\n    44→## 3. What Worked\n    45→\n    46→### 3.1 Per-Experiment XGBoost (Best Result)\n    47→\n    48→XGBoost with 30 physics-informed features, trained separately per experiment:\n    49→- **Average MAPE: 34.0%** (vs blackbox 70.4%) — **2x improvement**\n    50→- **5/16 experiments < 15% MAPE**, 9/16 < 30%\n    51→- **Zero regressions** — beats or matches blackbox on all 16 experiments\n    52→- Biggest wins: reasoning workloads (Llama-7B-reasoning: 123.5% → 13.0%, Mixtral-reasoning: 222.8% → 62.4%)\n    53→\n    54→**Full per-experiment leaderboard (XGBoost vs Blackbox):**\n    55→\n    56→| Model | Workload | XGB MAPE | BB MAPE | Improvement |\n    57→|-------|----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n    58→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 9.1% | 9.2% | +0.1 pp |\n    59→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 9.8% | 14.2% | +4.4 pp |\n    60→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 13.0% | 123.5% | +110.5 pp |\n    61→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 14.0% | 37.3% | +23.3 pp |\n    62→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 14.7% | 19.0% | +4.3 pp |\n    63→| codellama-34b | codegen | 16.1% | 21.6% | +5.5 pp |\n    64→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 25.7% | 30.8% | +5.1 pp |\n    65→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 28.3% | 33.6% | +5.3 pp |\n    66→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 28.3% | 128.6% | +100.2 pp |\n    67→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 30.9% | 40.3% | +9.4 pp |\n    68→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 31.1% | 90.8% | +59.7 pp |\n    69→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 33.4% | 69.7% | +36.3 pp |\n    70→| llama-2-7b | general | 50.9% | 72.9% | +22.0 pp |\n    71→| llama-2-70b | general | 55.4% | 61.2% | +5.7 pp |\n    72→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 62.4% | 222.8% | +160.5 pp |\n    73→| codellama-34b | general | 121.5% | 151.1% | +29.6 pp |\n    74→\n    75→### 3.2 Feature Engineering Insights\n    76→\n    77→The 30 features in 6 groups provided clear value over the 2-feature blackbox. Most informative features by XGBoost importance:\n    78→\n    79→| Rank | Feature | Description | Why It Helps |\n    80→|------|---------|-------------|-------------|\n    81→| 1 | `f_kv_blocks_used` | GPU KV cache blocks occupied | Best available proxy for total context length across all running requests |\n    82→| 2 | `f_decode_tokens` | Decode tokens in batch | Core batch computation feature (already in blackbox) |\n    83→| 3 | `f_running_depth` | Number of running requests | Proxy for batch complexity and attention fan-out |\n    84→| 4 | `f_prefill_tokens` | Prefill tokens in batch | Core batch computation feature (already in blackbox) |\n    85→| 5 | `f_num_decode_reqs` | Decode request count | Captures batch shape vs just token count |\n    86→| 6 | `f_total_flops_estimate` | Analytical FLOPs estimate | Physics-informed feature — strong for Mixtral |\n    87→| 7 | `f_prefill_x_decode` | Interaction: prefill × decode | Captures non-additive mixed-batch overhead |\n    88→| 8 | `f_decode_memory_intensity` | Memory bytes / decode FLOPs | Compute vs memory bound indicator |\n    89→| 9 | `f_batch_size_x_kv_pressure` | Interaction: batch_size × kv_max | Attention memory pressure |\n    90→| 10 | `f_kv_blocks_free` | Free GPU KV cache blocks | Inverse proxy for system load |\n    91→\n    92→**Key observation:** The top features are dominated by **KV cache state proxies** (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`, `kv_blocks_free`) rather than physics features. The model is learning to predict step time from system state because per-request KV information is missing.\n    93→\n    94→### 3.3 Analytical Decomposition Has Signal Where GEMM Dominates\n    95→\n    96→Per-experiment correlation of total analytical FLOPs estimate with step duration:\n    97→\n    98→| Correlation Range | Workload Type | Example |\n    99→|---|---|---|\n   100→| r > 0.85 | General (GEMM-dominated) | Mixtral-general r=0.94, Llama-7B-general r=0.86 |\n   101→| r = 0.35–0.65 | Codegen (mixed) | CodeLlama-codegen r=0.43 |\n   102→| r < 0.25 | Reasoning/roleplay (attention-dominated) | Mixtral-reasoning r=0.02, Llama-7B-reasoning r=0.12 |\n   103→\n   104→The physics is correct where GEMM dominates — but attention cost (which depends on per-request KV lengths) is the dominant component for reasoning/roleplay workloads.\n   105→\n   106→---\n   107→\n   108→## 4. What Failed and Why\n   109→\n   110→### 4.1 Global Models (Catastrophic Failure)\n   111→\n   112→Any model trained across all 16 experiments fails catastrophically:\n   113→- **Global Ridge 30f:** 301.7% MAPE\n   114→- **Global blackbox:** 670% MAPE\n   115→\n   116→**Root cause:** Step times span 3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations:\n   117→- Llama-2-7B (tp=1): 12–500 μs per step\n   118→- Llama-2-70B (tp=4): 500–250,000 μs per step\n   119→\n   120→A single model cannot fit both scales. Per-experiment (or per-model) training is mandatory.\n   121→\n   122→### 4.2 Cross-Model Generalization (Structural Failure)\n   123→\n   124→LOMO (Leave-One-Model-Out) XGBoost:\n   125→\n   126→| Holdout Model | Test MAPE | Why |\n   127→|---|---|---|\n   128→| llama-2-7b | **9908%** | tp=1 model with μs-scale steps; trained on tp=2/4 models with ms-scale steps |\n   129→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 186.6% | MoE architecture fundamentally different from dense training models |\n   130→| codellama-34b | 78.9% | Less extreme but still 5x worse than per-experiment |\n   131→| llama-2-70b | 65.5% | Closest to training distribution (similar scale) |\n   132→\n   133→**Root cause:** Features encode absolute values (FLOPs, KV blocks) that scale with model size. Architecture metadata (`model_id`, `tp_degree`, `is_moe`) is insufficient to bridge the scale gap. This is **not a model capacity issue** — it's a representation issue.\n   134→\n   135→### 4.3 Cross-Workload Generalization (Moderate Failure)\n   136→\n   137→LOWO (Leave-One-Workload-Out) XGBoost:\n   138→\n   139→| Holdout Workload | Test MAPE | Why |\n   140→|---|---|---|\n   141→| roleplay | 30.6% | Similar batch patterns to codegen — some transfer |\n   142→| codegen | 53.4% | Moderate transfer from other workloads |\n   143→| reasoning | 53.2% | Long contexts not well represented in other workloads |\n   144→| general | **301.6%** | Most diverse batch compositions — unpredictable from other workloads |\n   145→\n   146→**Root cause:** Less severe than LOMO because same model config → same step time scale. Failures concentrate in \"general\" workloads (most diverse batch compositions) and \"reasoning\" (long contexts with extreme KV lengths).\n   147→\n   148→### 4.4 Analytical Decomposition (Structural Incompleteness)\n   149→\n   150→The 4-component FLOPs decomposition fails because:\n   151→\n   152→1. **decode_attention_flops = 0** for all steps. Per-request KV cache lengths (`ProgressIndex`) are unavailable in step-level data. Decode attention is the dominant cost for 80.6% of steps (pure decode), making the decomposition structurally incomplete.\n   153→\n   154→2. **Only 6 pure-prefill steps** exist (out of 122,752). vLLM's chunked prefill makes nearly every batch mixed. The experimental design assumed large pure-phase subsets for correlation analysis — this assumption was wrong.\n   155→\n   156→3. **Correction factors compensate pathologically:** The optimizer set `decode_attn_factor = 39.5` trying to amplify a zero signal. The 36-parameter model (78.7% MAPE) actually performed **worse than the 3-parameter blackbox** (70.4%) because the analytical backbone with missing attention is less informative than raw `decode_tokens`.\n   157→\n   158→### 4.5 \"General\" Workloads Are Consistently Hardest\n   159→\n   160→Across all models and approaches, the 4 \"general\" workload experiments are the worst:\n   161→\n   162→| Model | General MAPE (XGB) | Next-Worst MAPE (XGB) |\n   163→|-------|--------------------|-----------------------|\n   164→| codellama-34b | **121.5%** | 25.7% (roleplay) |\n   165→| llama-2-70b | **55.4%** | 28.3% (roleplay) |\n   166→| llama-2-7b | **50.9%** | 30.9% (roleplay) |\n   167→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 9.1% (exception — Mixtral-general is easy) | 28.3% (roleplay) |\n   168→\n   169→**Root cause:** \"General\" workloads have the most diverse batch compositions — mixing short decode-only batches with occasional large prefill+decode batches. High step time variance within a single experiment makes prediction difficult even with 30 features.\n   170→\n   171→---\n   172→\n   173→## 5. Binding Constraints (What Blocks Further Progress)\n   174→\n   175→### 5.1 Missing Per-Request KV Cache Lengths (PRIMARY)\n   176→\n   177→The single most impactful limitation. The step-level training data contains only aggregate batch features (`batch.prefill_tokens`, `batch.decode_tokens`), not per-request KV cache lengths.\n   178→\n   179→**Impact on each approach:**\n   180→- **XGBoost:** Uses system-state proxies (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`) instead of per-request statistics (`kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`). These proxies capture occupancy but not per-request distribution. Two batches with identical total KV blocks but different per-request distributions (many short vs few long) have very different attention costs.\n   181→- **Analytical decomposition:** Decode attention FLOPs are literally uncomputable. This makes the decomposition incomplete for the dominant cost component.\n   182→- **Feature importance confirms it:** XGBoost's top features are all KV state proxies — the model is begging for better KV information.\n   183→\n   184→**Available in simulator:** BLIS's `LatencyModel.StepTime()` receives `[]*Request`, each with `ProgressIndex` (cumulative input_processed + output_generated). This is the per-request KV cache length proxy. It's available at prediction time but was NOT available in the training data.\n   185→\n   186→**Possible solutions for Round 2:**\n   187→1. Re-instrument vLLM to export per-request KV lengths in step-level traces\n   188→2. Derive approximate per-request KV lengths from per-request lifecycle data (already available in `request_metrics/`)\n   189→3. Design features that work without per-request KV (the approach we took, but with a ceiling)\n   190→\n   191→### 5.2 Step Time Scale Variation (SECONDARY)\n   192→\n   193→3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations. Forces per-model training. Not addressable without normalized/relative features.\n   194→\n   195→**Possible solutions for Round 2:**\n   196→1. **Log-scale prediction:** Predict `log(step_time)` instead of `step_time` — compresses the range\n   197→2. **Normalized features:** Divide FLOPs by model-specific capacity (peak_flops × tp_degree) to produce utilization features that are scale-independent\n   198→3. **Relative prediction:** Predict `step_time / baseline_step_time` where baseline is a reference batch configuration\n   199→4. **Hierarchical models:** Model-specific first stage (captures scale) + shared second stage (captures batch composition effects)\n   200→\n   201→### 5.3 Hyperparameter Underfitting (TERTIARY)\n   202→\n   203→XGBoost consistently selected shallow trees (max_depth=4, n_estimators=100) for 13/16 experiments. This suggests the model is **underfitting, not overfitting** — more expressive features would help more than deeper trees. The feature set, not the model capacity, is the bottleneck.\n   204→\n   205→---\n   206→\n   207→## 6. Data Characteristics Learned\n   208→\n   209→### 6.1 Phase Distribution\n   210→\n   211→| Phase | Steps | % of Total |\n   212→|-------|-------|-----------|\n   213→| Pure decode (prefill_tokens = 0) | 98,961 | 80.6% |\n   214→| Mixed batch (prefill + decode) | 23,789 | 19.4% |\n   215→| Pure prefill (decode_tokens = 0) | 6 | 0.005% |\n   216→\n   217→**Implication:** vLLM's chunked prefill makes nearly every batch mixed or pure-decode. Experimental designs assuming large pure-prefill subsets (like Idea 2) are invalid. Any step-time model must primarily handle decode-dominated and mixed batches.\n   218→\n   219→### 6.2 Step Time Distribution by Workload Type\n   220→\n   221→| Workload | Mean Duration | Median Duration | Std Dev | Coefficient of Variation |\n   222→|----------|--------------|-----------------|---------|------------------------|\n   223→| reasoning | 6,000–33,500 μs | High variance | Very high | >1.0 (bimodal) |\n   224→| general | 200–2,000 μs | Moderate | High | >0.8 |\n   225→| codegen | 160–320 μs | Low | Low-moderate | 0.3–0.6 |\n   226→| roleplay | 160–320 μs | Low | Low-moderate | 0.3–0.6 |\n   227→\n   228→**Implication:** Reasoning workloads have extremely high variance and bimodal distributions (long prefills interspersed with short decodes). This drives high MAPE even for models that capture the mean well.\n   229→\n   230→### 6.3 Feature Correlation Structure\n   231→\n   232→- `batch.prefill_tokens` and `batch.decode_tokens` are weakly correlated (r ≈ 0.1–0.3) — they provide mostly independent information\n   233→- `kv_blocks_used` and `running_depth` are moderately correlated (r ≈ 0.4–0.7) — both capture system load\n   234→- Physics features (`total_flops_estimate`, `arithmetic_intensity`) are highly correlated with `prefill_tokens` on prefill-heavy workloads but nearly orthogonal on decode-heavy workloads\n   235→- Interaction terms (`prefill_x_decode`, `batch_size_x_kv_pressure`) add unique variance that individual features don't capture\n   236→\n   237→### 6.4 Experiments Per Model\n   238→\n   239→| Model | TP | Steps | Avg Step Time | Experiments |\n   240→|-------|-----|-------|---------------|-------------|\n   241→| llama-2-7b | 1 | 47,034 | ~160–5,000 μs | 4 |\n   242→| llama-2-70b / 70b-hf | 4 | 23,860 | ~500–33,500 μs | 4 |\n   243→| codellama-34b | 2 | 29,094 | ~200–6,000 μs | 4 |\n   244→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 2 | 22,764 | ~160–8,000 μs | 4 |\n   245→\n   246→**Implication:** Llama-7B has the most steps (47K) — heavily represented. Data is not balanced across models.\n   247→\n   248→---\n   249→\n   250→## 7. Successful Techniques and Patterns\n   251→\n   252→### 7.1 Temporal Train/Test Split\n   253→\n   254→The 60/20/20 temporal split (earlier steps for training, later for testing) prevents autocorrelation leakage. This is critical because consecutive steps share system state (KV cache occupancy, queue depth) which could inflate accuracy artificially.\n   255→\n   256→### 7.2 Per-Experiment Training\n   257→\n   258→The only viable approach — step time scale varies 3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations. All production inference simulators (Vidur, Splitwise) use per-model calibration.\n   259→\n   260→### 7.3 System-State KV Proxies\n   261→\n   262→While imperfect, `kv_blocks_used`, `kv_blocks_free`, and `running_depth` provide meaningful signal about KV cache pressure. They correlate with step time because they capture total context length indirectly. However, they cannot distinguish per-request KV distribution.\n   263→\n   264→### 7.4 Physics-Informed Interaction Terms\n   265→\n   266→`prefill_x_decode` (prefill_tokens × decode_tokens) and `batch_size_x_kv_pressure` (batch_size × kv_max) capture non-additive mixed-batch effects that individual features miss. These were among the top 10 features for several experiments.\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## 8. Failed Techniques and Anti-Patterns\n   271→\n   272→### 8.1 Global Models\n   273→\n   274→Any model trained across all experiments fails catastrophically due to step time scale variation. Do not attempt global training without scale normalization.\n   275→\n   276→### 8.2 Analytical Decomposition Without Per-Request KV\n   277→\n   278→The 4-component FLOPs decomposition is physically correct but computationally incomplete without per-request KV lengths. The `decode_attention = 0` problem makes the decomposition worse than the simple blackbox.\n   279→\n   280→### 8.3 Correction Factors on Incomplete Backbone\n   281→\n   282→Learned multiplicative corrections cannot fix a structurally incomplete model. The optimizer compensates pathologically (factor=39.5 on zero signal). If the backbone is missing a component, add the component — don't amplify the existing ones.\n   283→\n   284→### 8.4 Pure-Phase Analysis with Chunked Prefill\n   285→\n   286→vLLM's chunked prefill produces only 6 pure-prefill steps. Experimental designs relying on pure-phase subsets are invalid under continuous batching with chunked prefill.\n   287→\n   288→---\n   289→\n   290→## 9. Open Questions for Round 2\n   291→\n   292→### 9.1 Can Per-Request KV Features Close the Gap?\n   293→\n   294→The `ProgressIndex` field is available per-request in the BLIS simulator. If we can either:\n   295→- (a) Derive per-request KV lengths from the per-request lifecycle data in `eval/ground_truth/*/request_metrics/`, or\n   296→- (b) Extend the training data to include per-request KV lengths\n   297→\n   298→...then both XGBoost and the analytical decomposition should improve substantially. The feature importance analysis shows the model is bottlenecked by KV information quality.\n   299→\n   300→### 9.2 Can Log-Scale or Normalized Prediction Enable Cross-Model Models?\n   301→\n   302→Per-model training works but requires N separate calibration runs. If features were normalized to model-specific capacity (e.g., FLOPs / peak_throughput, step_time / reference_step_time), a single model might generalize across configurations.\n   303→\n   304→### 9.3 Is Per-Step MAPE the Right Diagnostic?\n   305→\n   306→The primary metric is workload-level E2E mean error (not per-step MAPE). Per-step errors may cancel in aggregate. The 34% per-step MAPE might translate to <10% E2E mean error if errors are symmetric. This was NOT tested in Round 1. Round 2 should include BLIS E2E validation.\n   307→\n   308→### 9.4 Would More Training Data Help?\n   309→\n   310→Current per-experiment training sizes are 2,000–9,000 steps. The consistently shallow XGBoost trees suggest underfitting due to insufficient features, not insufficient data. But more diverse batch compositions (especially for \"general\" workloads) might help.\n   311→\n   312→### 9.5 Can We Leverage the Per-Request Lifecycle Data?\n   313→\n   314→The `eval/ground_truth/*/request_metrics/` directories contain per-token timestamps, input/output token counts, and E2E latencies. This data could:\n   315→- Derive approximate per-request KV lengths (ProgressIndex at each step)\n   316→- Enable workload-level E2E validation (compare predicted vs observed per-request E2E)\n   317→- Provide TTFT/ITL breakdown for Priority 2 metrics\n   318→\n   319→### 9.6 What About Simpler Models with Better Features?\n   320→\n   321→XGBoost with 30 features beats Ridge with 30 features by 2.7x (34% vs 92% avg MAPE). But the 30 features include several that are imprecise (KV proxies) or constant (attention ratios set to 0/1). A smaller set of high-quality features might enable simpler models (e.g., Ridge or piecewise linear) that are easier to integrate in Go.\n   322→\n   323→### 9.7 Can We Handle \"General\" Workloads Better?\n   324→\n   325→The 4 \"general\" experiments are consistently the hardest (50–121% MAPE for XGBoost). These have the most diverse batch compositions. Potential approaches:\n   326→- Cluster steps by batch composition type, train separate models per cluster\n   327→- Add batch composition entropy/diversity features\n   328→- Use quantile regression to handle bimodal step time distributions\n   329→\n   330→### 9.8 Idea 3 Feasibility Without Idea 2\n   331→\n   332→Evolutionary synthesis (OpenEvolve) was deferred because h2 depends on Idea 2's components. But h1 (evolving raw feature combinations) has no dependency on Idea 2 and could still discover non-obvious feature interactions. Worth revisiting if OpenEvolve infrastructure becomes available.\n   333→\n   334→---\n   335→\n   336→## 10. Reproducibility\n   337→\n   338→All experiment code is in `hypotheses/h-stepml/`:\n   339→\n   340→```\n   341→hypotheses/h-stepml/\n   342→├── shared/                      # Infrastructure (data_loader, splits, evaluation)\n   343→├── idea-1-tree-ensemble/\n   344→│   ├── h1-features/             # 30-feature Ridge regression\n   345→│   │   ├── run.sh               # Orchestrator\n   346→│   │   ├── engineer_features.py # Feature engineering (30 features, 6 groups)\n   347→│   │   ├── train_ridge.py       # Ridge training + prediction\n   348→│   │   ├── analyze.py           # Evaluation against baselines\n   349→│   │   └── FINDINGS.md          # Results and analysis\n   350→│   ├── h2-model/                # XGBoost per-experiment\n   351→│   │   ├── run.sh\n   352→│   │   ├── train_xgboost.py     # XGBoost grid search + training\n   353→│   │   ├── analyze.py\n   354→│   │   └── FINDINGS.md\n   355→│   └── h3-generalization/       # LOMO + LOWO cross-validation\n   356→│       ├── run.sh\n   357→│       ├── cross_validate.py    # Leave-one-out cross-validation\n   358→│       ├── analyze.py\n   359→│       └── FINDINGS.md\n   360→├── idea-2-analytical-decomposition/\n   361→│   ├── h1-features/             # 4-component FLOPs decomposition\n   362→│   │   ├── run.sh\n   363→│   │   ├── compute_components.py # Analytical FLOPs computation\n   364→│   │   ├── analyze.py\n   365→│   │   └── FINDINGS.md\n   366→│   └── h2-model/                # Learned correction factors\n   367→│       ├── run.sh\n   368→│       ├── fit_corrections.py   # Nonlinear least squares fitting\n   369→│       ├── analyze.py\n   370→│       └── FINDINGS.md\n   371→├── idea-3-evolutionary-synthesis/ # Deferred (HYPOTHESIS.md only)\n   372→├── problem.md                   # Problem statement\n   373→├── research.md                  # Full research document (WP1)\n   374→└── DECISION_GATE.md             # WP4/5 decision gate\n   375→```\n   376→\n   377→**Dependencies:** Python 3, pandas, scikit-learn, scipy, xgboost\n   378→**Data:** `eval/ground_truth/` (122,752 steps from 16 experiments)\n   379→**Hardware configs:** `model_configs/` (HuggingFace config.json), `hardware_config.json` (H100 specs)\n   380→\n   381→---\n   382→\n   383→## 11. Summary for Future Ideation\n   384→\n   385→**What the data tells us:**\n   386→1. Per-experiment XGBoost with 30 features is 2x better than blackbox (34% vs 70% avg MAPE)\n   387→2. The bottleneck is **feature quality** (missing per-request KV), not model capacity\n   388→3. Global models are structurally impossible without scale normalization\n   389→4. The analytical decomposition is physically correct but data-incomplete\n   390→5. \"General\" workloads are the hardest — high batch composition diversity\n   391→\n   392→**What Round 2 should explore:**\n   393→1. Deriving per-request KV features from lifecycle data (`request_metrics/`)\n   394→2. Log-scale or normalized prediction for cross-model generalization\n   395→3. BLIS E2E validation (does 34% per-step MAPE → <10% E2E mean error?)\n   396→4. Simpler models with better features (Ridge/piecewise with per-request KV)\n   397→5. Batch composition clustering for \"general\" workloads\n   398→6. Evolutionary synthesis (Idea 3 h1) if OpenEvolve becomes available\n   399→\n   400→**Hard constraints to respect:**\n   401→- Per-model training is mandatory (LOMO fails at 2559%)\n   402→- Features must be computable from `[]*Request` with `ProgressIndex` (Go integration)\n   403→- Prediction latency < 1ms per step\n   404→- Pure-Go implementation (no Python/ONNX runtime)\n   405→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"5a3b242c-f324-4891-a9ed-ea605ba113f7"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_016cHrsw3XpZsQAyd5HETHbt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Latency Model Fidelity for LLM Inference Simulation\n     2→\n     3→## Problem\n     4→\n     5→BLIS (Blackbox Inference Simulator) is a discrete-event simulator for LLM inference serving systems. The **ultimate metric is workload-level E2E mean error < 10%** — the accuracy of end-to-end request latency predicted by the simulator compared to ground truth.\n     6→\n     7→E2E latency in BLIS is the sum of **6 delay components**, each contributed by the `LatencyModel` interface or emergent from simulation dynamics:\n     8→\n     9→```\n    10→E2E(request) = QueueingTime(req)              [1] arrival-to-queue delay\n    11→             + (time waiting in WaitQ)         [2] emergent from simulation dynamics\n    12→             + SchedulingProcessingTime()      [3] per-request scheduling overhead\n    13→             + Σ StepTime(batch)               [4] GPU execution per batch step\n    14→             + Σ OutputTokenProcessingTime()   [5] per-token post-processing\n    15→             + KV transfer latency             [6] CPU↔GPU offload/reload\n    16→             + PreemptionProcessingTime()      [7] if preempted and re-queued\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→### Current Model State\n    20→\n    21→The current `LatencyModel` implementations (blackbox and roofline) have these limitations:\n    22→\n    23→| Component | Current Implementation | Limitation |\n    24→|---|---|---|\n    25→| **StepTime** | `beta0 + beta1*prefill + beta2*decode` (3 coefficients) | Only 2 features; no KV cache, architecture, or batch composition awareness |\n    26→| **QueueingTime** | `alpha0 + alpha1*inputLen` (2 coefficients) | Fixed linear model; doesn't account for system load or batch formation dynamics |\n    27→| **OutputTokenProcessingTime** | constant `alpha2` | Single constant for all tokens regardless of context |\n    28→| **SchedulingProcessingTime** | **returns 0** | Real scheduling has overhead (queue scanning, KV allocation, priority sorting) |\n    29→| **PreemptionProcessingTime** | **returns 0** | Real preemption has cost (KV block release, re-queuing, state bookkeeping) |\n    30→| **KV transfer latency** | Separate KV subsystem | Only applies to tiered (GPU+CPU) configurations |\n    31→\n    32→### Round 1 Findings\n    33→\n    34→Round 1 focused exclusively on replacing `StepTime()`. Key results (see `round1/round1_FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md`):\n    35→- **Best result:** Per-experiment XGBoost achieved 34.0% avg per-step MAPE (2x better than blackbox)\n    36→- **Binding constraint:** Missing per-request KV cache lengths in training data\n    37→- **Generalization fails:** Per-model training is mandatory (LOMO 2559.7% MAPE)\n    38→- **Critical gap:** Per-step MAPE was the only metric tested; workload-level E2E mean error was NOT evaluated\n    39→\n    40→### Round 2 Findings\n    41→\n    42→Round 2 tested 2 ideas on 10 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads, no reasoning). Both ideas added ProgressIndex-derived KV features, regime-based step-time splitting, and BLIS E2E validation. **All hypotheses across both ideas were refuted or not met.** Full details: `round2/FINDINGS_ROUND2.md`.\n    43→\n    44→#### Idea 1: Bayesian Calibration (2-Regime Piecewise Linear)\n    45→\n    46→2 regimes (decode-only vs mixed-batch), Ridge per regime, KV features (kv_sum/kv_max/kv_mean).\n    47→\n    48→| Hypothesis | Target | Actual | Status |\n    49→|---|---|---|---|\n    50→| H1: Piecewise StepTime | <30% MAPE | 87.4% | Refuted |\n    51→| H2: Joint BO | <15% E2E | Not run (H1 too inaccurate) | Blocked |\n    52→| H4: LOMO | <80% MAPE | 148.8% | Refuted |\n    53→| H5: LOWO | <40% MAPE | 155.4% | Refuted |\n    54→\n    55→#### Idea 2: Regime-Switching Ensemble (3-Regime Ridge) — Best Round 2 Result\n    56→\n    57→3 regimes (decode-only / mixed-light<256 / mixed-heavy>=256), Ridge per regime, KV features, BLIS E2E validation, secondary method calibration.\n    58→\n    59→| Hypothesis | Target | Actual | Status |\n    60→|---|---|---|---|\n    61→| H1: Regime Ridge MAPE | <15% | 64.4% | Not met |\n    62→| H2: BLIS E2E | <10% mean | 427.8% | Not met |\n    63→| H3: Secondary calibration | >=5pp E2E gain | 0.0pp | Refuted |\n    64→| H4: LOMO | <80% MAPE | 108.6% | Refuted |\n    65→| H5: LOWO | <25% MAPE | 117.4% | Refuted |\n    66→\n    67→#### Round 2 Per-Experiment BLIS E2E Results (Idea 2)\n    68→\n    69→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error | Status |\n    70→|---|---|---|---|---|\n    71→| 34b-roleplay | **3.3%** | 282.7% | 100.1% | E2E solved (likely coincidental) |\n    72→| mixtral-roleplay | 50.8% | 77.2% | **0.7%** | ITL solved |\n    73→| mixtral-codegen | 51.5% | 76.5% | **2.1%** | ITL solved |\n    74→| 7b-roleplay | 52.5% | 78.4% | **4.0%** | ITL solved |\n    75→| mixtral-general | 554.6% | 44,464% | **8.7%** | ITL solved |\n    76→| 70b-hf-codegen | 55.7% | 77.7% | 10.7% | ITL close |\n    77→| 70b-roleplay | 55.6% | 77.9% | 10.3% | ITL close |\n    78→| 70b-general | 182.7% | 12,567% | 23.5% | Unsolved |\n    79→| 34b-codegen | 370.2% | 30,425% | 95.9% | Unsolved |\n    80→| 34b-general | 2,901.1% | 230,931% | 80.3% | Unsolved |\n    81→\n    82→**Key observations:**\n    83→- **ITL is nearly solved** — 33.6% mean, 5/10 <10%, driven by the overhead floor mechanism\n    84→- **TTFT errors dominate E2E** — 31,906% mean TTFT makes step-time improvements irrelevant until fixed\n    85→- **CodeLlama-34B is a consistent outlier** — worst across all metrics\n    86→- **\"General\" workloads are hardest** — largest TTFT errors for every model\n    87→\n    88→#### Round 2 Critical Discovery: Overhead Floor Mechanism\n    89→\n    90→The `max(overhead, compute)` step-time floor is the single most impactful technique. Per-model overhead constants (derived from ground-truth ITL):\n    91→\n    92→| Model | Overhead (us) |\n    93→|---|---|\n    94→| Llama-2-7B (TP1) | 3,897 |\n    95→| CodeLlama-34B (TP2) | 6,673 |\n    96→| Llama-2-70B (TP4) | 8,029–8,203 |\n    97→| Mixtral-8x7B (TP2) | 9,125 |\n    98→\n    99→`step.duration_us` captures GPU forward pass only (~70–7,000us). Real step cycle time includes CPU overhead (scheduling, sync, memory management). The floor handles 77.9% of steps (decode-only) by clamping small-batch predictions to real cycle time.\n   100→\n   101→#### Round 2 Critical Discovery: KV Features Counter-Productive\n   102→\n   103→The central thesis of Round 2 — that ProgressIndex-derived KV features would improve prediction — was **refuted in raw linear space**:\n   104→- Idea 1: KV features hurt by +3.6pp (87.4% vs 83.8% without)\n   105→- Idea 2: KV features hurt by +20.5pp (64.4% vs 43.9% without)\n   106→\n   107→**Root cause:** kv_sum ranges 0–64,000+, causing Ridge coefficient instability. Only Mixtral benefited (-5.4pp). This is a **formulation problem, not a feature problem** — the features have signal but raw linear regression cannot handle their dynamic range. Feature scaling (StandardScaler), log-transform of features, or nonlinear models would likely fix this.\n   108→\n   109→#### Round 2 Overhead Integration Approaches (All Tested)\n   110→\n   111→| Approach | Result |\n   112→|---|---|\n   113→| Additive (compute + overhead) | Phase transition — under-capacity to overload, no stable point |\n   114→| Log-space cycle time | Exponential amplification — coefficients get multiplied, not added |\n   115→| **Max floor (best)** | `step_time = max(overhead, compute)` — handles memory→compute crossover |\n   116→| Floor + cap | `max(overhead, min(compute, 3*overhead))` prevents exp blowup |\n   117→\n   118→Log-space expm1 pitfalls: kv_sum coefficient 0.0001 × 64,000 = 6.4 → 601x multiplier. Prefill coefficient 0.06 × 500 = 30 → exp(30) = absurd. Use `use_log_target=False` for all BLIS-destined regimes.\n   119→\n   120→#### Round 2 Secondary Methods Finding\n   121→\n   122→Secondary LatencyModel methods (QueueingTime, SchedulingProcessingTime) contribute **exactly 0.0pp** to E2E improvement. Extracted constants are 200–400us — invisible against 100%+ E2E errors. Do not invest in secondary methods until the dominant error source (TTFT mismatch) is resolved.\n   123→\n   124→#### Round 2 Generalization Progress\n   125→\n   126→| Metric | Round 1 | Round 2 | Change |\n   127→|---|---|---|---|\n   128→| LOMO avg MAPE | 2,559.7% | 108.6% | **23.6x better** |\n   129→| LOWO avg MAPE | 109.7% | 117.4% | 0.9x (no improvement) |\n   130→\n   131→LOMO improved dramatically due to regime structure. LOWO regressed slightly — the regime structure did not help cross-workload transfer.\n   132→\n   133→**Mixtral generalizes exceptionally:** LOWO 19.1% avg (below 25% target), ITL 0.7%/2.1%/8.7%. A single Mixtral model works across all workloads.\n   134→\n   135→### Scope for Round 3\n   136→\n   137→The E2E target (<10%) requires addressing **two independent problems**:\n   138→\n   139→1. **TTFT/simulation fidelity** (PRIMARY BLOCKER) — TTFT errors of 31,906% mean indicate a systematic mismatch between BLIS's request lifecycle and the real system. This is not a step-time problem. Until TTFT is fixed, no step-time improvement can achieve the E2E target.\n   140→\n   141→2. **Step-time accuracy for remaining experiments** — ITL is solved for 5/10 experiments via the overhead floor. The remaining 5 need either better step-time models (feature-scaled KV, nonlinear models) or 34B-specific investigation.\n   142→\n   143→**The winning approach must integrate back into BLIS as a Go `LatencyModel` implementation.** The simulator's existing roofline model (analytical FLOPs/bandwidth with MFU lookup) is unaffected and not being replaced.\n   144→\n   145→## Ground-Truth Data\n   146→\n   147→### Overview\n   148→\n   149→122,752 step-level observations from instrumented vLLM v0.15.1 with OpenTelemetry tracing (10% sample rate). 12 experiments: 4 models × 3 workloads, all on H100 80GB GPUs.\n   150→\n   151→### Models and Configurations\n   152→\n   153→| Model | Architecture | TP | Parameters |\n   154→|-------|-------------|-----|-----------|\n   155→| Llama-2-7B | Dense | 1 | 7B |\n   156→| Llama-2-70B | Dense | 4 | 70B |\n   157→| CodeLlama-34B | Dense | 2 | 34B |\n   158→| Mixtral-8x7B-v0.1 | MoE (8 experts, top-2) | 2 | 46.7B total, ~12.9B active |\n   159→\n   160→### Workloads\n   161→\n   162→general, codegen, roleplay — each with different input/output length distributions. All runs: `max_model_len=4096`, `max_num_batched_tokens=2048`, `max_num_seqs=128`, chunked prefill enabled, prefix caching enabled.\n   163→\n   164→### Step-Level Features\n   165→\n   166→**Batch computation features** (causal):\n   167→- `batch.prefill_tokens` (int) — prefill tokens in this step\n   168→- `batch.decode_tokens` (int) — decode tokens in this step\n   169→- `batch.num_prefill_reqs` (int) — prefill request count\n   170→- `batch.num_decode_reqs` (int) — decode request count\n   171→- `batch.scheduled_tokens` (int) — total scheduled tokens\n   172→\n   173→**System state features** (potentially spurious):\n   174→- `queue.running_depth`, `queue.waiting_depth` — queue state\n   175→- `kv.usage_gpu_ratio`, `kv.blocks_free_gpu`, `kv.blocks_total_gpu` — KV cache state\n   176→\n   177→**Target**: `step.duration_us` (int) — wall-clock step execution time in microseconds\n   178→\n   179→### Data Characteristics\n   180→\n   181→Step durations span 3+ orders of magnitude:\n   182→- Smallest: ~12 μs (small decode-only batches)\n   183→- Largest: ~250,000 μs (large prefills)\n   184→- Roleplay/codegen: mean 160–320 μs (short, bursty)\n   185→\n   186→**Phase distribution** (from Round 2 10-experiment dataset, 77,816 steps):\n   187→\n   188→| Regime | Steps | Share |\n   189→|---|---|---|\n   190→| Decode-only (prefill = 0) | 60,613 | 77.9% |\n   191→| Mixed-light (0 < prefill < 256) | 17,129 | 22.0% |\n   192→| Mixed-heavy (prefill >= 256) | 74 | 0.1% |\n   193→\n   194→vLLM's chunked prefill makes nearly every batch mixed or pure-decode. Only 6 pure-prefill steps exist in the full 16-experiment dataset. The mixed-heavy regime (prefill>=256) is effectively empty without reasoning workloads.\n   195→\n   196→**Step data is ~10% sampled** — not every step is logged (OpenTelemetry tracing at ~10% rate).\n   197→\n   198→### Known Feature Gaps\n   199→\n   200→1. **No per-request KV cache lengths**: Only aggregate batch tokens available. Attention FLOPs scale with per-request kv_len (H8 showed 12.96× overestimate without per-request KV). The simulator's `ProgressIndex` (input_tokens_processed + output_tokens_generated) is available as a proxy at inference time.\n   201→2. **No MoE-specific features**: No active expert count, expert load balance, or tokens-per-expert.\n   202→3. **No prefix cache hit information**: `prefill_tokens` may reflect pre- or post-cache-hit count.\n   203→\n   204→### Additional Data Sources\n   205→\n   206→- **Per-request lifecycle data**: Per-token timestamps, input/output token counts — enables per-request KV length derivation and E2E validation\n   207→- **MFU benchmarks** (`bench_data/`): Kernel-level GEMM and attention MFU data by GPU — useful for physics-informed features\n   208→\n   209→## Baseline Results (WP0)\n   210→\n   211→### BLIS E2E Validation — Per-Model Linear Regression (THE NUMBER TO BEAT)\n   212→\n   213→Per-model+TP linear regression (one regression per model group, pooling all workloads):\n   214→- **Mean E2E error: 115.0%** (0/12 experiments below 10% target)\n   215→- Mean TTFT error: 102.9%\n   216→- Mean ITL error: 134.6%\n   217→- **R4 gate: PASSED** — blackbox is clearly insufficient, research is justified\n   218→\n   219→Per-model training coefficients (note negative intercepts producing invalid predictions):\n   220→\n   221→| Model+TP | beta0 | beta1 | beta2 | Train MAPE | Train r |\n   222→|----------|-------|-------|-------|------------|---------|\n   223→| CodeLlama-34B tp=2 | -5525 | 0.421 | 215.1 | 675.8% | 0.918 |\n   224→| Llama-2-70B tp=4 | -2633 | 1.306 | 106.4 | 199.2% | 0.934 |\n   225→| Llama-2-7B tp=1 | 992 | 3.403 | 7.031 | 610.3% | 0.359 |\n   226→| Mixtral-8x7B tp=2 | -8035 | 0.000 | 249.3 | 965.6% | 0.778 |\n   227→\n   228→Per-experiment BLIS E2E errors:\n   229→\n   230→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error |\n   231→|---|---|---|---|\n   232→| llama-2-7b-tp1-codegen | 86.2% | 88.0% | 72.3% |\n   233→| llama-2-7b-tp1-roleplay | 86.1% | 85.9% | 72.2% |\n   234→| llama-2-7b-tp1-general | 90.8% | 92.0% | 81.6% |\n   235→| llama-2-70b-tp4-general | 111.8% | 102.0% | 124.1% |\n   236→| llama-2-70b-tp4-codegen | 113.6% | 103.6% | 127.5% |\n   237→| llama-2-70b-tp4-roleplay | 113.9% | 103.4% | 128.2% |\n   238→| mixtral-8x7b-tp2-codegen | 141.3% | 113.7% | 183.5% |\n   239→| mixtral-8x7b-tp2-general | 138.5% | 111.7% | 177.9% |\n   240→| mixtral-8x7b-tp2-roleplay | 141.9% | 113.3% | 184.7% |\n   241→| codellama-34b-tp2-general | 132.3% | 110.3% | 165.3% |\n   242→| codellama-34b-tp2-codegen | 135.4% | 111.7% | 171.5% |\n   243→| codellama-34b-tp2-roleplay | 136.5% | 111.5% | 173.7% |\n   244→\n   245→### BLIS E2E Validation — Roofline (Informational Only)\n   246→\n   247→The analytical roofline model (zero calibration, FLOPs/bandwidth-based):\n   248→- **Mean E2E error: 4816%** (10/16 completed, 6 timed out at 300s)\n   249→- Massively overestimates step time, causing request starvation\n   250→- Only Mixtral codegen/roleplay were within 35% (GEMM-dominated workloads)\n   251→- The roofline model is informational only — ideas MUST NOT use roofline as input\n   252→\n   253→### Component Error Attribution (BC-0-6)\n   254→\n   255→StepTime dominates E2E error in all 12 experiments. With alpha=[0,0,0] (blackbox defaults):\n   256→- Queueing contribution: 0% (alpha coefficients are zero)\n   257→- Output processing: 0% (alpha2 is zero)\n   258→- Scheduling: 0 (returns 0)\n   259→- Preemption: 0 (returns 0)\n   260→- **Step time: 100% of modeled error**. Per-step MAPE ranges from 28.5% to 1287% (codegen, high batch variance)\n   261→\n   262→**Recommendation:** All improvement effort should focus on StepTime prediction. Any non-zero contribution to queueing/scheduling/preemption is additive benefit since the blackbox currently returns 0 for all of them.\n   263→\n   264→### Round 1 Per-Step Baselines (Historical Reference)\n   265→\n   266→Round 1 tested per-step MAPE only (no BLIS E2E validation):\n   267→- **Per-experiment XGBoost (30 features):** 34.0% avg MAPE — 2x better than blackbox (70.4%)\n   268→- **Global blackbox:** 670% MAPE — catastrophic failure across model scales\n   269→- **Key insight:** Per-step MAPE ≠ E2E error. The 34% per-step MAPE was never validated through BLIS.\n   270→\n   271→### Validation Gate Summary\n   272→\n   273→| Gate | Status | Detail |\n   274→|------|--------|--------|\n   275→| R1 (ProgressIndex as KV proxy) | FLAGGED | Pearson r ≈ 0 between total_tokens and E2E time; ProgressIndex is valid for KV cache length but not for E2E prediction. Lifecycle KV extractor available as fallback. |\n   276→| R2 (Sampling bias) | PASS | CV=0.44, max/min ratio=4.2, random sampling confirmed (~10% rate) |\n   277→| R4 (Blackbox sufficient?) | PASS | 115% E2E mean error — clearly beatable |\n   278→\n   279→## Evaluation Framework\n   280→\n   281→### Primary Metric\n   282→\n   283→**Workload-level E2E mean error < 10%** on each of the 12 experiments individually. For each experiment:\n   284→```\n   285→predicted_mean_e2e = mean over requests of (sum of predicted step times along request's path)\n   286→observed_mean_e2e  = mean over requests of (observed request-level E2E latency)\n   287→E2E_mean_error     = |predicted_mean_e2e - observed_mean_e2e| / observed_mean_e2e\n   288→```\n   289→\n   290→### All Metrics (ordered by priority)\n   291→\n   292→| Priority | Metric | Target |\n   293→|----------|--------|--------|\n   294→| P1 | Workload-level E2E mean error | < 10% per experiment |\n   295→| P1 | Per-step MAPE, Pearson r | Diagnostic (no hard target) |\n   296→| **P2** | **Generalization: model (LOMO)** | **LOMO MAPE < 80% per fold** |\n   297→| **P2** | **Generalization: workload (LOWO)** | **LOWO MAPE < 50% per fold** |\n   298→| **P2** | **Generalization: vLLM args sensitivity** | **Qualitative robustness analysis per idea** |\n   299→| P2 | TTFT mean fidelity | < 15% per experiment |\n   300→| P2 | ITL mean fidelity | < 15% per experiment |\n   301→| P3 | Tail behavior (p99) | No ranking inversions vs baseline |\n   302→| P3 | Ease of use, retraining story, reproducibility | Qualitative |\n   303→| P4 | Hardware generalization (H100 → A100) | Informational |\n   304→| P5 | Quantization transferability | Informational |\n   305→\n   306→> **Generalization is P2, not optional.** An idea that achieves <10% E2E but fails LOMO/LOWO/vLLM-args analysis is **not a viable winner** — it would be useless in production where new models, workloads, and vLLM configurations are deployed routinely. Reviewers MUST evaluate generalization with the same rigor as accuracy.\n   307→\n   308→### Data Split Strategy\n   309→\n   310→- **Primary**: Temporal split (60/20/20) within each experiment — prevents autocorrelation leakage\n   311→- **Generalization**: Leave-one-model-out (4-fold) + leave-one-workload-out (3-fold)\n   312→- **Short-circuit**: Ideas with h1 per-step MAPE > 30% are dropped (threshold calibrated to blackbox_MAPE + 10% if blackbox exceeds 25%)\n   313→\n   314→### Idea Review Criteria\n   315→\n   316→Beyond quantitative accuracy, idea reviewers evaluate each approach against the following dimensions. The standard is that **the approach must be defensible to a community of reviewers at a top-tier systems/ML conference or journal** (e.g., OSDI, SOSP, NSDI, MLSys, EuroSys).\n   317→\n   318→**BLOCKING dimensions** — reviewers MUST reject ideas that do not address these. An idea missing any blocking dimension cannot proceed to experimentation:\n   319→\n   320→| Dimension | Blocking? | What reviewers check |\n   321→|---|:---:|---|\n   322→| **Accuracy** | **YES** | Does the approach meet the P1 target (<10% E2E mean error)? Are per-step and E2E metrics both reported? |\n   323→| **Generalization across LLMs (LOMO)** | **YES** | Does the idea include a concrete LOMO experimental plan? Does its formulation use model-agnostic features (FLOPs, parameter count, TP degree) or model-specific memorization? Would it work on a model not in the training set (e.g., Llama-3, Qwen)? Reviewers should flag ideas where the formulation structurally prevents cross-model transfer. |\n   324→| **Generalization across workloads (LOWO)** | **YES** | Does the idea include a concrete LOWO experimental plan? Does its formulation depend on specific input/output length distributions, or does it capture workload-invariant compute physics? Reviewers should flag ideas that would fail on an unseen workload type (e.g., summarization, RAG). |\n   325→| **Generalization across vLLM config** | **YES** | Does the idea include a sensitivity analysis plan for the 7 key vLLM parameters (max_num_seqs, max_num_batched_tokens, max_model_len, chunked_prefill, prefix_caching, gpu_memory_utilization, tensor_parallel_size)? Does the formulation structurally depend on batch distribution shapes determined by these parameters? Reviewers should flag ideas where changing `max_num_seqs` from 128→256 would invalidate the model without retraining. |\n   326→| **Generalization across hardware** | No | Does the approach transfer across GPU generations (H100 → A100 → B200)? What changes when memory bandwidth, compute FLOPs, or GPU memory capacity differ? |\n   327→| **Ease of use** | No | How much expertise is required to deploy the model for a new model/GPU/config combination? Is the workflow self-service or does it require ML expertise? |\n   328→| **Retraining story** | No | Is retraining or fine-tuning required? Under what circumstances (new model, new GPU, new vLLM version, new workload)? How much data and compute does retraining require? How easy is the retraining process end-to-end? |\n   329→| **vLLM version sensitivity** | No | What happens when the serving engine (vLLM) changes versions? Do internal scheduling changes (e.g., new chunked prefill heuristics, changed batch formation logic) invalidate the model's assumptions? How is this detected and corrected? |\n   330→| **Overheads** | No | What are the training-time costs (data collection, compute, human effort)? What are the inference-time costs (latency per prediction, memory footprint, complexity of the Go integration)? |\n   331→| **Reproducibility** | No | Can results be reproduced from the provided code, data, and instructions? Are random seeds fixed? Are all hyperparameters documented? Is the training pipeline deterministic? |\n   332→\n   333→> **Reviewer instruction:** When reviewing ideas generated by `/research-ideas`, evaluate the top 4 blocking dimensions FIRST. If an idea has no LOMO plan, no LOWO plan, or no vLLM-args sensitivity plan, flag it as incomplete regardless of how good the accuracy approach looks. The purpose of this research is to find a **production-viable** latency model, not a benchmark-winning one.\n   334→\n   335→## Constraints\n   336→\n   337→### LatencyModel Interface (Frozen)\n   338→\n   339→The winning model must implement this 5-method Go interface:\n   340→\n   341→```go\n   342→type LatencyModel interface {\n   343→    StepTime(batch []*Request) int64          // Primary target\n   344→    QueueingTime(req *Request) int64          // Currently alpha0 + alpha1*inputLen\n   345→    OutputTokenProcessingTime() int64          // Currently alpha2\n   346→    SchedulingProcessingTime() int64           // Currently returns 0\n   347→    PreemptionProcessingTime() int64           // Currently returns 0\n   348→}\n   349→```\n   350→\n   351→Step-time estimation is the primary research target. The other 4 methods are secondary targets that contribute to E2E fidelity. At a minimum, improve StepTime while retaining current implementations for the other 4 methods.\n   352→\n   353→### Feature Availability at Prediction Time\n   354→\n   355→At inference time in the simulator, each Request in the batch provides:\n   356→- `InputTokens` (token sequence)\n   357→- `OutputTokens` (generated tokens so far)\n   358→- `ProgressIndex` (cumulative: input_processed + output_generated — KV cache length proxy)\n   359→- `NumNewTokens` (tokens to generate this step)\n   360→\n   361→Research models must use only features derivable from these fields plus experiment-level metadata (model name, TP degree).\n   362→\n   363→### Inference Latency\n   364→\n   365→Prediction must complete in <1ms per step (128 requests max). Linear models, tree ensembles (~100 trees), and small neural networks all qualify. Only large neural networks (>10M parameters) or GPU-inference-requiring approaches are excluded.\n   366→\n   367→### Go Integration Path\n   368→\n   369→The winning model must eventually run in Go. Viable paths:\n   370→1. **Coefficient export** — for parametric models (regression, piecewise linear)\n   371→2. **Go-native reimplementation** — for tree ensembles (Go libraries available)\n   372→3. **ONNX export** — for neural networks\n   373→\n   374→Each idea must specify which integration path it would use.\n   375→\n   376→## Generalization Requirements (MANDATORY — P2 PRIORITY)\n   377→\n   378→**Every idea must explicitly design for and test generalization across three dimensions.** An idea that achieves <10% E2E on training experiments but cannot generalize is not a viable solution — production deployments routinely introduce new models, new workload patterns, and changed vLLM serving configurations. Reviewers treat generalization failures as seriously as accuracy failures.\n   379→\n   380→### Dimension 1: Model Generalization (LOMO)\n   381→\n   382→**Test:** Leave-one-model-out cross-validation (4-fold: hold out each of llama-2-7b, llama-2-70b, codellama-34b, mixtral-8x7b).\n   383→**Target:** LOMO per-step MAPE < 80% per fold.\n   384→**Why it matters:** Users deploy BLIS for capacity planning across model families. A latency model that requires retraining from scratch for every new model is impractical. At minimum, the model should transfer between models of similar architecture/scale (e.g., 70B → 34B dense), and degrade gracefully for architecture shifts (dense → MoE).\n   385→**What ideas must specify:** (a) Which model features enable transfer (parameter count, architecture type, TP degree)? (b) What retraining is needed for a truly new model (e.g., Llama-3, Qwen)? (c) How much data from the new model is required?\n   386→\n   387→### Dimension 2: Workload Generalization (LOWO)\n   388→\n   389→**Test:** Leave-one-workload-out cross-validation (3-fold: hold out each of general, codegen, roleplay).\n   390→**Target:** LOWO per-step MAPE < 50% per fold.\n   391→**Why it matters:** Real deployments serve diverse traffic mixes. A model trained only on codegen traffic that fails on conversational traffic is brittle. The workloads in our dataset (general, codegen, roleplay) differ primarily in input/output length distributions and burstiness — the model should capture the underlying compute physics, not memorize specific length distributions.\n   392→**What ideas must specify:** (a) Which features are workload-invariant vs workload-specific? (b) How does the approach handle unseen input/output length distributions? (c) Would a new workload type (e.g., summarization, RAG) require retraining?\n   393→\n   394→### Dimension 3: vLLM Configuration Sensitivity (MANDATORY ANALYSIS)\n   395→\n   396→**Test:** Qualitative sensitivity analysis — for each tunable vLLM serving parameter, describe whether the model's predictions would change and whether retraining/recalibration would be needed.\n   397→**Target:** The idea must document its sensitivity to each parameter below and propose a recalibration strategy that does NOT require full retraining from step-level traces.\n   398→\n   399→| vLLM Parameter | Default in Data | Range in Practice | Why It Matters |\n   400→|---|---|---|---|\n   401→| `max_num_seqs` | 128 | 32–512 | Controls maximum batch size → changes batch composition distributions |\n   402→| `max_num_batched_tokens` | 2048 | 512–8192 | Controls chunked prefill budget → changes mixed-batch frequency |\n   403→| `max_model_len` | 4096 | 2048–131072 | Controls KV cache capacity → changes eviction/preemption behavior |\n   404→| `chunked_prefill` | enabled | on/off | Fundamentally changes batch composition (pure-prefill vs mixed batches) |\n   405→| `prefix_caching` | enabled | on/off | Changes effective prefill tokens per step |\n   406→| `gpu_memory_utilization` | 0.9 | 0.5–0.95 | Changes KV cache capacity → changes batch sizes under memory pressure |\n   407→| `tensor_parallel_size` | varies | 1–8 | Changes per-GPU compute/memory → changes step time scaling |\n   408→\n   409→**What ideas must specify for EACH parameter:** (a) Does the model implicitly depend on this parameter's value? (b) If the parameter changes, would the model's predictions be wrong? (c) What is the minimum recalibration needed (nothing / update one constant / retrain one component / full retrain)?\n   410→\n   411→**Reviewers must evaluate:** Does the idea's formulation *structurally* depend on the training data's vLLM config, or does it capture generalizable compute physics? A model that learns `step_time = f(batch_size)` where the relationship shape depends on `max_num_seqs=128` is fragile. A model that learns `step_time = f(FLOPs, memory_bandwidth)` is robust.\n   412→\n   413→### Historical Generalization Results (for calibrating targets)\n   414→\n   415→| Round | Idea | LOMO | LOWO | vLLM Args |\n   416→|---|---|---|---|---|\n   417→| R1 | Tree ensemble | 2,559.7% | 109.7% | Not analyzed |\n   418→| R2 | Bayesian calibration | 148.8% | 155.4% | Not analyzed |\n   419→| R2 | Regime ensemble | 108.6% | 117.4% | Not analyzed |\n   420→| R3 | Total-context model | 2,281.6% (REFUTED) | 2,162.7% (REFUTED) | Not analyzed |\n   421→| R3 | CMA-ES calibration | **14.8% E2E** (SUPPORTED) | Partial (8/10 within 2×) | Not analyzed |\n   422→\n   423→**Trend:** LOMO saw a breakthrough in R3 — CMA-ES artifact transfer achieves 14.8% mean E2E across models (best: Mixtral via 70B donor at 5.1%). However, the total-context model (without regime structure) regressed to R1-level LOMO (2,281.6%). LOWO remains unsolved for per-step models but CMA-ES shows implicit workload stability for dense models (9-16pp range). vLLM args sensitivity has never been analyzed. All three dimensions remain open for the next round.\n   424→\n   425→## Algorithm Scope\n   426→\n   427→**Not restricted to ML or to StepTime.** Research ideas may propose:\n   428→- Statistical regression (Ridge, Lasso, polynomial, piecewise)\n   429→- Tree ensembles (XGBoost, LightGBM, random forest)\n   430→- Neural networks (small MLPs, attention-based)\n   431→- Physics-informed models (analytical compute model + learned residuals)\n   432→- Hybrid approaches (analytical backbone + ML residual correction)\n   433→- **Multi-component calibration** (jointly optimize all 5 LatencyModel methods for E2E fidelity)\n   434→- **Scheduling/preemption overhead models** (data-driven models for the currently-zero methods)\n   435→- **End-to-end calibration** (tune any/all components with E2E mean error as the objective, not per-component accuracy)\n   436→\n   437→Each approach must:\n   438→1. Cite relevant prior work from systems/ML literature\n   439→2. Address all evaluation dimensions (P1–P6)\n   440→3. Specify which LatencyModel methods it covers (minimum: StepTime; **bonus: additional methods**)\n   441→4. Document its Go integration path\n   442→5. Be distinct from other proposed approaches\n   443→6. Include a **model-generalization hypothesis (LOMO — MANDATORY, MUST EXECUTE)** — a leave-one-model-out experiment (train on 3 models, predict on the held-out 4th) that evaluates whether the approach transfers to unseen model architectures and scales. This hypothesis must be **actually executed** with results reported in FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md section 9, not just scaffolded. If blocked by prior sub-hypothesis failure, document \"Not executed — blocked by [reason]\" with root cause.\n   444→7. Include a **workload-generalization hypothesis (LOWO — MANDATORY, MUST EXECUTE)** — a leave-one-workload-out experiment (train on 2 workloads, predict on the held-out 3rd) that evaluates whether the approach transfers to unseen workload distributions. Same execution requirement as item 6.\n   445→8. **Address vLLM-args sensitivity at ideation time (MANDATORY — checked during idea review, NOT a hypothesis).** Each idea's description in research.md must include a section analyzing its structural dependence on the 7 key vLLM parameters listed in the \"Generalization Requirements\" section above. For each parameter: (a) does the formulation depend on it, (b) would predictions break if it changed, (c) what recalibration is needed. This is a **design-time check**, not an experiment — reviewers evaluate it during WP1 idea review and reject ideas that are structurally fragile without a recalibration story.\n   446→   > **Historical note:** Rounds 1-3 showed a pattern of generalization hypotheses being scaffolded but never run (R1 idea-2 h3, R3 idea-2 h4/h5, R3 idea-3 h4/h5), and vLLM args sensitivity was never analyzed in any round. The macro plan now enforces LOMO/LOWO execution via WP4 Step 0 gate. If an idea is infrastructure-only (not a new model), provide a GENERALIZATION_NOTE.md with cross-experiment evidence.\n   447→\n   448→## Key Questions for Ideas to Address\n   449→\n   450→### Answered by Round 1+2 (DO NOT re-investigate)\n   451→\n   452→| # | Question | Answer | Round |\n   453→|---|---|---|---|\n   454→| Q1 | Which LatencyModel component contributes most to E2E error? | **StepTime is 100% of modeled error** (alpha coeffs are all zero). But TTFT/simulation mismatch dominates actual E2E error. | R2 |\n   455→| Q2 | Does per-step MAPE translate to E2E error? | **No simple relationship.** 64.4% per-step MAPE → 427.8% E2E error, but 33.6% ITL error. TTFT errors dominate E2E, not step-time errors. | R2 |\n   456→| Q3 | Can non-zero SchedulingProcessingTime/PreemptionProcessingTime improve E2E? | **No.** They contribute 0.0pp improvement — 200-400us corrections are invisible against 100%+ errors. | R2 |\n   457→| Q4 | Can we derive per-request KV features from lifecycle data? | **Yes, ProgressIndex proxy is available.** But raw KV features in linear regression are counter-productive (+20.5pp worse). Need feature scaling. | R2 |\n   458→| Q5 | Per-model vs global training? | **Per-model mandatory.** 3+ OOM step-time scale variation. LOMO >100% even after 23.6x improvement. | R1+R2 |\n   459→\n   460→### Open questions for Round 3\n   461→\n   462→1. **What causes the 31,906% mean TTFT error?** Is it the workload spec generator (request arrival patterns), BLIS request injection timing, BLIS prefill scheduling, or some other simulation-level mismatch with real vLLM? This is the PRIMARY blocker for <10% E2E.\n   463→\n   464→2. **Can feature scaling (StandardScaler, log-transform) make KV features productive?** KV features have signal but their 0–64,000 range causes Ridge instability. The right normalization or a nonlinear model should unlock them.\n   465→\n   466→3. **Why is CodeLlama-34B consistently the worst model?** Is it a data quality issue, architecture-specific batch dynamics, or a coefficient problem? 34B accounts for disproportionate error (99.2% per-step MAPE, 2,901% E2E for general).\n   467→\n   468→4. **Can the mixed-heavy regime be made useful?** Only 74/77,816 steps (0.1%) have prefill>=256. Should the threshold lower to 64/128, or should reasoning workloads be included in the dataset?\n   469→\n   470→5. **How to handle 3+ OOM step time range across models for cross-model transfer?** LOMO improved 23.6x but remains >80%. Feature normalization by model-specific constants (parameter count, FLOPS/token) might close the gap. The 34B interpolation result (63.4% LOMO fold) suggests interpolation between scales is feasible.\n   471→\n   472→6. **Is end-to-end calibration (E2E objective) more practical than per-component accuracy?** Per-step MAPE is a poor proxy for E2E error. Directly optimizing coefficients against BLIS E2E might find better trade-offs, but only after the TTFT mismatch is resolved.\n   473→\n   474→## Successful Techniques to Build On\n   475→\n   476→1. **Overhead floor (`max(overhead, compute)`)** — the most impactful technique, produces 5/10 ITL <10%\n   477→2. **Per-model overhead constants** — stable across workloads: 7B=3,897us, 34B=6,673us, 70B=8,029-8,203us, Mixtral=9,125us\n   478→3. **Per-model training** — mandatory, non-negotiable\n   479→4. **Regime separation** (decode-only vs mixed) — distinct modeling contexts, 23.6x LOMO improvement\n   480→5. **Temporal train/test split** — prevents autocorrelation leakage\n   481→6. **BLIS E2E validation pipeline** — `validate_e2e.py` + `validate_blis.py` infrastructure for running BLIS with custom coefficients\n   482→7. **Lifecycle KV extractor** — derives per-request KV proxy from lifecycle data\n   483→8. **Mixtral universal model** — MoE architecture generalizes across all workloads (LOWO 19.1%)\n   484→9. **Trace replay mode** (`--workload traces --workload-traces-filepath <csv>`) — eliminates workload-spec generation artifacts; all E2E experiments should use this as default mode\n   485→10. **CMA-ES for black-box DES calibration** — effective for optimizing noisy multi-experiment objective. Per-model, 96-152 evaluations, ~30 min/model\n   486→11. **Per-model TTFT additive corrections** — simple per-model constants (16-61ms) reduce TTFT from 67.6% to 9.4%\n   487→12. **FairBatching 3-coefficient OLS** — `a + b*new_tokens + c*kv_sum` outperforms complex feature engineering (56.2% vs 83.1% per-step MAPE)\n   488→13. **StepML CLI integration** — complete `--stepml-model` flag + factory dispatch + Go evaluator path\n   489→14. **CMA-ES cross-model artifact transfer** — CMA-ES artifacts generalize dramatically better than per-step models (14.8% LOMO E2E vs 2,281.6% LOMO MAPE) because they capture simulation dynamics (overhead floor, scheduling), not model-specific step times. Mixtral is the best universal donor (11.9–26.0%). 70B→Mixtral transfer (5.1%) outperforms Mixtral's in-distribution result (25.9%).\n   490→\n   491→## Eliminated Approaches (Do NOT Repeat)\n   492→\n   493→| Approach | Why It Failed | Round |\n   494→|---|---|---|\n   495→| Global models (all experiments) | 3+ OOM step-time scale variation | R1 |\n   496→| Analytical FLOPs decomposition without per-request KV | decode_attention = 0, structurally incomplete | R1 |\n   497→| Correction factors on incomplete backbone | Pathological compensation (factor=39.5 on zero signal) | R1 |\n   498→| Pure-phase analysis | Only 6 pure-prefill steps under chunked prefill | R1 |\n   499→| Raw KV features in linear regression | kv_sum up to 64K causes Ridge coefficient instability (+20.5pp worse) | R2 |\n   500→| 2-regime piecewise linear | Too coarse — mixed-batch heterogeneity too high for one regime | R2 |\n   501→| Joint Bayesian optimization on inaccurate base model | Cannot compensate for structural model errors | R2 |\n   502→| Secondary method calibration alone | 200-400us corrections invisible against 100%+ E2E errors | R2 |\n   503→| Log-space target with large features (expm1) | Exponential blowup: coeff×64K → exp(6.4) = 601x multiplier | R2 |\n   504→| Additive overhead (compute + overhead) | Phase transition from under-capacity to overload, no stable point | R2 |\n   505→| Feature scaling for multicollinear KV features | StandardScaler, log-transform, combinations all failed — issue is multicollinearity (4 correlated features), not scale | R3 |\n   506→| Per-step MAPE as proxy for E2E accuracy | 27pp per-step improvement → 0pp E2E improvement; overhead floor masks per-step gains | R3 |\n   507→| Workload-spec mode for E2E validation | Workload-spec introduces systematic 31,906% TTFT errors; use trace replay instead | R3 |\n   508→| Post-hoc corrections on CMA-ES results | TTFT additive corrections conflict with CMA-ES-optimized coefficients (+2.1pp worse) | R3 |\n   509→| Unconstrained CMA-ES optimization | Without ITL constraints, produces implausible parameter values (e.g., output_token_processing_time 0→1,899µs) | R3 |\n   510→\n   511→### Round 3 Findings\n   512→\n   513→Round 3 tested 3 ideas on 10 experiments (5 models × 3 workloads). **Key achievement: 427.8% → 15.1% mean E2E (28.3x improvement)** via two advances: trace replay eliminated workload-spec errors, CMA-ES found per-model coefficient settings. Full details: `round3/FINDINGS_ROUND3.md`.\n   514→\n   515→#### Idea 1: Trace-Driven Simulation with Lifecycle Replay\n   516→\n   517→Bypass BLIS's workload-spec generation by replaying ground-truth request traces via legacy CSV format.\n   518→\n   519→| Hypothesis | Target | Actual | Status |\n   520→|---|---|---|---|\n   521→| H1: Trace replay reduces TTFT | <100% TTFT | 78.8% (was 31,906%) | Supported |\n   522→| H2: Remaining E2E <25% | <25% E2E | 56.2% | Refuted |\n   523→| H3: Root cause workload-spec param | Identify param | All params <1% error | Refuted |\n   524→\n   525→#### Idea 2: Total-Context Linear Model with Feature Scaling\n   526→\n   527→Replace 2-feature model with 3-feature (`new_tokens + total_context`) using FairBatching formulation.\n   528→\n   529→| Hypothesis | Target | Actual | Status |\n   530→|---|---|---|---|\n   531→| H1: FairBatching 3-coeff OLS | <50% per-step MAPE | 56.2% (vs 83.1% baseline) | Partially Supported |\n   532→| H2: Feature scaling variants | <43.9% per-step MAPE | 83.0% best | Refuted |\n   533→| H3: BLIS E2E + 34B deep-dive | <50% E2E | 56.2% (identical to R2 trace) | Refuted |\n   534→| H4: LOWO generalization | <70% per-step MAPE | 2,162.7% | Refuted |\n   535→| H5: LOMO generalization | <80% per-step MAPE | 2,281.6% | Refuted |\n   536→\n   537→#### Idea 3: End-to-End Calibration via CMA-ES — Best Round 3 Result\n   538→\n   539→Jointly calibrate all LatencyModel coefficients by directly minimizing BLIS E2E mean error using CMA-ES.\n   540→\n   541→| Hypothesis | Target | Actual | Status |\n   542→|---|---|---|---|\n   543→| H1: CMA-ES + trace replay → E2E | <15% E2E | **15.1%** | Partially Supported |\n   544→| H2: Workload-spec mode | <50% E2E | Not tested (infra gap) | Not Tested |\n   545→| H3: Additive TTFT corrections | -5pp E2E | +2.1pp worse; TTFT 9.4% | Refuted for E2E |\n   546→| H4: LOWO generalization | All within 2× aggregate | 8/10 within 2× (15.1% agg) | Partially Supported |\n   547→| H5: LOMO cross-model transfer | <50% E2E | **14.8%** mean best-donor | Supported |\n   548→\n   549→#### Round 3 Per-Experiment BLIS E2E Results (CMA-ES, Best)\n   550→\n   551→| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error | Status |\n   552→|---|---|---|---|---|\n   553→| codellama-34b-general | **1.2%** | 69.3% | 102.7% | E2E solved |\n   554→| llama-2-70b-hf-codegen | **3.8%** | 67.6% | 111.6% | E2E solved |\n   555→| codellama-34b-codegen | **5.0%** | 68.9% | 90.2% | E2E solved |\n   556→| llama-2-70b-roleplay | **6.9%** | 67.6% | 117.0% | E2E solved |\n   557→| mixtral-general | 12.7% | 57.3% | 78.1% | Close |\n   558→| llama-2-70b-general | 16.2% | 82.5% | 72.0% | Unsolved |\n   559→| codellama-34b-roleplay | 17.5% | 66.2% | 135.4% | Unsolved |\n   560→| llama-2-7b-roleplay | 22.2% | 60.8% | 91.1% | Unsolved |\n   561→| mixtral-codegen | 30.9% | 66.4% | 41.5% | Unsolved |\n   562→| mixtral-roleplay | 34.2% | 69.3% | 34.5% | Unsolved |\n   563→| **MEAN** | **15.1%** | **67.6%** | **87.4%** | **4/10 solved** |\n   564→\n   565→#### Round 3 Critical Discovery: E2E ↔ ITL Tradeoff\n   566→\n   567→CMA-ES achieves 15.1% E2E but at 87.4% ITL (was 9.5% with trace replay baseline). **Root cause:** E2E = TTFT + Σ(ITL). Optimizing total E2E via shared coefficients produces arbitrarily bad ITL. CMA-ES uses `output_token_processing_time_us` as a proxy for missing simulation dynamics (e.g., llama-2-7b: 0→1,899µs). Need multi-objective or constrained optimization.\n   568→\n   569→#### Round 3 Critical Discovery: BLIS Simulates a \"Faster Universe\"\n   570→\n   571→With trace replay, every experiment shows BLIS completing requests in ~40% of real time. The overhead floor needs approximately doubling (from ~4ms to ~8ms for 7B, proportionally for larger models) to match real vLLM step cycle times.\n   572→\n   573→#### Round 3 Critical Discovery: Per-Step MAPE ↛ E2E\n   574→\n   575→A 27pp per-step improvement (83%→56%) has **ZERO impact** on BLIS E2E. The overhead floor dominates 70-90% of steps, completely masking GPU compute prediction improvements. **Optimize E2E directly, not per-step metrics.**\n   576→\n   577→## Cumulative Round History\n   578→\n   579→| Round | Ideas | Best E2E | Best ITL | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n   580→|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n   581→| R1 | Tree ensemble, analytical decomposition, evolutionary (deferred) | Not tested | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE (2x blackbox) | No BLIS integration |\n   582→| R2 | Bayesian calibration, regime ensemble | 427.8% mean (1/10 <10%) | 33.6% mean (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + regime structure | TTFT mismatch (31,906%) |\n   583→| R3 | Trace replay, total-context model, CMA-ES calibration | **15.1%** mean (4/10 <10%) | 87.4% mean (0/10 <10%) | Trace replay + CMA-ES (28.3x E2E improvement) | E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff |\n   584→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"9ecceeac-0f03-45a6-b46a-410c1b7bf385"}
