{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01TBa4bDt5pfDgNYFD2w5aM5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 1, H1: Physics-Informed Feature Set — FINDINGS\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Weakly Supported (per-experiment), Short-circuited (global)\n     4→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     5→\n     6→## Summary\n     7→\n     8→A 30-feature physics-informed feature set was engineered and evaluated with Ridge regression against the 2-feature blackbox baseline. The global model fails (301.7% MAPE) due to the 3-order-of-magnitude step time range across model configurations. However, per-experiment Ridge models show substantial improvement on the majority of experiments, validating the feature set's informativeness.\n     9→\n    10→## Experimental Setup\n    11→\n    12→- **Features:** 30 features in 6 groups — batch tokens (5), KV cache proxies (5), phase indicators (4), physics/roofline features (8), architecture metadata (3), interaction terms (5)\n    13→- **Model:** Ridge regression (sklearn, alpha=1.0) with StandardScaler\n    14→- **Split:** Temporal 60/20/20 within each experiment (shared infrastructure)\n    15→- **Data:** 122,752 steps from 16 experiments (4 models × 4 workloads, H100 GPUs)\n    16→\n    17→### Feature Set Limitations\n    18→\n    19→The HYPOTHESIS.md specified KV statistics derived from ProgressIndex (kv_mean, kv_max, kv_min, kv_std, kv_sum). However, **ProgressIndex is a per-request field not available in step-level ground-truth data** — the step-level traces only contain aggregate batch features. We substituted system-state KV proxies: `kv.usage_gpu_ratio`, `kv.blocks_free_gpu`, `kv.blocks_total_gpu`, `queue.running_depth`. This is a known data limitation documented in `problem.md`.\n    20→\n    21→Similarly, `attention_flops_ratio` and `gemm_flops_ratio` are set to constants (0.0 and 1.0) because computing attention FLOPs requires per-request KV cache lengths.\n    22→\n    23→## Results\n    24→\n    25→### Global Ridge (all experiments pooled)\n    26→\n    27→| Metric | Ridge (30f) | Blackbox (2f) | Naive Mean |\n    28→|--------|-------------|---------------|------------|\n    29→| MAPE | 301.7% | 670.2% | 861.4% |\n    30→| MSPE | +68.6% | +649.4% | — |\n    31→| Pearson r | 0.848 | 0.407 | — |\n    32→| p99 error | 1549.2% | 2343.5% | — |\n    33→\n    34→**Short-circuit triggered:** Global MAPE (301.7%) exceeds the 30% threshold. However, this threshold was designed for per-experiment models. The global model is structurally incapable of handling step times spanning 12μs to 250,000μs — no linear model can.\n    35→\n    36→### Per-Experiment Ridge (16 separate models)\n    37→\n    38→| Model | Workload | Ridge 30f MAPE | Blackbox MAPE | Δ |\n    39→|-------|----------|---------------|---------------|---|\n    40→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 9.0% | 9.2% | +0.2 |\n    41→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 9.3% | 123.5% | +114.2 |\n    42→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 15.7% | 19.0% | +3.3 |\n    43→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 15.9% | 14.2% | -1.7 |\n    44→| codellama-34b | codegen | 17.1% | 21.6% | +4.6 |\n    45→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 25.4% | 37.3% | +11.8 |\n    46→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 27.2% | 33.6% | +6.4 |\n    47→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 27.8% | 30.8% | +2.9 |\n    48→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 37.8% | 40.3% | +2.5 |\n    49→| llama-2-70b | general | 57.4% | 61.2% | +3.7 |\n    50→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 64.3% | 90.8% | +26.4 |\n    51→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 73.8% | 69.7% | -4.1 |\n    52→| codellama-34b | general | 143.7% | 151.1% | +7.4 |\n    53→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 181.0% | 128.6% | -52.5 |\n    54→| llama-2-7b | general | 283.3% | 72.9% | -210.4 |\n    55→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 484.9% | 222.8% | -262.0 |\n    56→\n    57→**Average per-experiment MAPE:** Ridge 30f = 92.1%, Blackbox = 70.4%\n    58→\n    59→### Top Features by Standardized Coefficient\n    60→\n    61→| Feature | Coefficient |\n    62→|---------|-------------|\n    63→| f_prefill_compute_intensity | +19845.7 |\n    64→| f_prefill_tokens | -13402.8 |\n    65→| f_kv_blocks_used | +7568.7 |\n    66→| f_decode_tokens | +6731.9 |\n    67→| f_arithmetic_intensity | -5327.5 |\n    68→\n    69→## Analysis\n    70→\n    71→### What Worked\n    72→- **6 experiments achieved < 30% MAPE** with Ridge, including 2 under 10% — proving the feature set captures meaningful physics\n    73→- **Reasoning workloads improved dramatically** (Llama-7B: 123.5% → 9.3%) — the physics features capture long-context behavior that raw token counts miss\n    74→- **Pearson r improved** from 0.407 (blackbox) to 0.848 (30f Ridge) globally\n    75→\n    76→### What Failed\n    77→- **4 experiments got significantly worse** than blackbox (Llama-7B-general: 72.9% → 283.3%, Mixtral-reasoning: 222.8% → 484.9%)\n    78→- The Ridge model is linear and cannot capture the nonlinear relationship between features and step time, especially for workloads with bimodal step time distributions\n    79→- System-state KV features (kv_blocks_used, running_depth) are informative but introduce temporal correlation — they describe *where* the system is, not *what* it's computing\n    80→\n    81→### Root Cause of Failures\n    82→The worst experiments (general workloads, Mixtral-reasoning) have highly variable batch compositions. A linear model overweights features that work for the majority of steps, producing extreme predictions on atypical batches. This motivates tree-based models (h2) which can learn nonlinear decision boundaries.\n    83→\n    84→## Verdict\n    85→\n    86→**The 30-feature set is informative but requires a nonlinear model.** Per-experiment Ridge shows clear improvement on 12/16 experiments, validating the feature engineering. The short-circuit threshold on the global model is misleading for this problem structure. Proceed to h2-model (XGBoost).\n    87→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"1cbf7541-43ee-4fc9-8028-935b2cffceba"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01WdnYLK1b7gR4BXe18g2v8c","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 2, H1: Analytical Component Decomposition — FINDINGS\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Not Supported (formal criteria), Informative (per-experiment signal)\n     4→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     5→\n     6→## Summary\n     7→\n     8→The 4-component analytical decomposition (prefill GEMM, prefill attention, decode GEMM, decode attention) was computed for all 122,752 steps and correlated with observed step duration. The formal hypothesis criteria (≥2 components with Pearson r > 0.8 on pure-phase subsets) is not met — primarily because vLLM's chunked prefill produces only **6 pure-prefill steps** across the entire dataset. Per-experiment correlations reveal strong signal for general workloads but weak signal for reasoning/roleplay.\n     9→\n    10→## Experimental Setup\n    11→\n    12→- **Method:** Correlation analysis (no train/test split — this is a structural validation)\n    13→- **Components computed:**\n    14→  - Prefill GEMM FLOPs: QKV + O projections + MLP (gate/up/down), scaled by architecture and TP\n    15→  - Prefill Attention FLOPs: QK^T + AV with causal masking (avg context ≈ P/2)\n    16→  - Decode GEMM FLOPs: same structure, decode tokens\n    17→  - Decode Attention FLOPs: **set to 0** — per-request KV cache lengths unavailable in step-level data\n    18→- **Architecture parameters:** Loaded from HuggingFace config.json for each of 4 models\n    19→- **Hardware:** H100 peak_flops = 989.5 TFLOP/s BF16 (no MFU correction — raw analytical)\n    20→- **Data:** 122,752 steps from 16 experiments\n    21→\n    22→## Results\n    23→\n    24→### Phase Breakdown\n    25→\n    26→| Phase | Steps | % of Total |\n    27→|-------|-------|-----------|\n    28→| Pure prefill (decode_tokens = 0) | 6 | 0.005% |\n    29→| Pure decode (prefill_tokens = 0) | 98,961 | 80.6% |\n    30→| Mixed batch | 23,789 | 19.4% |\n    31→\n    32→**Critical finding:** vLLM's chunked prefill scheduling produces almost no pure-prefill batches. The hypothesis assumed pure-phase subsets would be large enough for meaningful correlation analysis — this assumption is wrong.\n    33→\n    34→### Correlation on Pure-Phase Subsets\n    35→\n    36→| Subset | Component | Pearson r | n_steps |\n    37→|--------|-----------|-----------|---------|\n    38→| pure_prefill | prefill_gemm_us | N/A | 6 |\n    39→| pure_prefill | prefill_attn_us | N/A | 6 |\n    40→| pure_prefill | total_analytical_us | N/A | 6 |\n    41→| pure_prefill | batch.prefill_tokens (baseline) | N/A | 6 |\n    42→| pure_decode | decode_gemm_us | 0.4367 | 98,961 |\n    43→| pure_decode | decode_attn_us | N/A | 98,961 |\n    44→| pure_decode | total_analytical_us | 0.4367 | 98,961 |\n    45→| pure_decode | batch.decode_tokens (baseline) | 0.4202 | 98,961 |\n    46→| all | total_analytical_us | 0.3350 | 122,752 |\n    47→\n    48→**Hypothesis verdict: 0/4 components achieve r > 0.8. FAIL.**\n    49→\n    50→### Per-Experiment Correlations (total_analytical_us)\n    51→\n    52→| Model | Workload | Pearson r |\n    53→|-------|----------|-----------|\n    54→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 0.9420 |\n    55→| llama-2-7b | general | 0.8593 |\n    56→| codellama-34b | general | 0.6436 |\n    57→| llama-2-70b | general | 0.5954 |\n    58→| codellama-34b | codegen | 0.4343 |\n    59→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 0.3600 |\n    60→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 0.3380 |\n    61→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 0.2528 |\n    62→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 0.2490 |\n    63→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 0.2355 |\n    64→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 0.2024 |\n    65→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 0.1674 |\n    66→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 0.1207 |\n    67→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 0.1171 |\n    68→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 0.1160 |\n    69→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 0.0216 |\n    70→\n    71→## Analysis\n    72→\n    73→### Why Pure-Phase Correlation Fails\n    74→\n    75→1. **Only 6 pure-prefill steps exist.** vLLM's continuous batching + chunked prefill means nearly every batch contains at least one decode request. The experimental design assumed pure-phase batches would be common — they are not under continuous batching.\n    76→\n    77→2. **Decode attention is zero.** Without per-request KV cache lengths (ProgressIndex), decode attention FLOPs cannot be computed. Since 80.6% of steps are pure-decode, the analytical decomposition is missing the dominant time component for the majority of steps.\n    78→\n    79→3. **Decode GEMM correlates at r=0.437** — meaningful but not strong. Decode GEMM FLOPs are proportional to `decode_tokens * model_size`, which captures the linear scaling but misses the nonlinear effects of varying KV cache lengths and batch composition.\n    80→\n    81→### Where the Decomposition Has Signal\n    82→\n    83→The per-experiment correlations reveal a clear pattern:\n    84→- **\"General\" workloads show strong correlation** (Mixtral r=0.94, Llama-7B r=0.86) — these have moderate batch sizes and relatively uniform batch compositions where GEMM dominates\n    85→- **Reasoning/roleplay workloads show weak correlation** (r < 0.25) — these have long contexts where attention (KV-dependent) dominates over GEMM, and the missing decode_attn makes the analytical estimate incorrect\n    86→\n    87→### Structural Limitation\n    88→\n    89→The decomposition's backbone is correct in principle — GEMM and attention are the dominant compute components of transformer inference. However, **the step-level data lacks the per-request granularity needed to compute attention FLOPs**. The feature gap identified in `problem.md` (no per-request KV cache lengths) is the binding constraint, not the decomposition methodology.\n    90→\n    91→## Verdict\n    92→\n    93→**The formal hypothesis is not supported** (0/4 components > 0.8), but the root cause is data availability, not decomposition structure:\n    94→\n    95→1. Pure-phase subsets are too small (6 prefill steps) for meaningful correlation — chunked prefill invalidates the experimental design\n    96→2. Decode attention is uncomputable without per-request KV lengths — the most important component for 80.6% of steps is missing\n    97→3. Per-experiment correlations show the decomposition has signal where GEMM dominates (general workloads), confirming the physics is sound\n    98→\n    99→**This is an informational finding, not a kill signal for the decomposition approach.** If per-request ProgressIndex were available in step-level data (via LatencyModel interface extension), the decomposition would be fully computable and likely correlate much more strongly.\n   100→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"3476e8a0-e566-461f-9e75-0d204f6597fc"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01WbkViKrvbT7Lq5xzDrgsrT","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 1, H3: XGBoost Cross-Configuration Generalization — FINDINGS\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Not Supported\n     4→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     5→\n     6→## Summary\n     7→\n     8→A single XGBoost model does not generalize across unseen model configurations (LOMO avg 2559.7% MAPE) or workload types (LOWO avg 109.7% MAPE). The model learns configuration-specific patterns (step time scale, KV cache state distribution) that do not transfer. This confirms that **per-model XGBoost models are necessary** — consistent with how production inference simulators (Vidur, Splitwise) operate with per-model profiling.\n     9→\n    10→## Experimental Setup\n    11→\n    12→- **Model:** XGBoost with max_depth=6, n_estimators=300, learning_rate=0.05\n    13→- **Features:** 30 physics-informed features from h1\n    14→- **Validation:** 25% of training data held out temporally for early stopping (larger than h2's 20%)\n    15→- **CV schemes:**\n    16→  - LOMO: 4 folds, one model held out per fold (train on 12 experiments, test on 4)\n    17→  - LOWO: 4 folds, one workload held out per fold (train on 12 experiments, test on 4)\n    18→- **Data:** 122,752 steps from 16 experiments\n    19→\n    20→## Results\n    21→\n    22→### Leave-One-Model-Out (LOMO)\n    23→\n    24→| Holdout Model | Train Size | Test Size | Valid MAPE | Test MAPE | MSPE | Pearson r |\n    25→|---------------|-----------|----------|------------|-----------|------|-----------|\n    26→| llama-2-70b | 98,892 | 23,860 | 42.7% | 65.5% | +33.1% | 0.947 |\n    27→| codellama-34b | 93,658 | 29,094 | 209.2% | 78.9% | +48.3% | 0.965 |\n    28→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 99,988 | 22,764 | 57.3% | 186.6% | +154.5% | 0.905 |\n    29→| llama-2-7b | 75,718 | 47,034 | 36.5% | 9908.0% | +9907.9% | 0.519 |\n    30→\n    31→**LOMO Average: 2559.7% MAPE**\n    32→\n    33→### LOMO Per-Experiment Breakdown\n    34→\n    35→| Holdout | Model | Workload | MAPE | MSPE |\n    36→|---------|-------|----------|------|------|\n    37→| codellama-34b | codellama-34b | roleplay | 30.0% | +6.0% |\n    38→| llama-2-70b | llama-2-70b | roleplay | 32.0% | -0.8% |\n    39→| llama-2-70b | llama-2-70b | codegen | 49.4% | -11.7% |\n    40→| codellama-34b | codellama-34b | reasoning | 53.8% | -40.6% |\n    41→| llama-2-70b | llama-2-70b | general | 60.2% | +38.2% |\n    42→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 77.5% | -42.3% |\n    43→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 95.9% | +74.0% |\n    44→| codellama-34b | codellama-34b | general | 105.2% | +82.9% |\n    45→| codellama-34b | codellama-34b | codegen | 120.5% | +114.4% |\n    46→| llama-2-70b | llama-2-70b | reasoning | 147.3% | +145.0% |\n    47→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 185.4% | +169.6% |\n    48→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 359.5% | +352.4% |\n    49→| llama-2-7b | llama-2-7b | reasoning | 461.7% | +461.3% |\n    50→| llama-2-7b | llama-2-7b | general | 6781.0% | +6781.0% |\n    51→| llama-2-7b | llama-2-7b | codegen | 12471.2% | +12471.2% |\n    52→| llama-2-7b | llama-2-7b | roleplay | 12680.0% | +12680.0% |\n    53→\n    54→### Leave-One-Workload-Out (LOWO)\n    55→\n    56→| Holdout Workload | Train Size | Test Size | Valid MAPE | Test MAPE | MSPE | Pearson r |\n    57→|------------------|-----------|----------|------------|-----------|------|-----------|\n    58→| roleplay | 85,675 | 37,077 | 87.5% | 30.6% | +11.0% | 0.737 |\n    59→| reasoning | 104,668 | 18,084 | 103.1% | 53.2% | -37.6% | -0.411 |\n    60→| codegen | 85,725 | 37,027 | 57.0% | 53.4% | +42.9% | 0.737 |\n    61→| general | 92,188 | 30,564 | 96.6% | 301.6% | +286.0% | 0.236 |\n    62→\n    63→**LOWO Average: 109.7% MAPE**\n    64→\n    65→### LOWO Per-Experiment Breakdown (Top/Bottom 5)\n    66→\n    67→| Holdout | Model | Workload | MAPE | MSPE |\n    68→|---------|-------|----------|------|------|\n    69→| codegen | mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 20.4% | +4.2% |\n    70→| general | llama-2-7b | general | 23.1% | -0.3% |\n    71→| reasoning | llama-2-7b | reasoning | 24.5% | +21.9% |\n    72→| roleplay | llama-2-70b | roleplay | 25.5% | -2.4% |\n    73→| roleplay | codellama-34b | roleplay | 27.4% | +6.8% |\n    74→| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |\n    75→| codegen | codellama-34b | codegen | 121.4% | +118.1% |\n    76→| general | codellama-34b | general | 131.0% | +114.2% |\n    77→| general | mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 1299.0% | +1292.4% |\n    78→\n    79→### Feature Importance Stability\n    80→\n    81→**LOMO top features (by avg importance):**\n    82→\n    83→| Feature | Avg Importance | Avg Rank | Rank StdDev |\n    84→|---------|---------------|----------|-------------|\n    85→| f_kv_blocks_used | 0.4280 | 2.2 | 2.5 |\n    86→| f_kv_blocks_free | 0.1096 | 7.0 | 4.1 |\n    87→| f_num_decode_reqs | 0.1043 | 7.5 | 8.4 |\n    88→| f_decode_tokens | 0.0599 | 8.0 | 5.9 |\n    89→| f_decode_memory_intensity | 0.0505 | 6.0 | 2.9 |\n    90→\n    91→Top-10 average rank StdDev: **4.1** (moderate stability)\n    92→\n    93→**LOWO top features:**\n    94→\n    95→| Feature | Avg Importance | Avg Rank | Rank StdDev |\n    96→|---------|---------------|----------|-------------|\n    97→| f_intensity_x_moe | 0.3985 | 6.8 | 11.5 |\n    98→| f_decode_memory_intensity | 0.2409 | 3.2 | 3.2 |\n    99→| f_arithmetic_intensity | 0.1221 | 3.0 | 0.8 |\n   100→| f_running_depth | 0.0508 | 7.5 | 3.8 |\n   101→| f_kv_blocks_used | 0.0526 | 5.0 | 1.8 |\n   102→\n   103→Top-10 average rank StdDev: **3.4** (slightly more stable than LOMO)\n   104→\n   105→## Analysis\n   106→\n   107→### Why LOMO Fails Catastrophically\n   108→\n   109→**Llama-2-7B held out (9908% MAPE):** This is the most extreme failure. Llama-2-7B runs on 1 GPU (tp=1) with step times in the 12–500μs range. The model trained on 70B (tp=4), 34B (tp=2), and Mixtral (tp=2) learns a step time scale 10–100x larger. The features encode absolute values (total FLOPs, kv_blocks_used) that scale with model size, so the trained model predicts step times orders of magnitude too high for 7B.\n   110→\n   111→**Mixtral held out (186.6% MAPE):** MoE architecture has fundamentally different compute patterns. The MoE-specific features (`f_is_moe`, `f_active_param_ratio`, `f_intensity_x_moe`) provide metadata but don't capture expert routing dynamics. Dense models can't predict MoE behavior.\n   112→\n   113→### Why LOWO Fails Less Severely\n   114→\n   115→Workload generalization is more feasible because the same model configuration produces step times at the same scale regardless of workload. The failures are concentrated in \"general\" workloads (301.6%) which have the most diverse batch compositions — the model trained on codegen/roleplay/reasoning doesn't encounter the specific batch patterns of general workloads.\n   116→\n   117→### Feature Stability Interpretation\n   118→\n   119→- **LOMO:** `f_kv_blocks_used` dominates (0.43 importance) with high stability (rank StdDev 2.5) — this is a system-state feature that captures step time scale per model configuration. It's informative but not transferable.\n   120→- **LOWO:** Physics features (`f_arithmetic_intensity`, `f_decode_memory_intensity`) are more important and stable — these capture computation structure that transfers across workloads better than system state.\n   121→\n   122→## Verdict\n   123→\n   124→**The hypothesis is not supported.** A single XGBoost model cannot generalize across unseen model configurations. This is a fundamental structural limitation, not a model capacity issue:\n   125→\n   126→1. Step times span 3+ orders of magnitude across model sizes\n   127→2. The features encode absolute values (FLOPs, KV blocks) that are model-size-specific\n   128→3. Architecture metadata features (`f_model_id`, `f_tp_degree`, `f_is_moe`) are insufficient to bridge the scale gap\n   129→\n   130→### Implications for Go Integration\n   131→\n   132→The failed generalization confirms that **per-model (or per-experiment) XGBoost models are the practical deployment path**. This is consistent with existing practice:\n   133→- **Vidur** requires per-model profiling runs\n   134→- **Splitwise** uses per-model analytical models\n   135→- **BLIS blackbox** already uses per-model alpha/beta coefficients from `defaults.yaml`\n   136→\n   137→The recommended Go integration ships one serialized XGBoost model per model configuration, selected via `--model` flag — analogous to how `defaults.yaml` currently selects alpha/beta coefficients per model.\n   138→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"28966801-c404-449f-b711-9efa28c23370"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JXncBC82tjXUPxJnJj5RRt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 2, H2: Learned Correction Factors — FINDINGS\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Not Supported\n     4→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     5→\n     6→## Summary\n     7→\n     8→Learned multiplicative correction factors on the analytical decomposition fail to achieve competitive per-step MAPE. The 9-parameter global model achieves 96.0% average MAPE; the 36-parameter per-model variant achieves 78.7% — both worse than the blackbox baseline (70.4%). The analytical backbone is structurally incomplete without per-request KV cache information, and no amount of correction factor tuning can compensate.\n     9→\n    10→## Experimental Setup\n    11→\n    12→- **Model variants:**\n    13→  - **9-parameter global:** 4 component factors + 1 overhead + 4 MFU discounts, shared across all models\n    14→  - **36-parameter per-model:** 9 parameters × 4 model families\n    15→- **Fitting:** scipy.optimize.least_squares with 'trf' method, log-ratio objective: `min Σ (log(predicted/actual))²` for symmetric relative errors\n    16→- **Bounds:** Component factors ∈ [0.01, 100], overhead ∈ [0, 1e6], MFU ∈ [0.01, 1.0]\n    17→- **Split:** Temporal 60/20/20 (global split across all experiments)\n    18→- **Baseline:** Per-experiment blackbox (2-feature linear regression)\n    19→\n    20→## Results\n    21→\n    22→### Aggregate Metrics\n    23→\n    24→| Variant | Avg MAPE | Median MAPE | Avg MSPE | Exps < 15% | Exps < 25% |\n    25→|---------|----------|-------------|----------|------------|------------|\n    26→| 9-param global | 96.0% | 83.3% | +4.2% | 0/16 | 0/16 |\n    27→| 36-param per-model | 78.7% | 79.4% | +3.7% | 0/16 | 0/16 |\n    28→| Blackbox baseline | 70.4% | — | — | 1/16 | 1/16 |\n    29→\n    30→### Per-Experiment Results (36-parameter variant)\n    31→\n    32→| Model | Workload | 36-param MAPE | Blackbox MAPE | 36-param MSPE | 36-param r |\n    33→|-------|----------|--------------|---------------|---------------|-----------|\n    34→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 41.9% | 128.6% | +14.6% | 0.523 |\n    35→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 42.9% | 40.3% | +27.9% | 0.560 |\n    36→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 58.6% | 69.7% | +29.9% | 0.422 |\n    37→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 70.7% | 30.8% | +66.9% | 0.438 |\n    38→| codellama-34b | general | 74.7% | 151.1% | -34.2% | 0.420 |\n    39→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 75.3% | 14.2% | -72.8% | 0.962 |\n    40→| llama-2-70b | general | 76.1% | 61.2% | -70.3% | 0.268 |\n    41→| llama-2-7b | general | 78.9% | 72.9% | -78.7% | 0.669 |\n    42→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 79.9% | 90.8% | +20.4% | 0.687 |\n    43→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 83.5% | 123.5% | -61.6% | 0.163 |\n    44→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 84.4% | 19.0% | +83.6% | 0.184 |\n    45→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 86.0% | 33.6% | +82.8% | 0.346 |\n    46→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 91.4% | 37.3% | -90.5% | 0.925 |\n    47→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 92.4% | 222.8% | -82.2% | 0.852 |\n    48→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 99.7% | 9.2% | +99.7% | 0.657 |\n    49→| codellama-34b | codegen | 123.4% | 21.6% | +123.0% | 0.228 |\n    50→\n    51→### Fitted Parameters (9-param global)\n    52→\n    53→| Parameter | Value | Interpretation |\n    54→|-----------|-------|---------------|\n    55→| prefill_gemm_factor | 0.014 | Prefill GEMM heavily discounted (analytical overestimates) |\n    56→| prefill_attn_factor | 4.17 | Prefill attention amplified (compensating for causal masking approximation) |\n    57→| decode_gemm_factor | 0.49 | Decode GEMM at ~50% of analytical (MFU effect) |\n    58→| decode_attn_factor | 39.5 | **Extreme amplification** — trying to compensate for zero decode_attn |\n    59→| overhead_us | 85.7 | Base overhead per step |\n    60→| mfu_prefill_gemm | 0.998 | Near peak (unrealistic) |\n    61→| mfu_prefill_attn | 0.881 | Reasonable |\n    62→| mfu_decode_gemm | 0.744 | Reasonable |\n    63→| mfu_decode_attn | 0.500 | At lower bound (inert — decode_attn is zero) |\n    64→\n    65→### Fitted Parameters (36-param, per-model overhead)\n    66→\n    67→All 4 model families converged to **overhead = 0**, meaning the optimizer pushes all explanatory power into the component factors. MFU values vary from 0.49 (Mixtral) to 0.87 (Llama-70B), which are physically plausible.\n    68→\n    69→## Analysis\n    70→\n    71→### Why Correction Factors Fail\n    72→\n    73→1. **Missing backbone component:** `decode_attn_us = 0` for all steps because per-request KV cache lengths are unavailable. For pure-decode batches (80.6% of data), the analytical prediction is `decode_gemm_factor × decode_gemm_us + overhead`. This misses the attention component entirely, which is the dominant cost for long-context decode batches.\n    74→\n    75→2. **The optimizer compensates pathologically:** `decode_attn_factor = 39.5` is the optimizer trying to amplify a zero signal. Since `decode_attn_us = 0`, this parameter is completely inert. The `overhead` term (85.7μs) and `decode_gemm_factor` (0.49) absorb what they can, but cannot model KV-length-dependent variation.\n    76→\n    77→3. **MSPE is low but meaningless:** Average |MSPE| = 3.7% appears good, but this is because the errors are enormous in both directions (some steps are overestimated by 100%+, others underestimated by 90%+), and they happen to roughly cancel in the mean.\n    78→\n    79→### Comparison with Blackbox\n    80→\n    81→The 36-parameter model is **worse** than the 2-parameter blackbox on average (78.7% vs 70.4%). This is remarkable: 36 free parameters with physics-based features perform worse than 2 coefficients on raw token counts. The explanation is that the blackbox model's `decode_tokens` feature is a *better* proxy for decode step time than the analytically-derived `decode_gemm_us` — because `decode_tokens` implicitly correlates with batch size, which correlates with attention cost, while `decode_gemm_us` explicitly ignores attention.\n    82→\n    83→### Where Correction Factors Help\n    84→\n    85→The model does improve a few experiments relative to blackbox:\n    86→- Llama-70B-roleplay: 128.6% → 41.9% (blackbox fails badly here; corrections help)\n    87→- CodeLlama-general: 151.1% → 74.7%\n    88→- Llama-7B-reasoning: 123.5% → 83.5%\n    89→\n    90→These are experiments where the blackbox is particularly bad, and any structured prediction helps.\n    91→\n    92→### Parameter Efficiency\n    93→\n    94→Moving from 9 to 36 parameters reduces average MAPE by 17.3 pp (96.0% → 78.7%). This is a meaningful but insufficient improvement — 4× more parameters for 18% relative improvement suggests diminishing returns. The bottleneck is the backbone, not the correction factor count.\n    95→\n    96→## Verdict\n    97→\n    98→**The hypothesis is not supported.** Learned correction factors on an incomplete analytical backbone cannot compete with even the simple blackbox model. The root cause is identical to h1: **decode attention FLOPs are uncomputable without per-request KV cache lengths**, making the decomposition structurally incomplete for the 80.6% of steps that are pure-decode.\n    99→\n   100→### Comparison with Idea 1\n   101→\n   102→| Metric | Idea 2 (36-param) | Idea 1 (XGBoost) | Blackbox |\n   103→|--------|-------------------|-------------------|----------|\n   104→| Avg MAPE | 78.7% | 34.0% | 70.4% |\n   105→| Exps < 15% | 0/16 | 5/16 | 1/16 |\n   106→| Exps < 25% | 0/16 | 6/16 | 1/16 |\n   107→| Parameters | 36 | ~30K per model | 3 |\n   108→\n   109→Idea 1's XGBoost dramatically outperforms Idea 2's correction factors because:\n   110→1. XGBoost uses **system-state KV features** (kv_blocks_used, running_depth) as proxies for per-request KV information — imperfect but informative\n   111→2. XGBoost can learn **nonlinear relationships** between features and step time\n   112→3. Per-experiment training gives XGBoost implicit architecture-specific calibration\n   113→\n   114→### Recommendation\n   115→\n   116→**Abandon Idea 2** in its current form. The analytical decomposition is sound in principle but cannot be validated or deployed without per-request KV cache information. If the `LatencyModel` interface is extended to provide per-request `ProgressIndex`, Idea 2 could be revisited — the decomposition + correction factors approach would have the advantage of human interpretability (9 auditable constants vs 30K tree parameters) and smaller binary size.\n   117→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"b8264ea8-444c-44c8-b7d6-3318610cf1d8"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01EaHPRyEmuWt1tsBWUCnk9p","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Idea 1, H2: XGBoost Per-Experiment Models — FINDINGS\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** Weakly Supported\n     4→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     5→\n     6→## Summary\n     7→\n     8→Per-experiment XGBoost models with the 30-feature physics-informed set achieve an average 34.0% MAPE across 16 experiments — a 2x improvement over the blackbox baseline (70.4%). Five experiments achieve < 15% MAPE. The model is the strongest step-time predictor evaluated in this research campaign, but does not meet the < 15% MAPE target on all 16 experiments.\n     9→\n    10→## Experimental Setup\n    11→\n    12→- **Model:** XGBoost (per-experiment, 16 separate models)\n    13→- **Features:** 30 physics-informed features from h1\n    14→- **Hyperparameter search:** Grid over max_depth=[4,6,8], n_estimators=[100,300], learning_rate=[0.05,0.1], with min_child_weight=5, subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.8\n    15→- **Split:** Temporal 60/20/20 within each experiment; validation set used for early stopping\n    16→- **Baseline:** Per-experiment blackbox (2-feature linear regression)\n    17→\n    18→## Results\n    19→\n    20→### Per-Experiment XGBoost vs Blackbox\n    21→\n    22→| Model | Workload | XGB MAPE | BB MAPE | Δ | XGB MSPE | XGB r |\n    23→|-------|----------|----------|---------|---|----------|-------|\n    24→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 9.1% | 9.2% | +0.1 | +0.8% | 0.784 |\n    25→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 9.8% | 14.2% | +4.4 | +3.9% | 0.950 |\n    26→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 13.0% | 123.5% | +110.5 | +9.0% | 0.608 |\n    27→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 14.0% | 37.3% | +23.3 | +2.1% | 0.920 |\n    28→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 14.7% | 19.0% | +4.3 | +4.0% | 0.271 |\n    29→| codellama-34b | codegen | 16.1% | 21.6% | +5.5 | +3.9% | 0.448 |\n    30→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 25.7% | 30.8% | +5.1 | +9.6% | 0.730 |\n    31→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 28.3% | 33.6% | +5.3 | +14.5% | 0.660 |\n    32→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 28.3% | 128.6% | +100.2 | +13.9% | 0.802 |\n    33→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 30.9% | 40.3% | +9.4 | +11.3% | 0.882 |\n    34→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 31.1% | 90.8% | +59.7 | +14.4% | 0.707 |\n    35→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 33.4% | 69.7% | +36.3 | +19.3% | 0.490 |\n    36→| llama-2-7b | general | 50.9% | 72.9% | +22.0 | -50.4% | 0.318 |\n    37→| llama-2-70b | general | 55.4% | 61.2% | +5.7 | +32.6% | 0.217 |\n    38→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 62.4% | 222.8% | +160.5 | +52.6% | 0.826 |\n    39→| codellama-34b | general | 121.5% | 151.1% | +29.6 | +95.1% | 0.435 |\n    40→\n    41→### Aggregate Metrics\n    42→\n    43→| Metric | XGBoost | Blackbox |\n    44→|--------|---------|----------|\n    45→| Average MAPE | 34.0% | 70.4% |\n    46→| Median MAPE | 28.3% | — |\n    47→| Experiments < 15% | 5/16 | 1/16 |\n    48→| Experiments < 25% | 6/16 | 1/16 |\n    49→| Experiments < 30% | 9/16 | 2/16 |\n    50→\n    51→### Hyperparameter Selection\n    52→\n    53→The grid search consistently selected **max_depth=4, n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.05** for 13/16 experiments. This conservative configuration suggests the model is *underfitting*, not overfitting — more expressive features (especially per-request KV cache lengths) would help more than deeper trees.\n    54→\n    55→### Top Features by XGBoost Importance\n    56→\n    57→Across experiments, the most important features were:\n    58→1. `f_kv_blocks_used` — KV cache occupancy (system state proxy for total context length)\n    59→2. `f_decode_tokens` — number of decode tokens in batch\n    60→3. `f_running_depth` — number of running requests (proxy for batch complexity)\n    61→4. `f_prefill_tokens` — number of prefill tokens\n    62→5. `f_num_decode_reqs` — decode request count\n    63→\n    64→## Analysis\n    65→\n    66→### Strengths\n    67→- **2x improvement over blackbox** on average (34.0% vs 70.4%)\n    68→- **Reasoning workloads dramatically improved:** Llama-7B-reasoning 123.5% → 13.0%, CodeLlama-reasoning 37.3% → 14.0%\n    69→- **XGBoost beats or matches blackbox on every experiment** — no regressions\n    70→- **Systematic bias is moderate:** Most experiments have MSPE < 20%, meaning errors are relatively symmetric\n    71→\n    72→### Weaknesses\n    73→- **\"General\" workloads remain difficult:** CodeLlama-general (121.5%), Llama-70B-general (55.4%), Llama-7B-general (50.9%). These workloads have high step time variance with diverse batch compositions\n    74→- **Missing per-request KV features:** The model relies on system-state KV proxies (kv_blocks_used, running_depth) which are informative but imprecise. Per-request ProgressIndex would directly capture attention FLOPs\n    75→- **Some experiments have high MSPE:** CodeLlama-general (+95.1%), Mixtral-reasoning (+52.6%) show systematic overprediction\n    76→\n    77→### Error Pattern Analysis\n    78→\n    79→The worst experiments share two characteristics:\n    80→1. **High step time variance** — \"general\" workloads mix short decode-only batches with occasional large prefill+decode batches\n    81→2. **KV cache state is a poor proxy** — kv_blocks_used captures total cache occupancy but not per-request distribution. Two batches with identical total KV blocks but different per-request distributions (many short vs few long) have very different attention costs\n    82→\n    83→## Verdict\n    84→\n    85→**XGBoost with physics-informed features is the strongest approach tested**, achieving 2x improvement over blackbox. However, it falls short of the < 15% MAPE target on 11/16 experiments. The primary bottleneck is **missing per-request KV cache information**, not model capacity. The consistently shallow trees (depth=4) and feature importance analysis both point to insufficient input features rather than insufficient model complexity.\n    86→\n    87→### Recommendations\n    88→1. **For BLIS integration:** Per-experiment XGBoost models with 30 features are viable as a drop-in replacement for the blackbox model, improving 14/16 experiments\n    89→2. **For further improvement:** Extend the `LatencyModel` interface to pass per-request `ProgressIndex` to the step-time predictor, enabling per-request KV statistics (kv_mean, kv_max, kv_sum)\n    90→3. **Practical deployment:** Ship per-model XGBoost models loaded from JSON alongside `defaults.yaml`\n    91→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"16dc8567-3f45-4cbd-b89e-4757d2203cc0"}
