{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01GkucEMB7tiGDJj5oJBa4CG","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# StepML Research: WP4/5 Decision Gate\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-02-26\n     4→**Branch:** `stepml-experiments`\n     5→**Status:** Research complete. Integration decision required.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Executive Summary\n    10→\n    11→Three research ideas were explored to replace BLIS's blackbox latency model (3-coefficient linear regression on `prefill_tokens` and `decode_tokens`) with a data-driven step-time predictor achieving <10% workload-level E2E mean error:\n    12→\n    13→| Idea | Approach | Best Result | Verdict |\n    14→|------|----------|-------------|---------|\n    15→| 1. Tree Ensemble | XGBoost with 30 physics-informed features | **34.0% avg MAPE** (2x better than blackbox) | **Best available** |\n    16→| 2. Analytical Decomposition | FLOPs decomposition + learned corrections | 78.7% avg MAPE (worse than blackbox) | **Abandoned** |\n    17→| 3. Evolutionary Synthesis | LLM-guided MAP-Elites | Not attempted | **Deferred** |\n    18→\n    19→**Bottom line:** No approach meets the original <10% E2E mean error target on all 16 experiments. Per-experiment XGBoost (Idea 1) is the strongest result — a 2x improvement over blackbox with zero regressions. The binding constraint is **missing per-request KV cache lengths** in step-level training data.\n    20→\n    21→---\n    22→\n    23→## Leaderboard\n    24→\n    25→### Per-Step MAPE (sorted best to worst)\n    26→\n    27→| Rank | Model | Avg MAPE | Exps <15% | Exps <25% | Exps <30% | vs Blackbox |\n    28→|------|-------|----------|-----------|-----------|-----------|-------------|\n    29→| 1 | **XGBoost per-experiment (Idea 1 h2)** | **34.0%** | **5/16** | **6/16** | **9/16** | **+2x better** |\n    30→| 2 | Blackbox 2-feature baseline | 70.4% | 1/16 | 1/16 | 2/16 | — |\n    31→| 3 | Correction factors 36-param (Idea 2 h2) | 78.7% | 0/16 | 0/16 | 0/16 | -12% worse |\n    32→| 4 | Ridge 30-feature per-experiment (Idea 1 h1) | 92.1% | 2/16 | 3/16 | 6/16 | -31% worse |\n    33→| 5 | Correction factors 9-param (Idea 2 h2) | 96.0% | 0/16 | 0/16 | 0/16 | -36% worse |\n    34→| 6 | Ridge 30-feature global (Idea 1 h1) | 301.7% | — | — | — | Short-circuited |\n    35→\n    36→### Per-Experiment Detail (XGBoost — the winning model)\n    37→\n    38→| Model | Workload | XGB MAPE | BB MAPE | Improvement |\n    39→|-------|----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n    40→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | general | 9.1% | 9.2% | Match |\n    41→| llama-2-70b-hf | reasoning | 9.8% | 14.2% | +4.4 pp |\n    42→| llama-2-7b | reasoning | 13.0% | 123.5% | **+110.5 pp** |\n    43→| codellama-34b | reasoning | 14.0% | 37.3% | +23.3 pp |\n    44→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | codegen | 14.7% | 19.0% | +4.3 pp |\n    45→| codellama-34b | codegen | 16.1% | 21.6% | +5.5 pp |\n    46→| codellama-34b | roleplay | 25.7% | 30.8% | +5.1 pp |\n    47→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | roleplay | 28.3% | 33.6% | +5.3 pp |\n    48→| llama-2-70b | roleplay | 28.3% | 128.6% | **+100.2 pp** |\n    49→| llama-2-7b | roleplay | 30.9% | 40.3% | +9.4 pp |\n    50→| llama-2-70b-hf | codegen | 31.1% | 90.8% | **+59.7 pp** |\n    51→| llama-2-7b | codegen | 33.4% | 69.7% | +36.3 pp |\n    52→| llama-2-7b | general | 50.9% | 72.9% | +22.0 pp |\n    53→| llama-2-70b | general | 55.4% | 61.2% | +5.7 pp |\n    54→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | reasoning | 62.4% | 222.8% | **+160.5 pp** |\n    55→| codellama-34b | general | 121.5% | 151.1% | +29.6 pp |\n    56→\n    57→**XGBoost beats or matches blackbox on all 16 experiments — zero regressions.**\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→\n    61→## Success Criteria Evaluation\n    62→\n    63→### Priority 1: Workload-Level E2E Mean Fidelity\n    64→\n    65→| Criterion | Target | Achieved | Status |\n    66→|-----------|--------|----------|--------|\n    67→| E2E mean error <10% on all 16 experiments | <10% | **Not tested** (per-step MAPE only) | UNKNOWN |\n    68→| Statistically significant improvement | p < 0.05 | XGB beats BB on 16/16 experiments | LIKELY MET |\n    69→| Per-step MAPE as diagnostic | Informational | 34.0% avg (5/16 < 15%) | REPORTED |\n    70→\n    71→**Gap:** Workload-level E2E mean error was not computed because that requires running BLIS simulation with the trained model as the latency backend. Per-step MAPE is a diagnostic, not the primary metric. E2E mean error could be better (if per-step errors cancel) or worse (if they compound) than per-step MAPE.\n    72→\n    73→### Priority 2: Per-Metric Accuracy (TTFT, ITL)\n    74→\n    75→| Criterion | Target | Achieved | Status |\n    76→|-----------|--------|----------|--------|\n    77→| TTFT mean error <15% | <15% | Not tested | UNKNOWN |\n    78→| ITL mean error <15% | <15% | Not tested | UNKNOWN |\n    79→| Outperforms blackbox on E2E, TTFT, ITL | All three | Not tested | UNKNOWN |\n    80→\n    81→### Priority 3: Tail Latency Behavior\n    82→\n    83→| Criterion | Target | Achieved | Status |\n    84→|-----------|--------|----------|--------|\n    85→| No p99 ranking inversions | No inversions | Not tested | UNKNOWN |\n    86→| Extreme errors <10% of steps | <10% | Not tested | UNKNOWN |\n    87→\n    88→### Priority 4: Model Quality and Practicality\n    89→\n    90→| Criterion | Target | Achieved | Status |\n    91→|-----------|--------|----------|--------|\n    92→| Dense + MoE <15% E2E error | <15% | Mixtral best MAPE = 9.1% (general) | PARTIALLY |\n    93→| Features derivable from Request batch | Yes | **Partially** — KV proxies from system state, not Request batch | GAP |\n    94→| Retraining documented | Yes | Not yet documented | TODO |\n    95→| Reproducible | Yes | Fixed seeds, saved models | MET |\n    96→| Prediction <1ms | <1ms | Not benchmarked | UNKNOWN |\n    97→| Go integration path identified | Yes | Serialized XGBoost trees in JSON | **MET** |\n    98→\n    99→### Priority 5: Generalization\n   100→\n   101→| Criterion | Target | Achieved | Status |\n   102→|-----------|--------|----------|--------|\n   103→| Hardware generalization | Informational | H100 only (no cross-GPU data) | REPORTED |\n   104→| Quantization generalization | Informational | BF16 only | REPORTED |\n   105→| Cross-model generalization | <20% MAPE | LOMO avg 2559.7% | **FAIL** |\n   106→| Cross-workload generalization | <20% MAPE | LOWO avg 109.7% | **FAIL** |\n   107→\n   108→---\n   109→\n   110→## Root Cause Analysis\n   111→\n   112→### Binding Constraint: Missing Per-Request KV Cache Lengths\n   113→\n   114→The single most impactful limitation across all ideas is that **step-level training data lacks per-request KV cache lengths** (ProgressIndex). This affects:\n   115→\n   116→1. **Idea 1:** XGBoost uses system-state KV proxies (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`) instead of per-request statistics (`kv_mean`, `kv_max`, `kv_sum`). These proxies capture occupancy but not distribution.\n   117→\n   118→2. **Idea 2:** Decode attention FLOPs are literally zero — uncomputable without per-request KV lengths. This makes the analytical decomposition structurally incomplete for 80.6% of steps (pure decode).\n   119→\n   120→3. **Feature importance confirms it:** XGBoost's top feature is `f_kv_blocks_used` — the best available KV proxy. The model is begging for better KV information.\n   121→\n   122→### Secondary Constraint: Step Time Scale Variation\n   123→\n   124→Step times span 3+ orders of magnitude across model configurations (12μs for Llama-7B decode to 250,000μs for Llama-70B mixed batches). This makes global models fail catastrophically and forces per-model training.\n   125→\n   126→### Why \"General\" Workloads Are Hardest\n   127→\n   128→The 4 worst experiments (50-121% MAPE) are all \"general\" workloads. These have the most diverse batch compositions — mixing short decode-only batches with occasional large prefill+decode batches. The high variance requires features that capture per-batch compute structure, not just aggregate token counts.\n   129→\n   130→---\n   131→\n   132→## Convergence Review: Findings Quality\n   133→\n   134→### Idea 1 Findings Assessment\n   135→\n   136→| Dimension | Assessment |\n   137→|-----------|------------|\n   138→| Results match code | Verified — CSVs match FINDINGS.md tables |\n   139→| Statistical rigor | MAPE correctly computed; no significance tests (would strengthen) |\n   140→| Baselines compared | Blackbox baseline compared in every experiment |\n   141→| Conclusions follow evidence | Yes — \"weakly supported\" is accurate for 5/16 < 15% |\n   142→| Reproducible | `run.sh` is self-contained, seeds fixed |\n   143→| Actionable | Clear recommendation: per-experiment XGBoost, extend LatencyModel for KV |\n   144→\n   145→### Idea 2 Findings Assessment\n   146→\n   147→| Dimension | Assessment |\n   148→|-----------|------------|\n   149→| Results match code | Verified — decode_attn_factor = 39.5 amplifying zero signal |\n   150→| Root cause identified | Yes — missing per-request KV is the structural blocker |\n   151→| Abandonment justified | Yes — 36 params worse than 3-param blackbox is definitive |\n   152→| Salvage path documented | Yes — revisit if LatencyModel gains ProgressIndex |\n   153→\n   154→### Idea 3 Assessment\n   155→\n   156→| Dimension | Assessment |\n   157→|-----------|------------|\n   158→| Not attempted | Justified — h2 depends on Idea 2 (failed), h1/h3 require OpenEvolve infrastructure |\n   159→| Deferred, not abandoned | Correct — evolutionary search could still discover useful formulas if data improves |\n   160→\n   161→---\n   162→\n   163→## Decision\n   164→\n   165→### Recommendation: Conditional Integration of Per-Experiment XGBoost\n   166→\n   167→**Integrate Idea 1's per-experiment XGBoost as a `StepMLLatencyModel`** behind the existing `LatencyModel` interface, with these conditions:\n   168→\n   169→1. **Ship as opt-in** (`--stepml` flag), not as the default. The blackbox model remains default until E2E validation completes.\n   170→\n   171→2. **Per-model coefficient files** (serialized XGBoost trees in JSON), analogous to existing `defaults.yaml` alpha/beta coefficients. One file per model configuration.\n   172→\n   173→3. **Feature computation in Go** — the 30-feature vector is computed from batch composition at step time. The ~20 features that depend on system-state KV proxies use the existing `KVStore` observation methods.\n   174→\n   175→4. **Pure-Go tree evaluator** — XGBoost trees are if/else comparisons on feature thresholds. No CGo, no Python runtime, no ONNX. ~200 lines of Go.\n   176→\n   177→### Deferred Work (Not Part of Initial Integration)\n   178→\n   179→| Item | Reason |\n   180→|------|--------|\n   181→| Workload-level E2E validation | Requires BLIS simulation loop with StepML backend — do as Go integration test |\n   182→| TTFT/ITL mean accuracy | Requires mapping step predictions to per-request metrics — do during integration |\n   183→| Per-request KV features | Requires extending `LatencyModel.StepTime()` to receive `[]Request` with ProgressIndex |\n   184→| Cross-model generalization | Per-model training is the permanent approach (consistent with Vidur/Splitwise) |\n   185→| Idea 3 evolutionary search | Deferred until data quality improves (per-request KV available) |\n   186→\n   187→### Go Integration Path (WP6 Scope)\n   188→\n   189→```\n   190→sim/latency/\n   191→├── latency.go          # Existing: BlackboxLatencyModel, RooflineLatencyModel\n   192→├── stepml.go           # NEW: StepMLLatencyModel (implements LatencyModel interface)\n   193→├── stepml_features.go  # NEW: ComputeFeatures(batch, modelConfig) []float64\n   194→├── stepml_tree.go      # NEW: Pure-Go XGBoost tree evaluator\n   195→├── stepml_models/      # NEW: Per-model JSON coefficient files\n   196→│   ├── llama-2-7b.json\n   197→│   ├── llama-2-70b.json\n   198→│   ├── codellama-34b.json\n   199→│   └── mixtral-8x7b.json\n   200→└── register.go         # Modified: register StepML alongside Blackbox and Roofline\n   201→```\n   202→\n   203→**Feature contract:** `ComputeFeatures()` receives the same `BatchContext` that `BlackboxLatencyModel.StepTime()` already receives — no interface changes needed for the initial integration. The system-state KV features (`kv_blocks_used`, `running_depth`) are available from the `InstanceSimulator` observation methods.\n   204→\n   205→---\n   206→\n   207→## Open Questions for WP6\n   208→\n   209→1. **Should the XGBoost models be re-trained with more data?** Current training uses 60% of ~7,600 steps per experiment (~4,500 training steps). More calibration data might improve the 11 experiments above 15% MAPE.\n   210→\n   211→2. **Feature availability at inference time:** The 30-feature set includes some features (`kv.blocks_free_gpu`, `queue.running_depth`) that come from simulator state, not the `BatchContext`. How should these be plumbed into the `LatencyModel.StepTime()` call?\n   212→\n   213→3. **Model file distribution:** Should the JSON coefficient files be embedded in the Go binary (via `//go:embed`), loaded from disk (like `defaults.yaml`), or fetched alongside HuggingFace configs (like `--roofline`)?\n   214→\n   215→4. **Fallback behavior:** If no StepML model exists for a given `--model`, should BLIS fall back to blackbox or error?\n   216→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"0c78fc84-0f60-405d-b0a4-efc59b121030"}
