{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01TnAgJ3U6ALZKmfLKq5g98j","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# HYPOTHESIS: Two-Stage Calibration — Principled Cycle-Time Base + Constrained CMA-ES Residual\n     2→\n     3→**Round:** 4\n     4→**Idea:** 3 — Hybrid Calibration\n     5→**Date:** 2026-03-02\n     6→**Status:** Pending\n     7→\n     8→## Context and Prior Findings\n     9→\n    10→Round 3 demonstrated two complementary results:\n    11→1. **CMA-ES** achieves 15.1% mean E2E but 87.4% ITL (E2E-focused, ITL-blind)\n    12→2. **Trace replay baseline** achieves 56.2% mean E2E but 9.5% ITL (correctly calibrated per-step but poor E2E)\n    13→\n    14→The gap exists because CMA-ES compensates for a poorly calibrated base model by distorting secondary coefficients (`output_token_processing_time_us` inflated to 1,899μs). If the base model already produces correct step cycle times (via Idea 2's cycle-time regression), CMA-ES only needs small residual adjustments — the E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff softens because there's less to compensate for.\n    15→\n    16→This idea chains Idea 2 (principled base) → Idea 1 (constrained CMA-ES) with tight bounds (±20% of base values).\n    17→\n    18→### Related Work\n    19→\n    20→- Kennedy & O'Hagan, 2001 — Bayesian calibration with discrepancy term (physics model + statistical residual)\n    21→- Revati [2025] — extends Vidur's analytical models with profiling, <5% error\n    22→- R3 Idea 3 — unconstrained CMA-ES achieving 15.1% E2E / 87.4% ITL\n    23→- R3 Finding: CMA-ES cross-model transfer achieves 14.8% LOMO E2E — transferable dynamics\n    24→\n    25→## Sub-Hypotheses\n    26→\n    27→### H1: Stage 1 Principled Base (Cycle-Time Regression + TTFT Corrections)\n    28→\n    29→**Claim:** Cycle-time regression (from Idea 2) combined with TTFT additive corrections produces a base model with **mean E2E < 30%** and **mean ITL < 20%** across 10 experiments.\n    30→\n    31→**Refutation criteria:** Mean E2E > 50% (worse than R3 trace replay baseline) OR mean ITL > 30%.\n    32→\n    33→**Method:**\n    34→1. Use Idea 2's cycle-time extraction (H1) and regression (H2) artifacts\n    35→2. Apply per-model TTFT additive corrections from R3 H3 (16–61ms) to QueueingTime\n    36→3. Set `output_token_processing_time_us = 0` (absorbed into cycle time model)\n    37→4. Run BLIS validation via trace replay\n    38→5. Report per-experiment E2E, TTFT, ITL errors\n    39→6. This is the \"principled base\" — the starting point for Stage 2\n    40→\n    41→**Note:** If Idea 2 H2 already reports BLIS E2E results, H1 here simply adds TTFT corrections. The key test is whether TTFT corrections + cycle-time base together produce a balanced model.\n    42→\n    43→**Data split:** Same as Idea 2 H2 (temporal split for regression). BLIS E2E on all experiments.\n    44→\n    45→### H2: Stage 2 Constrained CMA-ES Residual Tuning\n    46→\n    47→**Claim:** Constrained CMA-ES (±20% bounds around Stage 1 values, dual-objective E2E+ITL) improves the principled base to **mean E2E < 12%** and **mean ITL < 18%**, with at least **6/10 experiments below 10% E2E**.\n    48→\n    49→**Refutation criteria:** Mean E2E > Stage 1 E2E + 5pp (CMA-ES makes base model worse) OR mean ITL > 25%.\n    50→\n    51→**Method:**\n    52→1. Start from H1's principled base coefficients as CMA-ES initial vector\n    53→2. **Tight bounds:**\n    54→   - `step_overhead_us ∈ [base × 0.85, base × 1.15]`\n    55→   - `output_token_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 200]`\n    56→   - `scheduling_processing_time_us ∈ [0, 1000]`\n    57→   - Step-time regime coefficients ∈ [base × 0.8, base × 1.2]\n    58→3. **Dual objective:** `f(x) = 0.5 * mean_e2e + 0.5 * mean_itl + 5.0 * max(0, itl - 0.20)`\n    59→4. Per-model optimization, σ₀ = 0.05 (smaller than Idea 1's 0.1 — tighter search)\n    60→5. Max 80 evaluations per model (vs 96-152 in R3 — starting closer to optimum)\n    61→6. **Safety net:** If any model's ITL worsens by >5pp vs Stage 1, discard CMA-ES for that model and use Stage 1 directly\n    62→\n    63→### H3: LOMO Generalization (Cross-Model Transfer)\n    64→\n    65→**Claim:** The hybrid approach achieves **mean best-donor E2E < 20%** in LOMO cross-model transfer, with **mean best-donor ITL < 30%** (R3 did not report LOMO ITL).\n    66→\n    67→**Refutation criteria:** Mean best-donor E2E > 30% (2× worse than R3's 14.8%).\n    68→\n    69→**Method:**\n    70→1. For Stage 1 LOMO: Train cycle-time regression on 3 models, evaluate BLIS E2E/ITL on held-out 4th\n    71→2. For Stage 2 LOMO: Apply CMA-ES artifacts (optimized on 3 models) to held-out 4th\n    72→3. Build cross-model transfer matrix for both E2E and ITL (extends R3 H5)\n    73→4. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_model_out()` for splitting\n    74→5. Report which stage contributes most to generalization: principled base (Stage 1) or CMA-ES residuals (Stage 2)\n    75→\n    76→### H4: LOWO Generalization (Cross-Workload Stability)\n    77→\n    78→**Claim:** The hybrid approach shows per-model workload variance **≤ 20pp** for dense models and **mean E2E within 2× of aggregate** for all 10 experiments.\n    79→\n    80→**Refutation criteria:** More than 3/10 experiments exceed 2× aggregate E2E.\n    81→\n    82→**Method:**\n    83→1. Evaluate per-experiment E2E/ITL from H2's best configuration\n    84→2. Group by model, compute per-workload breakdown\n    85→3. Measure range (max-min) per model\n    86→4. Compare against R3 LOWO results (8/10 within 2×)\n    87→5. Use `hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/splits.py:leave_one_workload_out()` for data splitting\n    88→\n    89→## Execution Plan\n    90→\n    91→1. **Depends on Idea 2 H1+H2:** Stage 1 uses Idea 2's cycle-time regression artifacts. If Idea 2 is executed first, Stage 1 reuses those artifacts; if not, Stage 1 re-derives them.\n    92→2. H1 — evaluate Stage 1 (principled base + TTFT corrections)\n    93→3. H2 — run Stage 2 CMA-ES on top of Stage 1\n    94→4. H3 + H4 — LOMO/LOWO generalization (can run in parallel after H2)\n    95→\n    96→## Short-Circuit Criteria\n    97→\n    98→- If Idea 2 H1 fails (cannot extract cycle times), this idea is blocked. Fall back to using R3's regime ensemble as the Stage 1 base.\n    99→- If H1 (Stage 1) produces mean E2E > 50% AND mean ITL > 25%, the principled base is not better than R3's trace replay — skip Stage 2 and document why.\n   100→- If H2 (Stage 2) produces E2E > 18% AND ITL > 25% (worse than both Idea 1 and R3 on both metrics), the hybrid approach is not synergistic — abort H3/H4.\n   101→\n   102→## Expected Outcome\n   103→\n   104→This idea represents the highest probability of achieving the research target: **E2E < 10% AND ITL < 15%**. By combining a correctly calibrated base (modeling what is measured) with constrained optimization (small residual corrections), we avoid the catastrophic E2E ↔ ITL tradeoff that plagued R3.\n   105→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"43b6cfde-641a-4329-a322-b1128691bfde"}
