{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01C4RLMGJc2EVVcRrBpPNssn","type":"tool_result","content":"42:Round 2 tested 2 ideas on 10 experiments (4 models x 3 workloads, no reasoning). Both ideas added ProgressIndex-derived KV features, regime-based step-time splitting, and BLIS E2E validation. **All hypotheses across both ideas were refuted or not met.** Full details: `round2/FINDINGS_ROUND2.md`.\n141:2. **Step-time accuracy for remaining experiments** — ITL is solved for 5/10 experiments via the overhead floor. The remaining 5 need either better step-time models (feature-scaled KV, nonlinear models) or 34B-specific investigation.\n513:Round 3 tested 3 ideas on 10 experiments (5 models × 3 workloads). **Key achievement: 427.8% → 15.1% mean E2E (28.3x improvement)** via two advances: trace replay eliminated workload-spec errors, CMA-ES found per-model coefficient settings. Full details: `round3/FINDINGS_ROUND3.md`.\n554:| llama-2-70b-hf-codegen | **3.8%** | 67.6% | 111.6% | E2E solved |\n567:CMA-ES achieves 15.1% E2E but at 87.4% ITL (was 9.5% with trace replay baseline). **Root cause:** E2E = TTFT + Σ(ITL). Optimizing total E2E via shared coefficients produces arbitrarily bad ITL. CMA-ES uses `output_token_processing_time_us` as a proxy for missing simulation dynamics (e.g., llama-2-7b: 0→1,899µs). Need multi-objective or constrained optimization."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"09d01587-989c-4ebe-bb8c-774b54728556"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RVuaHJFo1hExchGpHGTkix","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Comprehensive Findings Report\n\n### 1. FILES READ\n\nAll findings were sourced from these files within `/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/hypotheses/h-stepml/`:\n\n- `problem.md` (main, 584 lines -- the authoritative cumulative document)\n- `research.md` (Round 4 research ideas, identical content to `round4/research.md`)\n- `round1/round1_FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md`\n- `round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h1-features/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h2-model/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h3-generalization/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-2-analytical-decomposition/h1-features/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-2-analytical-decomposition/h2-model/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/DECISION_GATE.md`\n- `round4/idea-3-hybrid-calibration/HYPOTHESIS.md`\n- `shared/baseline_results/per_model_linear_baseline_summary.json`\n- `shared/baseline_results/per_model_linear_baseline.csv`\n- `shared/baseline_results/roofline_baseline_summary.json`\n- `shared/baseline_results/roofline_baseline.csv`\n- `shared/baseline_results/component_attribution.csv`\n- `shared/baseline_results/r1_gate.json`\n- `shared/baseline_results/r2_gate.json`\n\n**Note:** No `round2/` or `round3/` directories exist on this branch. R2 and R3 findings are embedded entirely within `problem.md` (the cumulative problem statement). The `problem.md` references `round2/FINDINGS_ROUND2.md` and `round3/FINDINGS_ROUND3.md` but these files are not present -- they likely exist on the main `stepml-experiments` branch or in other worktrees.\n\n---\n\n### 2. R3 CMA-ES RESULTS (15.1% E2E, 87.4% ITL)\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 537-563, Round 3 Idea 3 (End-to-End Calibration via CMA-ES):\n\n**Aggregate:** Mean E2E = **15.1%**, Mean TTFT = **67.6%**, Mean ITL = **87.4%**, 4/10 experiments solved (<10% E2E)\n\n**Per-experiment breakdown:**\n\n| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| codellama-34b-general | **1.2%** | 69.3% | 102.7% | E2E solved |\n| llama-2-70b-hf-codegen | **3.8%** | 67.6% | 111.6% | E2E solved |\n| codellama-34b-codegen | **5.0%** | 68.9% | 90.2% | E2E solved |\n| llama-2-70b-roleplay | **6.9%** | 67.6% | 117.0% | E2E solved |\n| mixtral-general | 12.7% | 57.3% | 78.1% | Close |\n| llama-2-70b-general | 16.2% | 82.5% | 72.0% | Unsolved |\n| codellama-34b-roleplay | 17.5% | 66.2% | 135.4% | Unsolved |\n| llama-2-7b-roleplay | 22.2% | 60.8% | 91.1% | Unsolved |\n| mixtral-codegen | 30.9% | 66.4% | 41.5% | Unsolved |\n| mixtral-roleplay | 34.2% | 69.3% | 34.5% | Unsolved |\n\n**Root cause of the E2E <-> ITL tradeoff:** CMA-ES inflated `output_token_processing_time_us` to implausible values (e.g., 0 -> 1,899us for llama-2-7b) to compensate for BLIS simulating a \"faster universe\" (~40% of real time). The single-objective formulation minimized E2E without knowledge of ITL consequences.\n\n---\n\n### 3. R3 TRACE REPLAY BASELINE RESULTS (56.2% E2E, 9.5% ITL)\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 515-527, Round 3 Idea 1 (Trace-Driven Simulation with Lifecycle Replay):\n\n- Mean E2E: **56.2%** (target was <25%, refuted)\n- Mean TTFT: **78.8%** (was 31,906% with workload-spec mode, so trace replay was a massive improvement)\n- Mean ITL: **9.5%** (well-calibrated ITL, driven by overhead floor mechanism)\n\nThis also matches the R3 Idea 2 result: FairBatching 3-coefficient OLS achieved **56.2% per-step MAPE** (vs 83.1% baseline), and when run through BLIS, it produced the same 56.2% E2E as the R2 trace replay baseline. This confirmed that **a 27pp per-step improvement (83% -> 56%) had ZERO impact on BLIS E2E** because the overhead floor dominates 70-90% of steps.\n\n---\n\n### 4. R3 TTFT ADDITIVE CORRECTIONS (16-61ms)\n\nFrom `problem.md` line 486 and `round4/research.md` line 31:\n\nPer-model TTFT additive corrections of **16-61ms** reduce TTFT error from **67.6% to 9.4%**. These are simple per-model constants applied to QueueingTime.\n\nHowever, when applied **post-hoc on CMA-ES results**, they made E2E **+2.1pp worse** (problem.md line 545). The R3 H3 finding was: \"Refuted for E2E\" -- TTFT additive corrections conflict with CMA-ES-optimized coefficients. For Round 4, the plan is to integrate TTFT corrections *within* the CMA-ES objective evaluation to avoid this double-counting.\n\n---\n\n### 5. R3 CROSS-MODEL TRANSFER RESULTS (14.8% LOMO E2E)\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 547 and 489:\n\nCMA-ES cross-model artifact transfer achieves **14.8% mean best-donor E2E** across models. This was a major breakthrough because:\n- CMA-ES artifacts generalize dramatically better than per-step models (14.8% LOMO E2E vs 2,281.6% LOMO MAPE for the total-context model)\n- Mixtral is the best universal donor (11.9-26.0%)\n- 70B->Mixtral transfer (5.1%) outperforms Mixtral's in-distribution result (25.9%)\n- CMA-ES artifacts capture *simulation dynamics* (overhead floor, scheduling), not model-specific step times, which is why they transfer\n\nThe total-context model (Idea 2) regressed badly: LOMO MAPE = **2,281.6%**, LOWO MAPE = **2,162.7%** (both refuted).\n\n---\n\n### 6. BLACKBOX BASELINE E2E NUMBERS\n\nThere are two versions of the blackbox baseline in the data:\n\n**From `problem.md` lines 211-243 (12-experiment set, trained per-model with forced beta0=0):**\n- **Mean E2E error: 115.0%** (0/12 below 10%)\n- Mean TTFT error: 102.9%\n- Mean ITL error: 134.6%\n\nPer-experiment E2E errors range from 86.1% (7b-roleplay) to 141.9% (mixtral-roleplay).\n\n**From `shared/baseline_results/per_model_linear_baseline_summary.json` (10-experiment R3 set, retrained per-model):**\n- **Mean E2E error: 99.4%** (0/10 below 10%)\n- Mean TTFT error: 98.9%\n- Mean ITL error: 98.8%\n\nThese per-experiment numbers from the CSV show BLIS completing requests at ~1% of real time (E2E predictions of 4-117ms vs ground truth of 2,000-5,300ms), confirming the \"faster universe\" problem.\n\n**From `shared/baseline_results/roofline_baseline_summary.json` (roofline, informational only):**\n- Mean E2E error: **4,765%** (massively overestimates step time)\n- Mean ITL error: 346%\n- Mean TTFT error: 346,393%\n\n---\n\n### 7. MODELS IN THE DATASET\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 153-158:\n\n| Model | Architecture | TP | Parameters |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Llama-2-7B | Dense | 1 | 7B |\n| Llama-2-70B | Dense | 4 | 70B |\n| CodeLlama-34B | Dense | 2 | 34B |\n| Mixtral-8x7B-v0.1 | MoE (8 experts, top-2) | 2 | 46.7B total, ~12.9B active |\n\n**Note on experiment counts:** \n- R1 used 16 experiments: 4 models x 4 workloads (general, codegen, roleplay, reasoning)\n- R2 used 10 experiments: 4 models x 3 workloads (no reasoning) -- \"reasoning\" was dropped\n- R3 used 10 experiments: described as \"5 models x 3 workloads\" -- the CMA-ES per-experiment table shows both \"llama-2-70b\" and \"llama-2-70b-hf\" entries, suggesting the 70B variant was split into two configurations. Workloads: general, codegen, roleplay.\n\n---\n\n### 8. WORKLOADS IN THE DATASET\n\nFrom `problem.md` line 162:\n\n**Three active workloads** (used in R2-R4): **general, codegen, roleplay**\n\nEach has different input/output length distributions. All runs use: `max_model_len=4096`, `max_num_batched_tokens=2048`, `max_num_seqs=128`, chunked prefill enabled, prefix caching enabled.\n\n**A fourth workload** -- **reasoning** -- was used in R1 (16 experiments) but dropped starting R2 (10 experiments). Reasoning workloads had extremely high variance and bimodal distributions (long prefills interspersed with short decodes).\n\n**Key workload characteristics from R1 findings:**\n- **General**: Most diverse batch compositions, consistently hardest workload (50-121% MAPE for XGBoost; 34B-general is the worst single experiment across all rounds)\n- **Codegen**: Short, bursty, mean 160-320us\n- **Roleplay**: Short, bursty, mean 160-320us, similar patterns to codegen\n- **Reasoning** (dropped): 6,000-33,500us mean, bimodal, extremely high variance\n\n---\n\n### 9. CUMULATIVE ROUND HISTORY\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 579-583:\n\n| Round | Best E2E | Best ITL | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| R1 | Not tested | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE (2x blackbox) | No BLIS integration |\n| R2 | 427.8% mean (1/10 <10%) | 33.6% mean (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + regime structure | TTFT mismatch (31,906%) |\n| R3 | **15.1%** mean (4/10 <10%) | 87.4% mean (0/10 <10%) | Trace replay + CMA-ES (28.3x E2E improvement) | E2E <-> ITL tradeoff |\n\n---\n\n### 10. ROUND 4 TARGET AND APPROACH (Idea 3: Hybrid Calibration)\n\nFrom `round4/idea-3-hybrid-calibration/HYPOTHESIS.md`:\n\n**Target:** E2E < 10% AND ITL < 15% simultaneously\n\n**Two-stage approach:**\n- **Stage 1:** Principled cycle-time regression (model the *actual* inter-token interval from lifecycle data, not GPU-only step.duration_us) + TTFT additive corrections (16-61ms). Expected: E2E ~20-30% with ITL ~12-20%.\n- **Stage 2:** Constrained CMA-ES residual tuning with tight bounds (+-20% of Stage 1 values) and a dual-objective (0.5*E2E + 0.5*ITL + penalty). Expected: E2E <10% with ITL <15%.\n\n**Primary binding constraints being addressed:**\n- BC-NEW-1: E2E <-> ITL fundamental tradeoff\n- BC-NEW-2: Step cycle under-prediction (\"faster universe\" -- BLIS at ~40% real speed)\n- BC-6: vLLM args sensitivity (never analyzed in any prior round)"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ab049a0 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 3360\ntool_uses: 29\nduration_ms: 146377</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"0a23adaa-82e1-45ee-b444-8fe15cb2ffd5","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the repository at /Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/ to find and read:\n\n1. ALL findings from Round 3 experiments (look in hypotheses/h-stepml/round3/ or similar)\n2. The research.md file at hypotheses/h-stepml/research.md\n3. The problem.md file at hypotheses/h-stepml/problem.md\n4. Any prior round FINDINGS.md or FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md files\n5. The baseline results at hypotheses/h-stepml/shared/baseline_results/\n\nI need:\n- R3 CMA-ES results (15.1% E2E, 87.4% ITL mentioned)\n- R3 trace replay baseline results (56.2% E2E, 9.5% ITL mentioned)  \n- R3 TTFT additive corrections (16-61ms mentioned)\n- R3 cross-model transfer results (14.8% LOMO E2E)\n- Blackbox baseline E2E numbers\n- What models are in the dataset\n- What workloads are in the dataset\n\nBe very thorough - read all FINDINGS.md files you can find.","agentId":"ab049a0","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Comprehensive Findings Report\n\n### 1. FILES READ\n\nAll findings were sourced from these files within `/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/hypotheses/h-stepml/`:\n\n- `problem.md` (main, 584 lines -- the authoritative cumulative document)\n- `research.md` (Round 4 research ideas, identical content to `round4/research.md`)\n- `round1/round1_FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md`\n- `round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h1-features/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h2-model/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-1-tree-ensemble/h3-generalization/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-2-analytical-decomposition/h1-features/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/idea-2-analytical-decomposition/h2-model/FINDINGS.md`\n- `round1/DECISION_GATE.md`\n- `round4/idea-3-hybrid-calibration/HYPOTHESIS.md`\n- `shared/baseline_results/per_model_linear_baseline_summary.json`\n- `shared/baseline_results/per_model_linear_baseline.csv`\n- `shared/baseline_results/roofline_baseline_summary.json`\n- `shared/baseline_results/roofline_baseline.csv`\n- `shared/baseline_results/component_attribution.csv`\n- `shared/baseline_results/r1_gate.json`\n- `shared/baseline_results/r2_gate.json`\n\n**Note:** No `round2/` or `round3/` directories exist on this branch. R2 and R3 findings are embedded entirely within `problem.md` (the cumulative problem statement). The `problem.md` references `round2/FINDINGS_ROUND2.md` and `round3/FINDINGS_ROUND3.md` but these files are not present -- they likely exist on the main `stepml-experiments` branch or in other worktrees.\n\n---\n\n### 2. R3 CMA-ES RESULTS (15.1% E2E, 87.4% ITL)\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 537-563, Round 3 Idea 3 (End-to-End Calibration via CMA-ES):\n\n**Aggregate:** Mean E2E = **15.1%**, Mean TTFT = **67.6%**, Mean ITL = **87.4%**, 4/10 experiments solved (<10% E2E)\n\n**Per-experiment breakdown:**\n\n| Experiment | E2E Error | TTFT Error | ITL Error | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| codellama-34b-general | **1.2%** | 69.3% | 102.7% | E2E solved |\n| llama-2-70b-hf-codegen | **3.8%** | 67.6% | 111.6% | E2E solved |\n| codellama-34b-codegen | **5.0%** | 68.9% | 90.2% | E2E solved |\n| llama-2-70b-roleplay | **6.9%** | 67.6% | 117.0% | E2E solved |\n| mixtral-general | 12.7% | 57.3% | 78.1% | Close |\n| llama-2-70b-general | 16.2% | 82.5% | 72.0% | Unsolved |\n| codellama-34b-roleplay | 17.5% | 66.2% | 135.4% | Unsolved |\n| llama-2-7b-roleplay | 22.2% | 60.8% | 91.1% | Unsolved |\n| mixtral-codegen | 30.9% | 66.4% | 41.5% | Unsolved |\n| mixtral-roleplay | 34.2% | 69.3% | 34.5% | Unsolved |\n\n**Root cause of the E2E <-> ITL tradeoff:** CMA-ES inflated `output_token_processing_time_us` to implausible values (e.g., 0 -> 1,899us for llama-2-7b) to compensate for BLIS simulating a \"faster universe\" (~40% of real time). The single-objective formulation minimized E2E without knowledge of ITL consequences.\n\n---\n\n### 3. R3 TRACE REPLAY BASELINE RESULTS (56.2% E2E, 9.5% ITL)\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 515-527, Round 3 Idea 1 (Trace-Driven Simulation with Lifecycle Replay):\n\n- Mean E2E: **56.2%** (target was <25%, refuted)\n- Mean TTFT: **78.8%** (was 31,906% with workload-spec mode, so trace replay was a massive improvement)\n- Mean ITL: **9.5%** (well-calibrated ITL, driven by overhead floor mechanism)\n\nThis also matches the R3 Idea 2 result: FairBatching 3-coefficient OLS achieved **56.2% per-step MAPE** (vs 83.1% baseline), and when run through BLIS, it produced the same 56.2% E2E as the R2 trace replay baseline. This confirmed that **a 27pp per-step improvement (83% -> 56%) had ZERO impact on BLIS E2E** because the overhead floor dominates 70-90% of steps.\n\n---\n\n### 4. R3 TTFT ADDITIVE CORRECTIONS (16-61ms)\n\nFrom `problem.md` line 486 and `round4/research.md` line 31:\n\nPer-model TTFT additive corrections of **16-61ms** reduce TTFT error from **67.6% to 9.4%**. These are simple per-model constants applied to QueueingTime.\n\nHowever, when applied **post-hoc on CMA-ES results**, they made E2E **+2.1pp worse** (problem.md line 545). The R3 H3 finding was: \"Refuted for E2E\" -- TTFT additive corrections conflict with CMA-ES-optimized coefficients. For Round 4, the plan is to integrate TTFT corrections *within* the CMA-ES objective evaluation to avoid this double-counting.\n\n---\n\n### 5. R3 CROSS-MODEL TRANSFER RESULTS (14.8% LOMO E2E)\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 547 and 489:\n\nCMA-ES cross-model artifact transfer achieves **14.8% mean best-donor E2E** across models. This was a major breakthrough because:\n- CMA-ES artifacts generalize dramatically better than per-step models (14.8% LOMO E2E vs 2,281.6% LOMO MAPE for the total-context model)\n- Mixtral is the best universal donor (11.9-26.0%)\n- 70B->Mixtral transfer (5.1%) outperforms Mixtral's in-distribution result (25.9%)\n- CMA-ES artifacts capture *simulation dynamics* (overhead floor, scheduling), not model-specific step times, which is why they transfer\n\nThe total-context model (Idea 2) regressed badly: LOMO MAPE = **2,281.6%**, LOWO MAPE = **2,162.7%** (both refuted).\n\n---\n\n### 6. BLACKBOX BASELINE E2E NUMBERS\n\nThere are two versions of the blackbox baseline in the data:\n\n**From `problem.md` lines 211-243 (12-experiment set, trained per-model with forced beta0=0):**\n- **Mean E2E error: 115.0%** (0/12 below 10%)\n- Mean TTFT error: 102.9%\n- Mean ITL error: 134.6%\n\nPer-experiment E2E errors range from 86.1% (7b-roleplay) to 141.9% (mixtral-roleplay).\n\n**From `shared/baseline_results/per_model_linear_baseline_summary.json` (10-experiment R3 set, retrained per-model):**\n- **Mean E2E error: 99.4%** (0/10 below 10%)\n- Mean TTFT error: 98.9%\n- Mean ITL error: 98.8%\n\nThese per-experiment numbers from the CSV show BLIS completing requests at ~1% of real time (E2E predictions of 4-117ms vs ground truth of 2,000-5,300ms), confirming the \"faster universe\" problem.\n\n**From `shared/baseline_results/roofline_baseline_summary.json` (roofline, informational only):**\n- Mean E2E error: **4,765%** (massively overestimates step time)\n- Mean ITL error: 346%\n- Mean TTFT error: 346,393%\n\n---\n\n### 7. MODELS IN THE DATASET\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 153-158:\n\n| Model | Architecture | TP | Parameters |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Llama-2-7B | Dense | 1 | 7B |\n| Llama-2-70B | Dense | 4 | 70B |\n| CodeLlama-34B | Dense | 2 | 34B |\n| Mixtral-8x7B-v0.1 | MoE (8 experts, top-2) | 2 | 46.7B total, ~12.9B active |\n\n**Note on experiment counts:** \n- R1 used 16 experiments: 4 models x 4 workloads (general, codegen, roleplay, reasoning)\n- R2 used 10 experiments: 4 models x 3 workloads (no reasoning) -- \"reasoning\" was dropped\n- R3 used 10 experiments: described as \"5 models x 3 workloads\" -- the CMA-ES per-experiment table shows both \"llama-2-70b\" and \"llama-2-70b-hf\" entries, suggesting the 70B variant was split into two configurations. Workloads: general, codegen, roleplay.\n\n---\n\n### 8. WORKLOADS IN THE DATASET\n\nFrom `problem.md` line 162:\n\n**Three active workloads** (used in R2-R4): **general, codegen, roleplay**\n\nEach has different input/output length distributions. All runs use: `max_model_len=4096`, `max_num_batched_tokens=2048`, `max_num_seqs=128`, chunked prefill enabled, prefix caching enabled.\n\n**A fourth workload** -- **reasoning** -- was used in R1 (16 experiments) but dropped starting R2 (10 experiments). Reasoning workloads had extremely high variance and bimodal distributions (long prefills interspersed with short decodes).\n\n**Key workload characteristics from R1 findings:**\n- **General**: Most diverse batch compositions, consistently hardest workload (50-121% MAPE for XGBoost; 34B-general is the worst single experiment across all rounds)\n- **Codegen**: Short, bursty, mean 160-320us\n- **Roleplay**: Short, bursty, mean 160-320us, similar patterns to codegen\n- **Reasoning** (dropped): 6,000-33,500us mean, bimodal, extremely high variance\n\n---\n\n### 9. CUMULATIVE ROUND HISTORY\n\nFrom `problem.md` lines 579-583:\n\n| Round | Best E2E | Best ITL | Key Achievement | Primary Blocker |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| R1 | Not tested | Not tested | 34% per-step MAPE (2x blackbox) | No BLIS integration |\n| R2 | 427.8% mean (1/10 <10%) | 33.6% mean (5/10 <10%) | Overhead floor + BLIS pipeline + regime structure | TTFT mismatch (31,906%) |\n| R3 | **15.1%** mean (4/10 <10%) | 87.4% mean (0/10 <10%) | Trace replay + CMA-ES (28.3x E2E improvement) | E2E <-> ITL tradeoff |\n\n---\n\n### 10. ROUND 4 TARGET AND APPROACH (Idea 3: Hybrid Calibration)\n\nFrom `round4/idea-3-hybrid-calibration/HYPOTHESIS.md`:\n\n**Target:** E2E < 10% AND ITL < 15% simultaneously\n\n**Two-stage approach:**\n- **Stage 1:** Principled cycle-time regression (model the *actual* inter-token interval from lifecycle data, not GPU-only step.duration_us) + TTFT additive corrections (16-61ms). Expected: E2E ~20-30% with ITL ~12-20%.\n- **Stage 2:** Constrained CMA-ES residual tuning with tight bounds (+-20% of Stage 1 values) and a dual-objective (0.5*E2E + 0.5*ITL + penalty). Expected: E2E <10% with ITL <15%.\n\n**Primary binding constraints being addressed:**\n- BC-NEW-1: E2E <-> ITL fundamental tradeoff\n- BC-NEW-2: Step cycle under-prediction (\"faster universe\" -- BLIS at ~40% real speed)\n- BC-6: vLLM args sensitivity (never analyzed in any prior round)"}],"totalDurationMs":146377,"totalTokens":3360,"totalToolUseCount":29,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":3359,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
