{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01EThwfxqsC8zmm22qk79vN2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# H4: Leave-One-Workload-Out (LOWO) Cross-Validation\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** PARTIALLY CONFIRMED\n     4→\n     5→## Key Numbers\n     6→\n     7→| Metric | Result | Target | Verdict |\n     8→|--------|--------|--------|---------|\n     9→| Aggregate E2E | 27.5% | - | - |\n    10→| Aggregate ITL | 43.7% | - | - |\n    11→| Within 2x aggregate | 10/10 | - | PASS |\n    12→| Dense model max range | 7.7pp | <=20pp | PASS |\n    13→| All experiments within 2x | 10/10 | - | PASS |\n    14→\n    15→Note: H4 uses H2's CMA-ES optimized coefficients (which traded E2E for ITL).\n    16→The workload stability analysis is still valid.\n    17→\n    18→## Per-Model Workload Breakdown\n    19→\n    20→| Model | Codegen | General | Roleplay | Range (pp) |\n    21→|-------|---------|---------|----------|------------|\n    22→| codellama-34b | 29.6% | 33.6% | 27.9% | 5.7 |\n    23→| llama-2-70b | 26.2% | 32.7% | 24.9% | 7.7 |\n    24→| llama-2-7b | - | - | 14.4% | 0.0 |\n    25→| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 27.5% | 31.7% | 26.7% | 5.0 |\n    26→\n    27→## Key Findings\n    28→\n    29→1. **Workload stability is excellent.** All dense models (codellama-34b,\n    30→   llama-2-70b, mixtral-8x7b-v0-1) show per-model E2E ranges of 5-8pp,\n    31→   well within the 20pp target. This means the coefficients generalize\n    32→   well across workload types.\n    33→\n    34→2. **General workload consistently has highest error** (~32-34% vs ~25-28%\n    35→   for codegen/roleplay). This may reflect different batch composition\n    36→   distributions (general workloads may have more variable prompt lengths).\n    37→\n    38→3. **All 10 experiments are within 2x of aggregate** (target met).\n    39→\n    40→4. **The absolute E2E values (27.5%) are elevated** because H4 uses\n    41→   CMA-ES coefficients (H2) which sacrificed E2E for ITL. With H1\n    42→   coefficients (5.7% mean E2E), the LOWO stability would be even better\n    43→   since H1's per-experiment variance is only 1-23%.\n    44→\n    45→## Comparison to R3\n    46→\n    47→| Metric | R3 LOWO | H4 (CMA-ES coeffs) | H1 coeffs (implicit) |\n    48→|--------|---------|---------------------|----------------------|\n    49→| Within 2x | 8/10 | **10/10** | ~10/10 (est.) |\n    50→| Max dense range | - | **7.7pp** | ~7pp (est.) |\n    51→\n    52→The workload stability of the hybrid calibration approach is better than R3,\n    53→with all experiments within 2x of aggregate and dense model ranges under 8pp.\n    54→\n    55→## Implications\n    56→\n    57→The direct calibration (H1) and CMA-ES-adjusted (H2) coefficients both show\n    58→excellent workload stability. This confirms that the overhead floor + per-token\n    59→regression structure captures workload-invariant dynamics correctly. The\n    60→workload type (codegen/general/roleplay) affects E2E by 5-8pp within a model,\n    61→which is a secondary effect compared to the model-specific overhead floor.\n    62→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"8ef0b39c-585a-44dc-baea-d150c763a667","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/hypotheses/h-stepml/round4/idea-3-hybrid-calibration/h4-lowo/FINDINGS.md","content":"# H4: Leave-One-Workload-Out (LOWO) Cross-Validation\n\n**Status:** PARTIALLY CONFIRMED\n\n## Key Numbers\n\n| Metric | Result | Target | Verdict |\n|--------|--------|--------|---------|\n| Aggregate E2E | 27.5% | - | - |\n| Aggregate ITL | 43.7% | - | - |\n| Within 2x aggregate | 10/10 | - | PASS |\n| Dense model max range | 7.7pp | <=20pp | PASS |\n| All experiments within 2x | 10/10 | - | PASS |\n\nNote: H4 uses H2's CMA-ES optimized coefficients (which traded E2E for ITL).\nThe workload stability analysis is still valid.\n\n## Per-Model Workload Breakdown\n\n| Model | Codegen | General | Roleplay | Range (pp) |\n|-------|---------|---------|----------|------------|\n| codellama-34b | 29.6% | 33.6% | 27.9% | 5.7 |\n| llama-2-70b | 26.2% | 32.7% | 24.9% | 7.7 |\n| llama-2-7b | - | - | 14.4% | 0.0 |\n| mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 | 27.5% | 31.7% | 26.7% | 5.0 |\n\n## Key Findings\n\n1. **Workload stability is excellent.** All dense models (codellama-34b,\n   llama-2-70b, mixtral-8x7b-v0-1) show per-model E2E ranges of 5-8pp,\n   well within the 20pp target. This means the coefficients generalize\n   well across workload types.\n\n2. **General workload consistently has highest error** (~32-34% vs ~25-28%\n   for codegen/roleplay). This may reflect different batch composition\n   distributions (general workloads may have more variable prompt lengths).\n\n3. **All 10 experiments are within 2x of aggregate** (target met).\n\n4. **The absolute E2E values (27.5%) are elevated** because H4 uses\n   CMA-ES coefficients (H2) which sacrificed E2E for ITL. With H1\n   coefficients (5.7% mean E2E), the LOWO stability would be even better\n   since H1's per-experiment variance is only 1-23%.\n\n## Comparison to R3\n\n| Metric | R3 LOWO | H4 (CMA-ES coeffs) | H1 coeffs (implicit) |\n|--------|---------|---------------------|----------------------|\n| Within 2x | 8/10 | **10/10** | ~10/10 (est.) |\n| Max dense range | - | **7.7pp** | ~7pp (est.) |\n\nThe workload stability of the hybrid calibration approach is better than R3,\nwith all experiments within 2x of aggregate and dense model ranges under 8pp.\n\n## Implications\n\nThe direct calibration (H1) and CMA-ES-adjusted (H2) coefficients both show\nexcellent workload stability. This confirms that the overhead floor + per-token\nregression structure captures workload-invariant dynamics correctly. The\nworkload type (codegen/general/roleplay) affects E2E by 5-8pp within a model,\nwhich is a secondary effect compared to the model-specific overhead floor.\n","numLines":62,"startLine":1,"totalLines":62}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HSWLQKVQ3RCts8cihD1Hzf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# H3: Leave-One-Model-Out (LOMO) Cross-Validation\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** REFUTED (mean best-donor E2E 30.7% > target 20%)\n     4→\n     5→## Key Numbers\n     6→\n     7→| Metric | Result | Target | Verdict |\n     8→|--------|--------|--------|---------|\n     9→| Mean best-donor E2E | 30.7% | <20% | FAIL |\n    10→| Mean best-donor ITL | 158.1% | <30% | FAIL |\n    11→\n    12→## Method\n    13→\n    14→For each of 4 normalized models, train the direct calibration (H1 approach)\n    15→on the remaining 3 models' data, then evaluate each donor model's coefficients\n    16→on the held-out model's experiments. Report the best donor per fold.\n    17→\n    18→## LOMO Transfer Matrix (E2E %)\n    19→\n    20→| Holdout \\ Donor | codellama-34b | llama-2-70b | llama-2-7b | mixtral-8x7b |\n    21→|-----------------|---------------|-------------|------------|--------------|\n    22→| codellama-34b | - | 31.1 | 33.3 | **28.5** |\n    23→| llama-2-70b | 20.4 | - | 47.0 | **6.7** |\n    24→| llama-2-7b | **82.9** | 137.3 | - | 137.6 |\n    25→| mixtral-8x7b | 20.2 | **4.5** | 46.8 | - |\n    26→\n    27→Best donors: mixtral for codellama (28.5%), mixtral for 70b (6.7%),\n    28→codellama for 7b (82.9%), 70b for mixtral (4.5%).\n    29→\n    30→## Key Findings\n    31→\n    32→1. **Large models transfer well to each other.** llama-2-70b and\n    33→   mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 have similar overhead floors (~18-19ms) and transfer\n    34→   bidirectionally with <7% E2E error. codellama-34b transfers reasonably\n    35→   to/from large models (20-28%).\n    36→\n    37→2. **Small models are untransferable.** llama-2-7b has fundamentally different\n    38→   batch dynamics (avg batch size 12 vs 33-46) and a much smaller overhead\n    39→   floor (9.7ms vs 14-19ms). No donor achieves <80% E2E error on 7B.\n    40→\n    41→3. **The overhead floor drives transferability.** Models with similar overhead\n    42→   floors (beta0) transfer well; models with different floors do not. This is\n    43→   because beta0 dominates the step time prediction (92-98% of total).\n    44→\n    45→4. **ITL transfer is even worse** (158.1% mean) because ITL error is structural\n    46→   and model-independent -- it reflects the fundamental BLIS vs lifecycle\n    47→   measurement gap.\n    48→\n    49→## Comparison to R3\n    50→\n    51→| Metric | R3 LOMO | H3 (this) |\n    52→|--------|---------|-----------|\n    53→| Mean best-donor E2E | 14.8% | 30.7% |\n    54→\n    55→R3's CMA-ES-based LOMO performed better (14.8%) because CMA-ES was E2E-optimized\n    56→without the overhead floor constraint. The direct calibration approach produces\n    57→per-model coefficients that are too model-specific to transfer.\n    58→\n    59→## Implications\n    60→\n    61→The poor LOMO result indicates that the direct calibration approach is inherently\n    62→model-specific. The overhead floor (beta0) must be calibrated per model, which\n    63→limits zero-shot generalization. For new models without E2E ground truth, the\n    64→approach cannot be used directly -- a model size heuristic (e.g., beta0 scaling\n    65→with parameter count) would be needed.\n    66→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e652145f-d03b-4eb5-bbf8-d7db257fe10a","uuid":"81d973df-155f-41ea-9635-6ef9e2068ea6","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/dipanwitaguhathakurta/Downloads/inference-sim-package/stepml-worktrees/round4-idea-3-hybrid-calibration/hypotheses/h-stepml/round4/idea-3-hybrid-calibration/h3-lomo/FINDINGS.md","content":"# H3: Leave-One-Model-Out (LOMO) Cross-Validation\n\n**Status:** REFUTED (mean best-donor E2E 30.7% > target 20%)\n\n## Key Numbers\n\n| Metric | Result | Target | Verdict |\n|--------|--------|--------|---------|\n| Mean best-donor E2E | 30.7% | <20% | FAIL |\n| Mean best-donor ITL | 158.1% | <30% | FAIL |\n\n## Method\n\nFor each of 4 normalized models, train the direct calibration (H1 approach)\non the remaining 3 models' data, then evaluate each donor model's coefficients\non the held-out model's experiments. Report the best donor per fold.\n\n## LOMO Transfer Matrix (E2E %)\n\n| Holdout \\ Donor | codellama-34b | llama-2-70b | llama-2-7b | mixtral-8x7b |\n|-----------------|---------------|-------------|------------|--------------|\n| codellama-34b | - | 31.1 | 33.3 | **28.5** |\n| llama-2-70b | 20.4 | - | 47.0 | **6.7** |\n| llama-2-7b | **82.9** | 137.3 | - | 137.6 |\n| mixtral-8x7b | 20.2 | **4.5** | 46.8 | - |\n\nBest donors: mixtral for codellama (28.5%), mixtral for 70b (6.7%),\ncodellama for 7b (82.9%), 70b for mixtral (4.5%).\n\n## Key Findings\n\n1. **Large models transfer well to each other.** llama-2-70b and\n   mixtral-8x7b-v0-1 have similar overhead floors (~18-19ms) and transfer\n   bidirectionally with <7% E2E error. codellama-34b transfers reasonably\n   to/from large models (20-28%).\n\n2. **Small models are untransferable.** llama-2-7b has fundamentally different\n   batch dynamics (avg batch size 12 vs 33-46) and a much smaller overhead\n   floor (9.7ms vs 14-19ms). No donor achieves <80% E2E error on 7B.\n\n3. **The overhead floor drives transferability.** Models with similar overhead\n   floors (beta0) transfer well; models with different floors do not. This is\n   because beta0 dominates the step time prediction (92-98% of total).\n\n4. **ITL transfer is even worse** (158.1% mean) because ITL error is structural\n   and model-independent -- it reflects the fundamental BLIS vs lifecycle\n   measurement gap.\n\n## Comparison to R3\n\n| Metric | R3 LOMO | H3 (this) |\n|--------|---------|-----------|\n| Mean best-donor E2E | 14.8% | 30.7% |\n\nR3's CMA-ES-based LOMO performed better (14.8%) because CMA-ES was E2E-optimized\nwithout the overhead floor constraint. The direct calibration approach produces\nper-model coefficients that are too model-specific to transfer.\n\n## Implications\n\nThe poor LOMO result indicates that the direct calibration approach is inherently\nmodel-specific. The overhead floor (beta0) must be calibrated per model, which\nlimits zero-shot generalization. For new models without E2E ground truth, the\napproach cannot be used directly -- a model size heuristic (e.g., beta0 scaling\nwith parameter count) would be needed.\n","numLines":66,"startLine":1,"totalLines":66}}}
